<HEAD>
<TITLE>DOJ Study Says Gang Crimes Worse</TITLE>
<!-- Comment Here -->
</HEAD>
<BODY>
Excerpted from EmergencyNet NEWS Service
<BR>
Saturday, June 22, 1996
<BR>
Vol. 2 - 174
<P>
<B>**LEAD STORY**</B>
<P>

<H2>NATIONWIDE SURVEY SHOWS GANG PROBLEMS GETTING WORSE</H2>
By Steve Macko, ENN Editor
<P>

The United States Justice Department on Thursday released
preliminary findings of a nationwide survey on street gangs.
The survey found that gang problems were worsening in about
50 percent of the communities that responded.  Only ten
percent of the responding communities reported some improvement
in their gang problems.
<P>

This survey that was conducted by The National Youth Gang Center
(NYGC), under the direction of the DOJ's Office of Juvenile
Justice and Delinquency Prevention, sent the survey to more
than 4,200 police and sheriff's departments in December of
1995.  81 percent or 3,447 of the agencies responded to
the survey.  1,974 said that they had youth gang activity in
their cities or counties.  This was said to be the first large-
scale survey, of its kind, that included both urban and rural
communities.
<P>

Only 210 of the respondents said that gang activity was decreasing
in their jurisdictions.  The rest said that the problem was
staying the same or was getting worse.
<P>

This was only a preliminary report that was put out by the NYGC.
In the coming months, the survey will be expanded to cover more
police and sheriff's departments, schools and social service
agencies.  The report will also examine gang trends in specific
cities and counties.  The final report will be published in the
summer of 1997.
<P>

U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno was supposed to announce these
preliminary findings at an anti-gang conference in Dallas, Texas.
She was unable to attend because of other pressing business in
Washington.  In remarks prepared for The National Youth Gang
Symposium, Reno said that law enforecement is "committed to putting
these gangs out of business -- with a tough, smart mix of prosecutions,
police, aid to communities and common-sense programs to invest in
young people before they take the wrong path.  And we will support
community innovations like school uniforms, curfews and truancy
prevention."
<P>

It was reported that more than 600 law enforcement professionals,
prosecutors, researchers, educators and youth service providers
attended the Dallas conference.
<P>
(c) EmergencyNet News Service, 1996, All Rights Reserved.
<P>
