<HEAD>
<TITLE>Boston Firefighters Have Busy Holiday</TITLE>
<!-- Comment Here -->
</HEAD>
<BODY>
For Immediate Release: 12/26/95-14:00CST
<BR>
<H3>FIREFIGHTERS WORK EXTRA HARD ON CHRISTMAS...</H3>
By Steve Macko
<P>
Members of the Boston Fire Department rescued 15 people from a
6 Alarm fire on Box 514 at 1170 Commonwealth Avenue in the city's
Brighton Section, during the early hours of Christmas Day.  Heavy
smoke conditions were reported in the 3-story brick 9-flat apartment
building with dimensions of 75x100.
<P>
Residents of the building were forced to flee to rear porches and
fire escapes because the smoke was so thick in the building's corridors.
A Boston Fire Department spokesman said, "You litterally couldn't see
your hand in front of your face."  When firefighters arrived at about
0435 EST, they found several people shouting for help from the upper
floors in the rear of the fire building.  The alley, behind the building,
was blocked by parked cars, so firefighters could not move the apparatus
close enough to help affect rescues.  But the Boston Fire Department
is world reknown for their ladder work.  BFD members grabbed ground
ladders and rescued all of the trapped residents.
<P>

Six firefighters were injured in this spectacular blaze.  The worst
injuries came to Firefighter John Steiner, a 6-year veteran.  Steiner,
while affecting rescues, fell from a second floor window.  He was
transported to Masschusetts General Hospital by EMS with a collapsed
lung, a compound fracture to his elbow, a broken wrist and possible rib 
injuries.  Five other firefighters suffered minor injuries ranging
from smoke inhalation and burns to a pulled back muscle.
<P>

Boston Fire Commissioner Martin Pierce praised his men for their
efforts.  Pierce said that they did "an outstanding job under very
tough conditions."
<P>
<HR>
<B>Related Stories:</B>

Other victims involved in fires in other parts of the United States
were not as lucky as the people in Boston, on Christmas Day.  In
Portland, Oregon, fire swept through a wood frame dwelling and
killed two people, a mother and her teenage son.  Seven other people
in the home were injured.  Cause of the blaze is still under investigation.
<P>

A 3rd Alarm on Box 1484 at 807 43rd Street in Brooklyn, New York,
killed a 75-year-old man and his 69-year-old wife.  Fire was in a
3-story brick rowhouse 20x80.  Heavy smoke conditions were reported
by FDNY personnel when they arrived at about 0225 EST.
<P>
(c) Emergency Response & Research Institute, All rights reserved.
<BR>
