<HEAD>
<TITLE>Pennsylvania Flooding Disaster/Fire</TITLE>
<!-- Comment Here -->
</HEAD>
<BODY>
EmergencyNet News: 01/22/96-14:00CST
<BR>
<B>Pennsylvania...</B>

<H2>Firefighters in Pennsylvania Fight Both Fire and Ice </H2>

Four homes were destroyed and three others were damaged in a
4 Alarm fire in a flooded area in Harrisburg, Pennsylvania, on 
Monday morning.  The area had been evacuated over the weekend 
because the Susquehanna River had flooded on Saturday evening. 
<P>
Pennsylvania had been declared a federal disaster area
following a January seventh blizzard that dumped up to 32 inches
of snow on the state. A warming trend then turned the snow into raging streams and rivers.  State Governor Tom Ridge says the flooding caused widespread
damage in the western part of his state including the cities of Pittsburgh and Harrisburg.

Firefighters had to wade through the hip-deep, icy water to reach
the scene of the fire near the intersection of Front and Cannois. 
The mayor of Harrisburg said, "We've lost most of the whole side 
of one street.  It's nearly impossible to access, let alone fight 
a fire in that condition."
<P>

Front-end loaders were brought in to clear snow and ice so fire
apparatus could attempt to get closer to the scene of the blaze.
Firefighters were still hampered by four-feet of water in the
street.  Two firefighters were treated for hypothermia.
<P>

The fire started at about 0300 EST and took firefighters about
four hours to bring under control.  It is believed that the blaze
was caused by a short in an electrical box that was not turned off
at the time of the evacuation.
<P>
