<img src="fn099401.gif" align=right>
<h3>Fire News From Around the World 09/94<BR>
</H3>
Dateline; Chicago, IL, September 9, 1200CDT <P>
August 22, 1994<P>
<h3>Complex Series of Factors Cause Deaths of 14 Firefighters<P>
</H3>An investigation prepared by the U. S. Forest Service and the U.S. Bureau of Land management has found that the deaths of fourteen (14) firefighters in a Colorado wildfire were largely due to &quot;human error&quot;.  The report concluded that the tragic deaths of a team of elite &quot;smokejumpers&quot; and &quot;hotshots&quot; was due to a combination of preventable circumstances and &quot;breakdowns in communications&quot;, said Mike Dombeck, acting director of the Bureau of Land Management.  According to Dombeck, &quot;The fire behavior on July 6 could have been predicted on the basis of fuels, weather, and topography...but fire behavior information was not requested (by the firefighters) or provided...therefore critical information was not available for developing strategy or tactics.&quot;<P>
According to other witnesses, the veteran firefighters also made a number of tactical errors that contributed to their deaths.  These errors reportedly included constructing a fire line downhill, when the fire was below them, and inadequate planning of escape routes.  Among other lapses included in the report were; failures to alert the on-scene firefighters of a change in the weather, violations of eight (8) of ten (10) standard wildfire operating procedures, disregard of twelve (12) of the eighteen firefighter &quot;Watch Out&quot; situations, and a failure to alert the crews to the presence of a highly flammable type of tree on the hillside (Gambel Oak).<P>
Firefighters that lived through the ordeal, described fire conditions at the South Canyon fire as being &quot;horrendous&quot;.  One eyewitness said, &quot;The fire literally exploded behind the ridge...with 100 foot flame heights...at this point I decided to run...as I neared the top of the ridge a wall of flame 150 ft. high and a quarter of a mile wide was on the ridgetop and racing down the other side.&quot;<P>
The investigation revealed that the fatal injuries to the firefighters were caused as a wind-driven wall of flames came over a ridge and down the other side, while a separate firestorm was ascending the same hillside.  The fallen firefighters were caught in the middle, with few places to escape.  Controversy swirled, during the investigation, around the issue of whether or not the stricken firefighters used personal fire protection shelters, but experienced investigators admit that they probably would have made little difference, considering the fire conditions.<P>
According to Forest Service veterans, the all of the firefighters involved in the fatal accident were not &quot;rookies&quot; and many of them had fought numerous fires.  They say that it is possible that they disregarded some basic safety rules out of &quot;sheer fatigue&quot;, and/or &quot;familiarity on the fireground&quot; or nonchalance; after all, they had done this dozens of times and nothing bad had happened.  They said that this fire could result in some changes in procedures, but that the important point was that every firefighter, rookie or veteran, had to pay close attention to basic safety procedures.<P>
August 4, 1994<P>
<h3>Senior Australian Fire Brigade Official &quot;Seconded&quot; to Commercial Firm <P>
</H3>In an unprecedented move, a senior Melbourne Metropolitan Fire Brigade (MMFB) officer has been seconded to work for Knight, Frank, &amp; Hooker, a prominent commercial property management and real estate sales firm.  According to Emergency Services Minister Pat McNamara, this is a &quot;landmark&quot; deal that will provide an undisclosed amount of money (believed to be several hundred thousand dollars) for the Melbourne Fire Brigade, in exchange for a experienced fire officer to provide the firm with fire safety audits, to develop fire emergency procedures, and assist with fire safety training for building occupants.<P>
McNamara was quoted by the Australian Associated Press as saying, &quot;For the first time the MMFB will step into the commercial arena to market its first class services as an expert on fire and building safety.&quot;  McNamara also said that this was a &quot;prime example&quot; of the government's recent policy of marketing public sector &quot;specialists&quot; to the private sector.  The money paid for the fire officer's service on the Knight, Frank, &amp; Hooker board will reportedly be used to offset expenses of the MMFB.<P>
A spokesperson for the real estate firm, John Hull, was quoted as saying that this move might be used as a model to set up similar commercial arrangements in other Australian states.<P>
August 18, 1994<P>
<h3>NFPA says Home Escape Plans Could Save Lives  <P>
</H3>Quoting American fire safety statistics, the National Fire Protection Association (NFPA) today announced that many more lives could be saved if families had a fire escape plan.  NFPA experts pointed to the fact that 78% of all fire deaths, that have occurred in the home, have happened when people are normally sleeping, between 02:00 a.m. and 04:00 a.m.  They say that many fire deaths occur because people aren't warned of a fire early enough, or that they become disoriented in the smoke and are unable to escape it.  The NFPA report says that these problems could be solved by some simple measures, such as installing a working smoke detector, carbon monoxide detector, and practicing home fire evacuation plans.<P>
Fire prevention specialists report that most fire death victims never see flames, that they are overcome by poisonous carbon monoxide fumes.  The NFPA urged families to contact their local fire department in order to help to plan their family fire safety strategy.  Some basic components of an effective plan might include:<P>
1. Install smoke detectors on every level of the home. keep them         clean and dust free. Check and change the batteries on a              scheduled basis.<P>
2. With your children, draw a floor plan of every level of your          home. Designate fire exits, including one for each bedroom.           Also designate a safe meeting place, outside the home, where          family members should meet in the case of emergency.<P>
3. After preparing the diagram, have all family members                  (especially children) practice actually escaping from the             home.  Everyone should practice crawling to the nearest safe          exit, if that is safely possible. <P>
4. Children should practice touching and opening doors to see if          they are &quot;hot&quot; and how to recognize the need to use another            exit                     <P>
5. If they are unable to exit from the door to their room they           should learn how to open windows and wave a sheet or piece of         clothing to gain attention of arriving firefighters.<P>
6. Every family should have a multi-rated fire-extinguisher and          know how to use it on small or smoldering fires.<P>
7. Warn children to NEVER hide from a fire, and to automatically         go to a firefighter or police officer, should they be                 separated from their family during an emergency.<P>
Fire prevention educators say that many more lives could be saved, if parents and children would take a little time to plan for emergencies and to actually practice these fire safe behaviors.<P>
September 9, 1994<P>
<h3>British Columbia Officials Declare &quot;Environmental Emergency&quot;<P>
</H3>The provincial government of British Columbia today declared an &quot;Environmental Emergency&quot; condition in regard to the discovery of several barrels of what are believed to be toxic materials.  The barrels were found at the Rainy-Hallow site, which is adjacent to the Tatshenshini-Alesk Wilderness Park.  The site is very near to one of the largest Bald Eagle refuge areas on the North American Continent.<P>
According to B.C. Environmental Minister Moe Sihota, he has dispatched a clean-up and containment team to the area.  Sihota is quoted by the Reuters News service as saying; &quot;Cleaning up these dangerous toxics and protecting the area from further contamination is our top priority.&quot;   The minister also criticized the U.S. government and military for their alleged involvement in the original dumping of the barrels into the wilderness area.  Reportedly, the U.S. has denied the dumping the barrels of potentially deadly DDT and Dioxins at an oil pumping site for the Alaskan Pipeline.  A U.S. government spokesperson said that the military had not occupied the site since 1974, and had no knowledge of the toxic dump described by Canadian officials.<P>
B.C. government officials said that they had been tipped off about the &quot;environmental emergency&quot; by a little-known group called the &quot;Alaska Clear Water Alliance&quot;.  The government spokesperson said that the alliance had actually found only one barrel of DDT (Pesticide), but feared that many more would be found in the area.  Additional fears were expressed that the barrels would leach into ground water and leak into the Khehini River and contaminate Eagle breeding grounds in nearby areas.<P>
August 14, 1994<P>
<h3>Australian Volunteer Firefighters Call for&quot;Standardization&quot; <P>
</H3>At the 12th Annual Australian Assembly of Volunteer Fire Brigade Associations, representatives of over 280,000 Australian volunteer firefighters called for sweeping changes in both fire brigade equipment and procedures. The meeting, held in Hobart, Australia, reportedly reviewed the performance of volunteer and professional firefighters, in regard to major fires that occurred in New South Wales earlier this year.  As the result of this review, several recommendations were to be sent to national fire authorities for consideration.<P>
One of the major problems, found by the volunteers, was that the various fire brigades were divided into municipal and metropolitan subdivisions and that they could not effectively interface, should that be necessary in the event of large disaster such as the New South Wales (NSW) fires.  A spokesperson for the organization said that there was no common radio frequency which allowed the various departments to talk to each other.  He said that in one instance, if firefighters used their normal radio frequencies that they would have been talking to &quot;the local taxi service&quot;.  Further, he said that fire companies operating at the same scene, and in line of sight, couldn't talk between themselves to coordinate tactics.  One firefighter commented that, at the NSW fires, that the use of a cellular phone was probably the most effective communications tool, but that the cellular frequencies were always busy during the fire.<P>
There was also discussion, at the meeting, regarding the compatibility of hoses, hydrants, and pumpers and the fact that they all didn't have the necessary threading and sizes to allow them to interoperate. The volunteer firefighters expressed their concerns that this incompatibility could lead to injury and possibly even death, should fire apparatus from differing jurisdictions need to quickly work together to provide water to attacking firefighters.<P>
The results of the volunteers recommendations were gathered into a comprehensive report and were to be forwarded to the Australian Fire Authority Council in Melbourne.<P>
September 9, 1994<P>
<h3>Hong Kong Firefighters Search For Survivors in Building Collapse<P>
</H3>Five people were killed and several others injured when a building suddenly collapsed on a busy street in downtown Hong Kong. The building, which was being demolished by a construction crew, reportedly failed, sending tons of concrete and debris onto  unsuspecting passerbys here on Friday.  According to eyewitnesses, the front of the Wing On department store crashed through an overhead protective barrier and buried the victims.  <P>
Hong Kong Fire Brigade members were called to scene and were using overhead cranes and other heavy lift equipment to remove massive concrete boulders from the stricken.  Fire trucks and ambulances were seen screaming down the busy and crowded Nathan Road, where the collapse had occurred. At least four people were successfully rescued from the rubble and transported alive to area hospitals.  Five bodies, two woman and three men, were recovered from the debris and declared dead at the scene.<P>
Building department officials cordoned off the area out of fears of additional collapse. Three sides of the building remained standing, although unstable and potentially hazardous.  The cause of the collapse is unknown at the time of this report, but government officials promised a thorough investigation.<P>
September 7, 1994<P>
<h3>Moscow Police Station Explodes; Six Killed,  Dozens Injured <P>
</H3>At least three explosions rippled through a Moscow police station on Wednesday, with sections of the station collapsing following the blasts. The Emergencies Ministry, at first, announced the deaths of ten (10) people, but later accounts revised the death toll downward.  The police station was located in the Eastern district of Vykhino, and had received no prior warning of any sort of danger.<P>
According to eyewitness reports, Moscow firefighters were on the scene for many hours sifting through the rubble and performing rescues.  A report from the Itar-Tass news agency said that many people were buried and they were being dug from the debris by hand.  Sounds of entombed people were said to be heard for several hours into the rescue effort, and several of those found were said to have suffered critical injuries. Dozens were thought to have been transported to several area hospitals. <P>
The cause of the explosions, thought to be three in number, was immediately unknown, although speculation of a terrorist or &quot;gangster&quot; bombing was heard from several sources.  The Tass agency said that the first explosion was thought to have exploded in an area of the building where internal travel papers were processed.  Police said that an area-wide investigation would be conducted and that &quot;the strictest measures would be taken against those involved in this outrage&quot;, should they be caught.<P>
