<TITLE>Phoenix Police and Gang Crackdown</TITLE>
<!-- Comment Here -->
</HEAD>
<BODY>
EmergencyNet News: 03/16/96
<BR>
<B>Phoenix...</B>
<P>
<H2>Phoenix Task Force Undertakes Gang Crackdown</H2>
By Steve Macko, ENN Editor
<P>

Authorities in Phoenix, Arizona, announced a massive crackdown
on some of the largest and most violent street gangs.  More
than 100 suspects were targeted during a two-day sweep that
happened on Thursday and Friday (Mar 14-15th, 1996).  More than 150 
law enforcement officers arrested about 70 adults and juveniles who 
are said to be members of about six Phoenix-area street gangs.
Most of the suspects were arrested for illegal selling of weapons
and stolen vehicles.  One south Phoenix gang was heavily targeted
by the task force -- the Wetback street gang.
<P>

Officers during the raids recovered about $1.4 million in stolen
property and guns.  A source told ENN that the vast quantity of  
weapons that were seized were sawed-off, single-shot shotguns.
This sweep was said to probably be the largest of its kind in the 
history of the Phoenix metropolitan area.  The suspects arrested 
will face various charges, including federal firearm violations.
<P>

Bruce Gebhardt, the Special-Agent-In-Charge of the FBI's Phoenix
field office said that the raids was meant to send a message,
most of all, to the Wetback gang.  Gebhardt said, "The message is
that this is a highly professional and motivated task force.  It
has the capability to investigate, infiltrate, arrest and prosecute
you for your criminal activities."
<P>

This operation was said to be a part of an on-going strategy that
is patterned to the same kind of successful strategy that the FBI 
uses against organized crime syndicates.  The crimes committed by
members of organized street gangs are treated as a single criminal
enterprise rather than unconnected, individual crimes committed by
gangbangers.  If convicted of running a criminal enterprise,
defendants can look forward to a life sentence in prison.
<P>
(c) EmergencyNet News Service, 1996, All Rights Reserved.
<P>
