<TITLE>FBI Critical Incident Response Group</TITLE>
<!-- Comment Here -->
</HEAD>
<BODY>
Excerpted from; EmergencyNet NEWS Service (ENNFAX)
<BR>
Monday, April 22, 1996
<BR>
Vol. 2 - 113
<P>
<B>**LEAD STORY**</B>
<P>
<IMG ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="/FBI2.GIF">
<H2>THE FBI'S CRITICAL INCIDENT RESPONSE GROUP...</H2>
By Steve Macko, ENN Managing Editor
<P>

The town of Jordan, Montana, is located in Garfield County.
Garfield County is so vast that it is almost the size of
the entire state of Connecticut.  Currently, there are
about 150 agents of the Federal Bureau of Investigation,
Garfield County Sheriff's deputies and members of the
Montana Highway Patrol conducting "loose" perimeter patrols
around a 960-acre property that is known as "Justus Township."
<P>

"Justus Township" is not an officially recognized governmental
body, but it is home of the militant group known as the "Freemen."
The law enforcement officers outside of the property are working
very hard to ensure that this situation doesn't explode into
another bloody Waco or Ruby Ridge. 
<P> 

The potential for a bloody conflict is very high.  The Freemen
are known to be well armed.  So the FBI works to negotiate a
peaceful end to this standoff.  How long will it take?  No one
knows.
<P>

What is known is that FBI officials are prepared for a long
siege.  The thing that is most noticeable with the FBI agents
is ... patience.  They are equipped with everything that they
may need -- M-16 rifles, body armor, sidearms.  But they know
that the thing that need most, in this situation, is ... patience.
<P>

Clint Van Zandt is a former FBI behavior expert.  Van Zandt said
that the effort to decrease the chances of an armed clash "is
really the first outing" of the Bureau's new approach to crisis
management.
<P>

Handling the Freemen siege is the FBI's new Critical Incident
Response Group.  This team brings in all of the FBI's crisis
units.  The Hostage Rescue Team, additional FBI SWAT personnel,
hostage negotiators, behavorial scientists and other specialists.
This team has set up shop in what is being called a high-tech
command post.
<P>

The Critical Incident Response Group was created in 1994 and is
headed by 25-year FBI veteran Robin Montgomery.  Specialists
who monitor the FBI say that Montgomery has taken an expansive
view of his role and has been known to consult outside sources
to seek the answers that he needs to help resolve a situation. Many say this is a rational approach that may prove beneficial in the future.
<P>

The acknowledged mistakes made at Waco and Ruby Ridge led to
the creation of the FBI's new unit.  The idea, of course, is
to not repeat those past mistakes.  An assessment of the Waco
and Ruby Ridge incidents revealed that there were problems with
the FBI's command structure and specific management strategies of hostage/barricade
situations.
<P>

Some examples of past mistakes, that have now been corrected,
are: At Ruby Ridge, the operations plan of the FBI did not
include any negotiations and the FBI's chief negotiator was
not invited into discussions on strategy.  A U.S. Justice 
Department review found "much evidence that a negotiation 
strategy was not the highest priority."
<P>

At Waco, a report written by Harvard law professor Alan Stone,
found that "negotiators and tactical units were at times
operating independently in an uncoordinated and counterproductive
fashion." Independent experts suggest that a more "integrated approach", 
utilizing all available resources in concert, seems a more productive approach.
<P>

However, when it comes to the way that the FBI is handling
the Freemen situation, everyone, including past critics such as
Professor Stone, are giving the FBI "high marks." Clint Van Zandt explains, "You've got a lot of senior commanders now who fully understand the prior mistakes."
<P>
The situation in Jordan, Montana, continues.
<P>
(c) EmergencyNet News Service, 1996, All Rights Reserved.
<P>
