<HEAD>
<TITLE>Egyptian Fire -Worst Since 1942</TITLE>
<!-- Comment Here -->
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<BR>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE: 10:30CST
<P>
<H3>Egypt Fire Disaster Worst Since 1942</H3>
<BR>

Chicago, IL, November 3, 1994 -- In what is being described as the
worst fire disaster in more than half a century, 475 people are
believed dead in a freak flood/fire in Assiut Province, Egypt.
According to official sources, a train carrying fuel oil to a
military petroleum supply depot derailed in the midst of the
worst rainstorm in Egypt in sixty (60) years. Downed electrical
wires then ignited the viscous fuel and it floated on the flood
waters and spread through the Village of Dronka.  As if that
weren't bad enough, lightening then struck a fuel tank in the
depot and it also burst into flames. Two hundred and fifty eight
people reportedly perished in the initial "lava flow of fire" or
in a number of fires then caused by it.
<P>

At the time of this report, fires are still reportedly burning
out of control in several areas in Southern Egypt. Firefighters
and military troops dispatched to assist them are said to be
"overwhelmed" by this latest challenge. Fire officials say that
numerous buildings were ignited by the "burning flood" and that
they are still recovering bodies, more than twenty-four (24)
hours after the start of the tragic incident. Firefighters said
that the death toll is expected to rise as they continue to
search through the ruins of what was once a village of 22,000
people. More than 200 homes are known to have been completely
destroyed, either by fire or the deluge of rain. Many of the
residents have reportedly fled the scene, fearing that
"Judgement Day" had come.
<P> 

Samih el Saeed, Governor of Assiut Province, said that more than
two hundred (200) people were injured and that more than seventy
(70) had suffered extensive burns. He also said that more than
35 people were known to have drowned in other parts of the
province.  A local hospital spokesperson said that many of the
burn patients brought there are unexpected to live, because of
the severity of their injuries.  Medical supplies and personnel
are reported to be responding to the scene from Cairo, more than
200 miles (320km) to the North.  Another eighteen (18) bodies
were discovered early Thursday morning in the burnt out wreck
that was once an apartment building. Injuries and deaths are
also reported in Sohag and Qena provinces, but exact numbers are
difficult to obtain from the more remote areas of the Southern
desert.
<P>

Fire experts say that this unusual fire/flood combination and
its estimated 475 deaths exceeds the largest loss of life since
the infamous Coconut Grove fire in Boston, MA that occurred in
1942. Four hundred and ninety two (492) people lost their lives
in that blaze.
<P>

(C) EmergencyNet News Service, Emergency Response & Research 
     Institute, 1994. All rights reserved.
<P>
