<HEAD>
<TITLE>Fire/Hostage Incident in Harlem</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE:13:00CST
<BR>
<H3> HATE CRIME SIEGE IN HARLEM?? </H3>
<B>At Least Eight Dead Injured In Shoot-out and Blaze Caused by Gunman
</B><P>
By James J. Fay-ENN NY/NJ Metro Correspondent
<BR>
New York, NY., December 9, 1995 -- A hostage incident and 3
alarm blaze at 272 West 125 St. in the Harlem section of
Manhattan, NYC, has resulted in the deaths of eight people. Six
others were reported injured, four from gunshot wounds.
<P>
At approximately 1000 hrs. EST, NYC Police were notified of a
"man with a gun" call for an individual who was reportedly
brandishing a gun in the vicinity of West 125 St. and Fifth Ave.
A man was identified by officers and a foot pursuit ensued.
<P> 
During the brief chase, shots were fired by the wanted person.
Concerns were raised on the radio by officers for Christmas
shoppers in the area of the heavily traveled commercial strip.
Police pursued the perpetrator into a store at 272 West 125 St.,
a men's clothing store, opposite the landmark Apollo Theater.
The area of the store had been the scene of several civil rights
demonstrations in the past two weeks.
<P> 
Shots continued to be fired from the store at the officers, and
one officer was reportedly trapped by gunfire emulating from the
store.  NYPD Emergency Service Units responded from Manhattan,
the Bronx and Brooklyn, upon reports from patrol units of the
shots being fired, with hostages inside the store. Initial
reports of at least 10 customers being held hostage were given
to police at the time of the takeover.
<P>
Police and SWAT members closed off the area in front of and
across the street  for both uniformed and plainclothes officers,
as well as the press, and designated the area as a "Heavy Vest"
area, due to the continued possibility of shots being fired.
<P>
The alleged perpetrator, still in the store, then pulled the
steel security gate down in the front of the store, and then
presumably set the store on fire. The FDNY was ordered by NYPD
to respond to the corner of W. 125 St. and Eighth Ave. and
advised that there were still shots being fired.  Upon arrival,
the first FD units transmitted a "10-75," with the 16th
Battalion immediately reporting an "All Hands" fire.
<P>
Due to the potential threat to firefighters, the initial attack
on the fire was to the 2nd floor of the 2 story, 100x100
commercial building, that was under renovation. Several fire
hoses were stretched to the front of the store, in an attempt to
extinguish the fire from the street, without actually entering
the building.  The fire continued to grow and eventually reached
a 3rd Alarm, with additional units called in to assist in the
eventual search. When the fire was finally brought under
control, NYPD Emergency Service Units and NYC's SWAT teams
entered the store, that was still smoldering, to search for the
gunman and his hostages. Once inside,  they made a gruesome
discovery...several bodies.
<P>
David Bookstaver, official NYC*EMS spokesman, told ENN that EMS
initially found and treated four people for gunshot wounds from
the original gunshots that had initiated the siege. In addition,
at least two NYPD Police Officers were removed to the hospital
due to the psychological trauma of the shootout.  Four
firefighters were also reportedly slightly injured in the rescue
effort. At approximately 1125 Hrs, EST, EMS reported four DOA's
as a result of the fire, with a total of at least four other
civilian injuries, all due to gunshot wounds.
<P>
By 1230 Hrs. the FDNY reported three additional DOA's (10-45
code 1),and at 1235 hrs.EST one additional DOA as a result of
the fire that engulfed the store. This brought to eight (8) the
total of victims. An NYC*EMS Captain, from the scene, told ENN 
that he believed that all eight deaths were as the result of
smoke inhalation, but that at least one victim may have suffered
severe smoke inhalation and burns and may not survive.
<P>
Speculation surrounding the motivation for the hostage taking
and fire is centering on the fact that civil rights
demonstrations have been, held in recent weeks, near the store.
According to at least one unconfirmed report, the gunman may
have participated in these previous demonstrations. Reportedly,
there had been plans by the building management to evict a black
record store from the same building. The building is managed by
a white Jewish man. Purportedly, threats to burn and loot the
clothing store had been previously made by an African American
man. A major "hate crime" investigation continues at this at the
time of this report.
<P>
                             -30-
<BR>
