<HEAD>
<TITLE>Illinois School Fire Safety</TITLE>
<!-- Comment Here -->
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<BR>
<P>
Illinois...ENNFAX Report from 11/09/95
<P>
By Steve Macko
<P>
<H3>Illinois School Fire Safety Suffers?</H3>
<P>
Considerable opposition is being placed against a state of Illinois
House Bill that will reduce the level of fire safety required in two
Illinois school districts -- one in Kankakee and another in the
southwest Chicago suburb of Lemont.  The Office of the State Fire
Marshal, the Illinois Fire Chiefs Association, the Illinois Fire
Inspectors Association and the Illinois Fire Protection Districts
Association all oppose House Bill 854 that will allow the school 
districts to bypass a law that requires installing fire sprinkler 
systems into any new construction or any renovated construction that 
is over fifty percent of total current square footage.
<P>

Tom O'Connell, a retired 31-year member of the Chicago Fire Department
said, "It is outrageous that the safety of Illinois school children be
compromised to satisfy the self-serving, political whims of two school
districts."  Fire safety in Chicago and Illinois schools came to the
forefront in 1958 with the infamous Our Lady of Angels school fire
in Chicago that killed 96 children and three nuns.  After this fire,  
much more strigent fire codes, in regards to school buildings was
put into effect in almost every community in the United States.
According to O'Connell the requested exemptions by the two school 
districts goes against common sense.
<P>

Fires in schools are not uncommon in the United States.  The National
Fire Protection Association said that there are an average of 8,200
school fires every year in the United States.  An average of 190
children are killed or injured, every year, in these fires.
<P>
(c) Emergency Response & Research Institute, 1995, All rights reserved.
<P>
