<BR>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE-EMERGENCYNET NEWS SVC.-11-15-95-1630CST
<BR>
<P>
<H3>HOLIDAY FIRE SAFETY TIPS ANNOUNCED</H3>
<P>
Chicago, IL.   Deadly fires occur every year at this time.
These fires take unecessary lives and cause tragedies at what
should be a joyous time of year. The dangers involved with
the holiday season should prompt an examination of everyone's 
home fire safety habits.
<P>  
According to Clark Staten of the Chicago based Emergency Response & Research
Institute, this concern is based on several blazes
that have taken lives in Chicago and elsewhere in the country.
Preliminary indications show that at least one of the major causes
of these fatal fires are faulty electrical extension cords. Something that could be easily avoided.
<P>

"During the holiday season, we seem to put an increased
electrical load on our sometimes already overburdened
circuits", Staten said.  "The possible result of overloading
cicuits are tragedies that occur with amazing frequency at this time of year",
the veteran paramedic added.  "Unfortunately, many people
forget to individually check their light strands and
extension cords before installing them on a Christmas tree or
in windows", he continued. "Christmas is a time to be
extremely conscious of fire safety... by doing so, we can all
have a happy and healthy New Year", Staten concluded.
<P>

According to the Emergency Response & Research Institute, the
following items should be checked when completing a home fire
safety checklist for the holiday season:
<P>
<HR>
<BR>
<H4>Electrical Dangers</H4>
<P>

1. Check all extension cords for "fraying", loose
   connections, or bent plugs
<P>

2. Check all light strands for "fraying" cords, loose bulbs,
   broken or cracked sockets, and serviceable plugs
<P>

3. Do NOT exceed the manufacturer's (Underwriters Laboratory)
   recommendations for the number of strands of lights to be
   connected together
<P>

4. Do NOT use small diameter "light utility" extension cords
   for multiple electrical appliances/lighting devices
<P>

5. Do NOT use indoor rated extension cords or lights for
   outdoor displays
<P>

6. Do NOT disable or bypass grounded circuits (three prong
   outlets and plugs)
<P>

7. Do not "pinch" or "crimp" power cords when laying and
   hanging lights and displays
<P>

8. Insure that you are using the correct size circuit
   breaker or fuses for the circuit that will support your
   Christmas lights...do NOT place a larger fuse in the
   circuit if it repeatedly "blows"...reduce the number of
   lights/devices that are being used
<P>

9. If any cord, light set, or circuit, feels warm to the
   touch...DISCONNECT it IMMEDIATELY and check the entire
   connection for defects.
<P>
10. If in doubt about ANY electrical connection...DON'T use
    it...replace/fix it!
<P>
<BR>
<H4>Fire/Open Flames</H4>
<P>

1. DO NOT use an oven or stove burners for heating your house
   or apartment!  The money is far better spent on a well
   ventilated heating system
<P>

2. Use space heaters with extreme caution and AVOID any that
   use an open flame.  Insure that they are NEVER located
   near ANY combustible materials (i.e. curtains, chairs,
   bedding, etc.)
<P>

3. Use extreme caution when using candles for
   decoration...NEVER use them on or near a Christmas tree
<P>

4. Insure that you have a mesh grate around all fireplaces
   that contains the possible movement of sparks or ashes
<P>

5. Be extremely cautious when emptying ashtrays into
   trash/garbage cans...non-extinguished smoking materials
   can smolder for hours and then burst unexpectedly into
   flames many hours later
<P>

GIVE YOURSELF A GIFT THIS CHRISTMAS...
<P>

REPLACE THE BATTERY IN ALL SMOKE DETECTORS AND TEST THEM
PRIOR TO THE HOLIDAY SEASON!!  DON'T HAVE ONE ??
GET ONE AND USE IT!!  THE LIFE YOU SAVE MAY BE YOUR OWN !!
<P>
<HR>

