<HEAD>
<TITLE>EmergencyNet News--01/04/96</TITLE>
<!-- Comment Here -->
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<B>ENNnewsFAX</B>
<BR>
EmergencyNet NEWS Service
<BR>
Wednesday, January 3, 1996
<BR>
Vol.2 - 003
<BR>
<B>**LEAD STORY**</B>
<BR>
<H3>NORTHERN IRELAND VIOLENCE...</H3>
   ANDRE DE NESNER
<BR>
   LONDON
<P>

Four people have been killed in Belfast this month as violence
returns to the streets of Northern Ireland's largest city.
<P>

A previously unknown group calling itself Direct Action
Against Drugs has claimed responsibility for the killings. All of
the four men shot to death were Roman Catholics and police
believe the gunmen responsible for the attacks are linked to the
Irish Republican Army.
<P>

For nearly 16 months now, nationalist paramilitary groups,
such as the IRA, and their pro-British, or loyalist, counterparts
have been abiding by the terms of their respective cease-fires.
Many people in Northern Ireland believe this latest wave of
violence is not a breach of the cease-fires, but at the same time
they are concerned it might escalate.
<P>

David Ervine is a senior member of the small progressive
unionist party known to have close links to pro-British
paramilitary groups. He says while the latest killings have been
in Belfast's Roman Catholic areas people in his Protestant
constituency are very fearful: "People are very worried. People 
are really, really worried.  They think it is a windup to or a precursor 
if you like to something more serious and one hopes that that is not 
the case.  And one hopes that people on the other side and people 
like me are working as feverishly as they can behind the scenes to 
make sure that does not happen."
<P>

Belfast police say the killings are a sign the IRA may be
exercising its own brand of justice against suspected drug
dealers, while at the same time intimidating people in areas it
controls.
<P>

However Ken Maginnis, security spokesman for the moderate
Protestant Ulster Unionist party, believes the killings may lead
to something more ominous: "The more sinister reason for the 
killings is in preparation for the beginning of murder of people 
within the Protestant community and that will be done in the 
not too distant future, probably within the next month by the 
IRA killing a member of a Protestant loyalist organization and 
saying we killed this person because he was involved in drugs, 
but they really will expect the loyalist paramilitaries to retaliate."
<P>

Mr. Maginnis says if that does happen, he hopes the loyalist
paramilitaries will not retaliate.
<P>

However David Ervine, with close links to loyalist
paramilitaries, says these groups will have to show a great deal
of restraint not to respond: "My desire would be that if we had a 
scenario like that, that the loyalists would hold fast. I fear that 
they would hold fast for hours, I do not think I could hold it for days."
<P>

Many politicians have condemned the killings in Belfast.
However Sinn Fein, the political wing of the Irish Republican
Army, has not. Over the past few months, senior Sinn Fein
officials have warned of a possible return to violence by the IRA
if there is no movement in the Northern Ireland peace process.
<P>
:: Produced by INEWS ::
<HR>
<H3>**NATIONAL FIRE NEWS**</H3>
<B>Suburban Chicago Fire Activity...</B>
Fire on January 2:
<P>
NAPERVILLE, IL - Box Alarm fire at 1315 McDowell Road.  At about
1830 CST, fire was reported in one unit of a 2-story apartment
building 75x75.   Located in southwest DuPage County.
<P>
Incident on January 3:
<P>
NORTHLAKE FPD, IL - EMS 2nd Alarm on Box 299 for the Pin-In MVA at
Northbound I-294 at Mile Marker 36.  At least one victim was
extricated from a car and was transported in Code Red (Critical)
condition.  This was a five ambulance response.  Time of the 
alarm was 1156 CST.  Located in the western suburbs.
<P>

<B>FDNY Fire Activity For Today...</B>
<BR>
BROOKLYN, NY - 2nd Alarm on Box 1285 at 340 19th Street.  Heavy fire 
was reported throughout a 3-story brick dwelling 20x40.  Fire
reportedly did communicate to an exposure building.  Five lines
were used by firefighters.  Time of the alarm was 0940 EST.
<P>
<HR>
<B>Nationwide Fire Activity...</B>
<BR>
Fire on January 2:
<BR>
LAKEWOOD, CALIFORNIA - 3 Alarm fire at Candlewood and Lakewood Blvd.
Los Angeles County firefighters battled a blaze in 50x75 retail
store inside of a 500x75 strip mall.  Time of the alarm was at
about 2100 PST.
<P>

Fires on January 3:
<BR>

MILWAUKEE, WISCONSIN - Working Fire at 1563 South 13th Street.
Fire in an apartment building resulted in the death of two
children.  Time of the alarm was at about 0745 CST.
<P>
SAN ANTONIO, TEXAS - 2 Alarm fire at FM 3175 and Somerset Road.
At 0800 CST, a 2-story dwelling was reported to be fully involved.
<P>
<B>Indiana...</B>
<BR>
One person suffered minor injuries when an explosion and fire
erupted at a water purification plant in Whiting, Indiana, on
Tuesday.  The explosion happened across the road from the huge
Amoco Oil refinery, which is located in northwest Indiana, just
outside of Chicago.
<P>
The blast happened at about 1100 CST.  It is not known what caused
the explosion.  The 47-year-old victim suffered first- and second-
degree burns and was treated and released from St.Catherine's
Hospital in East Chicago.
<P>
<B>New Jersey...</B>
<BR>
1995 statistics for the Jersey City, New Jersey, Fire Department
were released on Tuesday.  10,932 total incidents were recorded
last year.  There were 37 two alarm fires, 11 three alarm and
two blazes went to the four alarm level.
<HR>
<H3>**NATIONAL LAW ENFORCEMENT NEWS**</H3>
<B>CPD Police Activity...</B>
<BR>
Police shooting on January 2:
<BR>
A 36-year-old woman was shot by a Chicago Police officer on
Tuesday night at a CHA housing project at 2910 South Dearborn
Street in the 21st Police District on Chicago's South Side.
Details of the incident are sketchy, but the woman is believed
to have lunged at the officer with a knife and was shot.
<P>
<B>NYPD Police Activity...</B>
<BR>
Homicide on January 1:
<BR>
QUEENS - The body of a 33-year-old male was found at 97th Place
and 57th Avenue in the 110th Precinct.  He had been shot once in 
the face.  NYPD detectives have few leads in the case.
<P>
<B>Alabama...</B>
<BR>
By Steve Macko
<BR>
An Episcopal priest was injured by an exploding package on Monday
in Opelika, Alabama, located about 60 miles east of Montgomery.
Federal agents from the United States Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco
and Firearms said that the device was a homemade bomb that was
made with murderous intent.
<P>

The priest survived the explosion by what one ATF Special Agent 
said as "sheer luck."  The priest walked into his carport and
found a box on the truck of his automobile.  When he picked the
box up, it exploded.  It is believed that the priest was not the
intended target of the device.  The bomb, most likely, was meant
for a retired ATF Special Agent that lives nearby.
<P>

ATF investigators said that the explosive device was a solid
explosive that was inside of a cardboard box with the word, "U-Haul"
printed on the side.  The device was designed to explode when the
box was moved or lifted.  The Special Agent-In-Charge of the
Birmingham ATF office said, "There's no question that bomb was put
there to kill someone.  It was a vicious device, an anti-personnel
device, designed to kill, designed to murder."  It is believed that
the device was loaded with nails.
<P>

The priest is reported to be in good condition at a local hospital.
Later, the ATF said that they believe that the bomb may have been
an act of anti-government violence.  A note was found near the
bomb and included these words: "Alabama to unite against the ATF
conspiracy."  The ATF is continuing their investigation.
<P>
<B>Wisconsin...</B>
<BR>
Researchers at the Medical College of Wisconsin have been able
to determine that a short-barreled .25-caliber handgun is the
most common weapon used in homicides and suicides in the
Milwaukee area.  One handgun, the inexpensive Raven MP 25,
was said to be used in 14 percent of the homicides and 12 percent
of the suicides carried out in a five year period in Milwaukee.
<P>
<HR>
<H3>**INTERNATIONAL EMERGENCY SERVICES REPORTS**</H3>
<B>Canada...</B>
<BR>
A house fire in the suburbs of Montreal claimed the lives of five
people on Tuesday.  Fire broke out in the basement of the two-story
brick dwelling located in Laval, Quebec, at about 0900 EST.
<P>

Firefighters found two parents and two children aged 5 and 6-years
in the master bedroom of the home.  The 5-year-old twin of one of
the dead children was found in the basement.  All of the victims
apparently died from smoke inhalation.
<P>

<B>Zaire...</B>
<BR>
A passenger truck that was carrying almost 100 people crashed into
a ditch on New Year's Day killing at least 32 people and injuring
62 others.  The truck was said to be traveling at about 50 MPH when
a tire blew out and sent the truck into the ditch in the capital
city of Kinshasa.
<P>
Even though this Mass Casualty Incident happened in a city with a
population of six million people, it took emergency services more
than two hours to reach the victims.  Emergency services in Zaire
are said to be normally slow, but they were even more so because
of the holiday.
<P>
Many doctors and emergency medical workers in the capital city 
reportedly have not been paid in months or, in some cases, even
years.  Commuters must often rely upon passenger trucks because
the public transportation system is in shambles.
<P>
<B>Great Britain...</B>
<BR>
A woman went on a rampage in a London JobCentre on Wednesday.  She
reportedly was armed with several knives and screwdrivers and stabbed
four people.  Two of the victims were women with stab wounds to their
heads.  One man suffered a stab wound to his right upper arm.  A
London Ambulance Service spokesman said, "They are all serious."
<P>
Scotland Yard said, "It is believed that a female entered the 
JobCentre with a knife and assaulted a number of people."  The
woman was arrested by police with any apparent incident.  The
motive for the woman's rampage is not known.
<P>
Of the four victims, the worst injured was a man who was found by
police outside of the building with a large carving knife embedded
in his head.  A Metropolitan Police sergeant said that the man was
conscious, calm and talking.  The sergeant said, "The knife looked
like a big carving knife.  It was stuck in the left side of his
head, sticking out at an angle.  The man was calm, but then he
hadn't seen himself."
<P>
The sergeant told what else he saw at the scene, "The woman had
several weapons.  I have seen at least two knives and two screwdrivers
and I understand there may be more.  When we arrived there were lots
of knives and lots of blood.  At first there were not enough
ambulances to deal with the casualties and the crews had to split
up.  Eventually there were three ambulances here."
<P>
<HR>
<H3>**DISASTER NEWS**</H3>
<B>
<BR>Florida...</B>
<BR>
The Metro-Dade Emergency Operations Center has reported that a
tornado hopscotched across the Dade County suburbs on Wednesday
morning and has injured at least four to six people and damaged
several homes.
<P>

Metro-Dade Police said that a tornado and high winds from a
thunderstorm had caused major damage to at least seven homes
in a suburban area located just south of Miami.  The wind also
reportedly ripped a hole in the roof of a church.
<P>

The National Weather Service said that a line of thunderstorms
stretched across the southern tip of the Florida Peninsula and
had spawned a tornado that had winds ranging rom 75 to 110 MPH.
One forecaster at the NWS said, "Tornadoes are very short-lived
in South Florida, so this whole episode was probably over in
five minutes.  It's not like the Midwest where they come down
and stay on the ground for half an hour and travel for 100 or
150 miles."
<P>
<HR>
<H3>**MILITARY - INTELLIGENCE - TERRORISM**</H3>
<B>India..</B>
<BR>
At least five people were killed and another 21 were injured when
a bomb exploded in a crowded bazaar in New Delhi on Wednesday.
The blast set three shops on fire and it took firefighters about
one hour to bring the blaze under control.  There was no immediate
claim of responsibility for the bombing.  Sikh separatists are
said to be responsible for major bombings in the city in September
and November.
<P>
<B>Germany...</B>
<BR>
A United States official in Bonn, Germany, said on Tuesday that
U.S. intelligence has received unconfirmed reports that Muslim
extremists may be planning terrorist attacks against United States
and Isreali targets in Germany.  It is said to be unclear of when 
and where the possible attacks may be carried out.  But it is
believed that the terrorists who are planning the attack are in
Germany or are enroute.
<P>
Last Friday, the United States Embassy in Germany did issue a warning
to American citizens to increase their personal security awareness.
There has been no known word from the Embassy or the government of
the State of Isreal.
<P>
<B>Isreal...</B>
<BR>

The security chief of Isreal's famed Shin Bet security service has
told Isreal's Knesset Foreign Affairs and Defense Committee that
West Bank towns that the Palestinian Liberation Organization (PLO)
has taken over could become breeding grounds for terrorism against
the State of Isreal.
<P>

The director, who only be identified by the initial "C", said that
the areas in the Gaza Strip and Jericho have already been used as
"launching pads" for terrorist attacks in Isreal.
<P>

"C" said that PLO chief Yassar Arafat has been trying to oppose
members of the Hamas and Islamic Jihad terrorist groups in those
areas.  More than 80 suspected terrorists have been arrested for
planning attacks on Isreal.  However, even despite the efforts of
Arafat and the PLO, the terrorists have increased their operational
ability and have no problem, whatsoever, finding volunteers to carry
out suicide attacks.
<P>
Shin Bet is most concerned that towns like Ramallah, which is located
just north of Jerusalem and Qalqiliya, which is near Tel Aviv, will be
used for the planning and implementation of additional terrorist attacks.
<P>
