<HEAD>
<TITLE>NYPD Drug Busts Congest the System </TITLE>
<!-- Comment Here -->
</HEAD>
<BODY>
Excerpted from EmergencyNet NEWS Service (ENNFAX)
<BR>
Monday, April 8, 1996
<BR>
Vol. 2 - 099
<P>
<B>**LEAD STORY**</B>
<P>
<H2>NYPD DRUG PUSH HAS ADVERSE EFFECT ON SYSTEM...</H2>
By Jim Fay  ENN NYC-NJ Metro Correspondent
<P>

The much heralded multi-borough NYPD drug enforcement
campaign, called "Operation Juggernaut,"  has caused
immediate problems to a system that was never setup
to handle massive arrest.
<P>

While the Police Department announced plans to
cover all bases in the effort, two other parts
of the NYC criminal justice triangle, the courts
and the District Attorney's offices, are attempting
to make do with the resources they have.
<P>

Finger pointing has begun already, as narcotic teams
in Brooklyn, Queens, and in The Bronx, make large number
of arrest, but continue to process them through a bottle-
neck of bureaucracy that was set up many years ago to
handle the one cop, one collar, type of process.
Arraignments have been delayed well beyond the mandatory
twenty-four hour period, and precinct holding cells are
far passed overcrowded to the point of what one
Sergeant called, "dangerous," when he told of more than
thirty suspects being held in station house holding
cells, and seeing the same people in the cells at 1600
hours one day that were there when he left at 2400 the
night before.  The Sergeant's precinct, one of the busiest
in NYC, usually experiences ten to 15 arrests in a twenty
four hour period.  But from April 1 to April 4, they had
recorded 165 arrest due to the drug push.
<P>

Although the NYPD can, and has, brought personnel from
around the city to effect this effort of numerous
"buy and bust" arrests in the neighborhoods that need
them, the D.A.'s have already stated that their manpower
is low to begin with, and by bringing other Assistant
District Attorneys into the purge, it will definitely
have a ripple effect on ongoing prosecutions.  Assistant
Bureau Chief of the DA's officers are being sent to
the arraignment parts of the courts to move the throng
through the initial stages of making bail or accepting
pleas before a judge.
<P>

NYC has a particularly unusual procedure, in that every
arrest, except for very minor ones, has to be evaluated
by an Assistant District Attorney (ADA) before being brought
before a judge. This procedure on a slow day can cause an
officer to remain on duty 12 to 24 hours above his normal
time of duty, just to process one arrest. On a Saturday morning
it is not unusual to see upwards of 150 police officers lined
up at Manhattan's Criminal Court Building to begin the process of
being seen by an ADA, with one arrest each, ranging from
DWI to murder. This is a far cry from what other officers,
even in major cities, experience.  And since each officer
is usually on overtime with the arrest, it has generated an
in-house term of "collars for dollars."
<P>

The court system has already announced that they will
have to "do with what we got,"  and, with the exception
of transferring four or five Civil Court judges to the
Criminal Courts, and changing a few vacations, has done
very little in anticipation of the arrests.
<P>

All of this is compounded by the expectation that many
of the suspects will opt to go to trial for their offenses,
causing even more confusion, and the need for even more
Grand Jury indictments. Public Defenders will deluge the
court with writs of habeas corpus, if their clients are
not "seen" by a judge within in the twenty four hours
required, ultimately dismissing the charges.
<P>

The problem in NYC is one that has existed for many
years.  The boundaries between police, DA's and the courts
are well defined.  Crossing them even for the sake of
expediency and streamlining an archaic system has met with
disdain on all parts.  Of course, everyone blames everyone
else. The results are that massive arrests of the type
that are needed periodically are caught between what is
needed and what can be accomplished.
<P>
(c) EmergencyNet News Service, 1996, All Rights Reserved.
