<TITLE>Double Bombing/Bank Robbery</TITLE>
<!-- Comment Here -->
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<B>Washington...</B>
<P>

<H2>Double Bombing/Bank Robbery in Spokane, WA</H2>

Police in Spokane, Washington, along with investigators from
the Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) and the United States
Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms (ATF) are investigating
the bombing of a newspaper office and a bank robbery, both of
which, it would appear, by the same two men wearing ski masks.
<P>

The incidents happened on Monday.  No injuries were reported.
At the newspaper office, an employee spotted a man wearing a
ski mask and camouflage clothing leave a suspicious package
outside.  The employee said he opened the door, saw the package
with a lit fuse, and quickly closed the door.  Moments later,
there was an explosion that blew out two doors and several windows.
<P>

Ten minutes after that explosion, about 3 1/2 miles west of the
newspaper office, two masked gunmen entered a bank and ordered
15 people inside to immediately evacuate it.  They took an unknown amount of
cash.  A pipe bomb was left by the men and exploded inside of
the bank.  Again, nobody was injured, but extensive damge occurred
inside the bank. 
<P>

Witnesses reported seeing a white and maroon van at both locations.
A stolen van that fit this description was found by police in a 
parking lot a few blocks away from the bank a short while later.
<P>

At the newspaper office, a one-page, typewritten note was found
where the bomb exploded.  The note reportedly made religious
references and mentioned "Yahweh" which apparently means "God"
in Hebrew.  It has been reported that the term Yahweh has been
used by members of Christian Identity Movement. This movement 
is believed to have connections to white-separatist groups.
<P>

It was noted by at least one Chicago counter-terrorist analyst that bank robbery is 
a common tactic in the furtherance of guerilla movements and has been 
used by any number of "liberationist movements"...or someone who wants the 
police to think that's who committed the crime.
<P>
(c) EmergencyNet News Service, 1996, All rights reserved.
<P>
