<HEAD>
<TITLE>Fire in The NY Hamptons</TITLE>
<!-- Comment Here -->
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<BR>
<H2>Wildfires Strike the Hamptons in New York</H2>
<BR>
EmergencyNet NEWS Service
<BR>
Emergency Response & Research Institute
<BR>
6348 N. Milwaukee, Suite 312 , Chicago, IL 60646
<BR>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE: 11:00CDT
<BR>
Contact: By Clark Staten
<BR>
Phone:	 (312) 631-ERRI
<BR>
FAX:	 (312) 631-4703
<BR>
Internet: enn@emergency.com
<BR>
<HR>
<BR>  
<H4> Wildfires Strike the Hamptons</H4>
<P>
Chicago, IL., August 25, 1995 -- Early this morning, something
unusual happened in Brooklyn.  An alarm was reportedly struck on
Box# 500 and at least ten fire engines were dispatched for
mutual aid in Westhampton, Long Island.  Several NYFD senior
chiefs and communications personnel were also sent to assist in
a major firefighting effort that has been described by N.Y. Gov.
George Pataki as being the largest fire of the past fifty (50)
years, in New York State.  An additional five (5) pumpers have
reportedly been sent, within the past hour, from New York City.
<P>
At least forty (40) firefighters have reportedly been injured
while battling the blaze, that has been burning since Thursday.
Their injuries range from minor bumps and bruises to smoke
inhalation and trouble breathing. According to fire officials,
more than 170 firefighting units have been dispatched to the
scene. Concerns have been raised about the safety of more than
1,000 volunteer "structural firefighters" who have been
attempting to control the conflagration.
<P> 
Several say that they are doing everything that they can, but one 
exhausted firefighter told ENN that they do not have the training or
equipment for "wildlands" firefighting and that "city tactics"
don't work in "the bush".  Col. Ed Jacoby, Forest Ranger
Commander, of the New York Forestry service, said that five (5)
fixed wing airplanes will be dropping water this morning in an
attempt to help firefighters to gain an upper hand on the blaze
that has been burning out of control since last night.  Several
state helicopters are also being used for command and control
functions and to drop water on "hot spots".
<P>
President Clinton, who is on vacation in Wyoming, has sent
Federal Emergency Management Agency Chief James D. Witt to the
scene to coordinate the federal response to the situation.  Witt
said that additional resources from Minnesota and Kentucky would
be flown into the area this morning, to assist in the fight. At
least six "strike teams" of elite federal wildland firefighters
were also expected to be sent to the scene.  Gov. Pataki has
declared the location as a disaster area and Pres. Clinton is
said to have authorized federal funding of the firefighting
efforts.
<P>
New York forestry officials have estimated that at least 6,000
acres of land have been burned as of this morning, and that the
fire is still considered "out of control". Speculation as to the
cause of the fire has centered on arson, and a complete
investigation has been ordered. Several areas have been
evacuated, according to police officials, and many very
expensive resort mansions and homes are reportedly still
threatened by the wind-driven fire.
<P> 
Wildfire control experts say that this fire is most unusual for
the New York area and that control of the fire is being hampered
by shifting 35 m.p.h. winds that are pushing it, first in one
direction and then in the next. Additionally, they say that it
naturally takes some time to shift effective "wildfire"
resources from the Mid-West and Western part of the United
States, where these kinds of fires normally occur, to the East
Coast, where they routinely do not operate.
<P>
Local fire officials said that they couldn't give an estimate
when the fire would be contained and declared under control, but
that every possible effort is under way at the time of this
report.
<P>
                       -30-
<BR>
<BR>
<HR>
