<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Gen. McCaffrey & War on Drugs</TITLE>
<!-- Comment Here -->
</HEAD>
<BODY>
Excerpted from; EmergencyNet NEWS Service (ENNFAX)
<BR>
Sunday, April 21, 1996
<BR>
Vol. 2 - 112
<P>
<B>**LEAD STORY**</B>
<P>
<H2>GENERAL McCAFFREY LEADS THE BATTLE AGAINST DRUGS...</H2>
By Steve Macko, ENN Editor
<P>

Retired 4-star U.S. Army General Barry McCaffrey has fought
for his country around the world.  From Vietnam to Kuwait
and in South America.  But this tough, no-nonsense military
officer who has close-cropped hair may be facing his toughest
assignment ever.  Early last month President Bill Clinton
appointed McCaffrey as the new head of the Office of National
Drug Control Policy.  Now, the 53-year-old general is discovering
a whole new world right here in the United States.
<P>

In the past year, 12 million Americans will have used illegal
drugs.  50 federal agencies and countless state and local law
enforcement departments have been unable to stop the flood of
drugs that continues to come into this country.
<P>

In Vietnam, McCaffrey had to face machine-gun fire.  He raced
across the sands of southern Iraq during the Gulf War.  But
earlier this month, the general was in Chicago visiting Cook
County Jail on Chicago's West Side.  He came to look at 
alternative plans to locking up non-violent drug offenders.
<P>

McCaffrey talked to defendants who were awaiting trial.  They
defendants told him about the program that allows them to spend
up to eight hours a day in drug treatment and in classes.  The
general said that his tour in Chicago was "enormously useful."
<P>

McCaffrey's new job keeps him on the go.  One day he'll be in
Chicago.  The next day, it's back to Washington and from there
it's a trip to Mexico City.
<P>

When the general was confirmed by the U.S. Senate in March.
When the President nominated McCaffrey for the post, nobody
missed the symbolism of having the highly decorated, 4-star
general become the nation's "drug czar."
<P>

Do not speak to McCaffrey about a "drug war."  McCaffrey said,
"The metaphor is inadequate to what we're doing.  We're not
going to run a year- or two-year-long campaign and achieve
total victory."  McCaffrey says that drugs must be approached
like cancer.  Treat the pain and try to kill the disease at
the roots. He also insists that his appointment to a civilian agency is
not an effort to make it more military.
<P>

Above everything else, don't call McCaffrey the "drug czar."
The general barked, "I'm not the drug czar.  I'm just the
quarterback of this effort.  In this country, nobody's in
charge, and we like it that way.  It's not what I do.  We
have to fight drugs as a country."
<P>

When President Clinton named McCaffrey to his new post, he
vowed to give the general the tools he needed to wage battle
on the drug problem in the United States.  One of the first
things McCaffey said was that the U.S. cannot "arrest our way"
out of the drug problem that is gripping the country.
<P>

Supreme Court Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg officiated over the
ceremony that installed McCaffrey into his new post.  Ginsburg
called the 1964 graduate of West Point a "clear thinking man of
action."
<P>

Last month, after taking office, McCaffrey said, "I'm going to
be a coordinator, an energizer, a manager, a watchdog.  I'm going
to be focused and serious about this."  The general warned, "We
will not arrest our way out of the drug challenge ...law enforcement
officials of America are hopefully going to have our complete
support but there has got to be more than that.  This problem isn't
going to be solved by the federal government.  The people who are
going to pull this together are school teachers, are religious
leaders, are families, are coaches, police officers, that's who's
going to do it."
<P>

The President thanked McCaffrey for taking the job and "accepting
this call to lead our nation's battle against drugs."  The President
also said, "Drugs are as much a threat to our security as any
outside enemy is today.  They are the leading cause of crime and
violence."  "I want you to have the tools you need," the President
told McCaffrey.
<P>

Clinton also said, "Our national security, the well-being of our
children are at stake.  We can create a safer, more drug-free
society.  We can do this if we work together."
<P>

It's hard to imagine anyone better qualified than McCaffrey
for his postition.  He had to retire from the Army, where he
served for 31 years.  McCaffrey was decorated for valor in
combat during the Vietnam War.  In the 1991 Gulf War, he led
the 4th Infantry Division.  The last two years he was the chief
of the U.S. Southern Command that is based in Panama.  He directed
all U.S. troops in Latin America.  The U.S. Southern Command has
been heavily involved in interdicting drugs and helping countries
in Central and South America block their own production and
transportation of drugs.
<P>

The general said that leaving the military after 31 years of
service was "very painful."  But, he said, his new job "is
fundamentally the protection of the American people.  So, in
that sense, it won't be different from what I've been doing the
last 31 years."
<P>

Speaking about what can be done about the drug problem, McCaffrey
reiterated, "This is not a war that's going to be won by anybody's
military."  He said that the effort will require attacks from all
sides.  This includes treatment for drug addicts, efforts to keep
children away from drugs and continued support of law enforcement.
<P>

McCaffrey does know, first hand, what drugs can do to people.  He
said, "The U.S. Army that I was a part of and so loved was almost
destroyed by alcohol abuse and illegal drugs in the 70's.  Up to
two-thirds of our battalion were using drugs all the time or some
of the time, and the impact on our discipline, on rape, violence,
spiritual loss of focus, physical health was just atrocious."
<P>

It does seem that Barry McCaffrey is the right man for the job.
It has taken a military man to tell everyone that the country
cannot wage a "war" on drugs.  Hopefully, he can install some
programs that work and place the focus of how to deal with the
problem in the right direction.  The thing is -- if McCaffrey
can't succeed ... who in the world ever will?
<P>
(c) EmergencyNet News Service, 1996, All Rights Reserved.
