<HEAD>
<TITLE>Oakland Fire, Two Days of Hell--01/92 </TITLE>
<!-- Comment Here -->
</HEAD>
<BODY>
1400 CDT-01/12/92   Immediate release - Non exclusive
<BR>
<H2>"TWO DAYS of HELL" in Alemeda County, CA.</H2>

Alemeda Co., CA.  With "exploding trees" and entire
neighborhoods on fire, a major brush fire burned out of
control overnight in the vicinity of Oakland CA.
Firefighters from more than 50 departments were unable to
extinguish the blaze on Sunday, due to high winds and
unusually warm October heat that has turned the already dry
scrub brush on the surrounding hills into "fireballs" that
crackled, popped, and roared as they consumed more than 200
Alemeda County homes.
<P>

Several exhausted rural and mutual aid firefighters
complained of the fact that their suction connections would
not fit the water hydrants in the Oakland area.  Many stood
by, frustrated, awaiting the arrival of adapters that would
allow them to "go to work" on the fire. Oakland Mayor Elihu
Harris was heard to comment that the fire was "out of
control".  Fire Chiefs from several communities, city fire
officers, and state officals were meeting constantly to map a
strategy that would allow them to stop the fire at various
points.  Each "battleline" was drawn, and each one was
overjumped by the wind-whipped brands of burning debris.
<P>

A single-family dwelling near Oakland was the site of the
deaths of a family of five people, who died while trying to
escape the flames. Neighbors said that they had stayed in
their home in an attempt to salvage their belongings when the
entire neighborhood "lit up" in a burst of fire described as
"Hell on Earth" by one bystander. 
<P>

At least one firefighter was reported killed during a rescue 
attempt, and dozens more were transported to several area 
hospitals for treatment of heat exhaustion and smoke inhalation.  
According to a reputable West coast firefighting source another firefighter
is listed as missing ( at the time of this report) and at
least one police officer has been reportedly killed by the
blaze.  According to one hospital spokesman, as many as 200
people have been transported to area hospitals.
<P>

Fire Service experts have recounted that the weather has been
a major detriment to the firefighting effort. First, on
Sunday, high winds prevented the California and Federal
Forestry Service aerial tankers from dropping water on the
"hotspots", and on Sunday Night and Monday morning a deep
blanket of fog enveloped the area.  Ground visability in the
areas of greatest need was reduced to almost zero. Due to a
large number of high voltage power lines and radio towers in
the vicinity, airplanes have had great difficulty in low
level flight and hitting their targets on the ground.
<P>

Also mentioned as a major problem concerning the inability of
extinguishing the blaze, was a poor water supply in an area
that has suffered almost five (5) years of drought.
Reports, early on Monday morning, indicate that two Southern
and Eastern "legs" of a triangular shaped fire are still
burning out of control and that firefighters may be gaining
an upper hand on the Northernly most "leg" of the still
spreading inferno. A firefighter, who asked to remain
unidentified, was quoted as saying, "Unless the tankers fly,
we will lose several more neighborhood to this blaze....it is
truly the worst fire I have ever seen".
<P>

Additional firefighting and emergency medical services (EMS)
resources are reportedly being dispatched from all over the
state of California to the fire, in an attempt to bring it
under control before it engulfs several additional
neighborhoods. California Governor Pete Wilson was reported
to have flown over the fire and declared it a State Disaster
Area. Members of the California National Guard were placed on
stand-by to prevent looting and to asist in the non-technical
aspects of firefighting.
<P>

One veteran firefighter, covered with sweat and grime,
summed up the feelings of many emergency workers at the
scene, "If we catch a break on the weather and the winds stay
down...we could make some real progress on this one by
tommorow morning...if not... a lot of people are going to
lose their property and maybe their lives".
<P>

By Clark Staten, Executive Director
<BR>
   Emergency Response & Research Institute
<BR>
   Available by Computer/Modem - Emergency BBS 312-631-3467
<P>
