<HEAD>
<TITLE>January IAFC Report-Gary Ludwig</TITLE>
<!-- Comment Here -->
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<B>**SPECIAL FEATURE**</B>
<H4>THE FOLLOWING IS A REPRINT FROM THE
INTERNATIONAL ASSOCIATION OF FIRE CHIEFS NEWSLETTER
"ON SCENE"</H4>
<P>


<H3>CITIES AND FIRE AGENCIES TRIUMPH IN CALIFORNIA!
</H3>
By Gary G. Ludwig, MS, EMT-P
<P>

Its official!  Several months ago I wrote about the major California
fire victory that will establish case law on EMS for California.  The 
appellate court decision indicated cities and fire agencies are 
entitled to control EMS if they provided any level of EMS on 
June 1, 1980 and had not entered into a written agreement with the
county.  In essence, fire agencies can begin fire-based EMS 
transport programs if they desire without interference from the 
counties who were generally seen as in bed with commercial 
providers and the California Ambulance Association.  At the time of
my writing, the decision was tentative.  Now, the final decision has 
come in and some legal experts believe the opinion of the judges 
contains even stronger language supporting the cities and fire 
agencies.
<P>

In my opinion, was of the reasons for this victory was because of the
strong networking system among the fire agencies throughout California.  
It is not uncommon for fax machines to run non-stop with information 
flowing back and forth when important EMS issues are on the table -
something fire agencies within other states should start looking toward.
<P>

In an unprecedented action, the IAFC and the IAFF have joined hands 
in a combined effort to assist a well known and respected fire department 
with their proposal to city officials to improve service levels in their 
community by assuming the transport role of EMS.  More on this in the 
future!
<P>

The Charlotte Fire Department (NC) recently made a proposal to improve
the level of service in their community by merging Mecklenburg County 
EMS into the department as a separate bureau.  At the center of the 
issue are financial problems and delayed responses times by 
Mecklenburg EMS.  Battalion Chief Jim Burke tells me the proposal 
calls for training EMS paramedics on a voluntary basis to also be 
firefighters.
<P>  

These medics would be placed on all front-line apparatus 
to produce a heavy front-load ALS within four minutes of critical calls.  
Conversely, firefighters could volunteer to be trained as paramedics 
and would be available to work on ambulances.  Those individuals not 
wishing to be cross-trained would still be secured in their jobs since the 
proposal calls for no lay-offs.  Ambulances would be placed in existing 
engine houses and ambulance stations would be closed to save on 
finances.  Another economic saving would occur when the two 
communication centers would be merged while streamlining efficiency.  
This program would augment the existing first responder program where 
CFD will shortly advance from AEDs on twelve pieces of equipment to all 
43 front line vehicles.  Chief Burke can be reached at 704-525-5442.
<P>

AMR had a fourth quarter one-time, non-recurring restructuring charge of
$23 million as they incurred severance costs, fixed asset disposals, and 
lease termination costs.  Following this restructuring will be a break up 
of AMR's operations into six regional units in 1996.
<P>

This month we profile EMS Section member Chief Tom Girard from Salina,
Kansas.  Chief Girard has been with the department since 1966, serving as
Chief since 1988.  SFD assumed EMS transport in 1983 from a 3rd service 
county operation.  SFD has a total staff of 87 personnel (18 paramedics), 
four stations, housing four BLS engines, three ambulances, and one ALS 
quint.
<P>

Besides being the total ALS provider, Chief Girard has one full time
teacher on staff who is dedicated strictly to public education.  
Visiting some 5,000 students annually from preschool through the 
sixth grade, the teacher not only stresses fire safety and prevention, 
but broader issues of life safety and injury prevention.  SFD has a 
"Welcome to Our Town" program.  Names of new residents are 
obtained from a local greeter service.  These new residents are then 
visited by the first-due engine company who welcomes them and 
advises them all of the services available from SFD.  In my opinion, 
a great marketing tool.  Chief Girard can be reached at (913)826-7340.
<P>
<I>Gary G. Ludwig is on the Executive Board of the EMS Section and is with 
the St.Louis Fire Department, responsible for EMS and communications.  
He can be reached at 314-533-4175; fax 314-289-1977; AOL at GaryLudwig; 
or LUDWIGSTLFD on ICHIEFS.</I>
<P>
<A HREF="/firepage.htm"><B>Return to the ENN News Page</B></A>
</BODY>
</HTML>

