<HEAD>
<TITLE>NYC Dept. Store Struck by Firebombs</TITLE>
<!-- Comment Here -->
</HEAD>
<BODY>
For Immediate Release: 12/13/95-16:00EST
<BR>
<H3>INCENDIARY DEVICES IGNITE IN MACY'S</H3>
By Jim Fay,  ENN NYC/NJ Metro Correspondent
<P>
Retailers in NYC are more vigilant during the holiday season. But
this year, it is not just for shoplifters and pickpockets.
<P>
On the heels of the W. 125 St. Massacre in Harlem, in which eight
people were killed in a shooting incident and fire set in a clothing
store,  NYC Fire and Police Departments responded to a fire in the
jewelry department of the R. H. Macy's located in a Queens, NYC,
shopping mall.
<P>
At approximately 1545 hrs., EST, the FDNY reported an "All Hands"
fire in the store, located at Queens Blvd. and 90th Street. While operating
at this fire, three other incendiary devices went off, causing small fires
in the jewelry section, where firefighters were working.  NYPD precinct patrol supervisors on the scene immediately called for Emergency Service Units and the NYPD Bomb Squad to respond, in anticipation of additional devices and explosions.
<P>
Upon the extinguishment of the initial fires, the FDNY 5th Division
Deputy Chief, at the scene, ordered a primary search of the immediate
area for possible additional devices. Finding none, the chief ordered all
shoppers, as well as all firefighters, out of the large department store and the entire shopping mall area. Queens Blvd., where the incident occurred,  is a main shopping strip in a middle class and upper-middle class section of the Borough of Queens.  Traffic conditions were substantially worsened by the arrival of the numerous emergency servcie units.
<P>
Upon arrival of the NYPD Emergency Units and Bomb Squad, a more
intensive search was done by bomb sniffing dogs and appropriately
equipped Police personnel of the first floor, where the explosions first
occurred. The search then continued as well in the rest of the three-story complex. It was discovered that the devices were battery-controlled, timed devices, hidden in shelving  and under counters. Fire damage was minimal, and the smoke conditions caused little panic in the Christmas shoppers.
<P>
NYPD Chief of Department Louis Anemone indicated that the store had
received threatening phone calls at about 1100 hrs., EST., from a
"disgruntled customer," who indicated that he attempted to return an item,
and was refused.  Because of that, the caller said he would set bombs in
the store.
<P>
No injuries to customers, firefighters or police were reported. A
representative of Macy's had nothing to say except that the store would
remain closed for the remainder of the day to assist police and FDNY
Fire Marshals in the investigation.
<P>
<A HREF="ennday.htm"><B>Return to the ENN News Page</B></A>
</BODY>
</HTML>

