<HEAD>
<TITLE>FBI/ATF Report; Church Fires in S.E. </TITLE>
<!-- Comment Here -->
</HEAD>
<BODY>
EmergencyNet News Service
<BR>
5/22/96  09:11CDT
<P>

<H2>FBI/ATF Report to Congress on Series of Afro-American Church Fires</H2>

WASHINGTON (ENN) - Federal officials on Tuesday before the House Judiciary Committee said they have found no evidence of a national conspiracy in a recent number of fires at southern black churches.  They will, however, continue their investigation into the arsons.
<P>

John Magaw, the director of the United States Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms (ATF), said, "We have not yet found any evidence of an interstate or national conspiracy, but until our work is done no motive or suspect will be eliminated.  There are indications of a conspiracy involving at least two fires in South Carolina." 
<P> 

The director said that five arrests were made in South Carolina, and in other cases -- one arrest was made in Alabama and one in Mississippi.  Magaw said, "There are a number of people who think alike throughout the country and they see somebody do something and they go do it themselves." The director was essentially saying that it appears that most of the church fires were copy-cat in nature.
<P>
Several black ministers, that testified before the committee, brought forth allegations that the fires were "racially motivated" and that they believed that they were somehow connected.  Agents said that the "methods of operation" (MO) of the perpetrators were not consistent and that while they may be generally "racially motivated", there does not appear to be a "commonality" between the cases.
<P>  

Deval Patrick, an Assistant Attorney General for Civil Rights, told the Committee, "It is premature to draw conclusions one way or the other as to whether the fires we are seeing are part of an organized hate movement."
<P>

The ATF and FBI continue to collectively investigate 32 fires in predominately black churches that have occured since January of 1995.  Six of the fires have occurred in Tennessee, five in South Carolina, five in Louisiana, four in Alabama, three in Mississippi, one in Georgia and one in Virginia.
<P>
(c) EmergencyNet News Service, 1996, All Rights Reserved.
<P>
