<HEAD>
<TITLE>"Good Times" is a Hoax</TITLE>
<!-- Comment Here -->
</HEAD>
<BODY>
For Immediate Release: 03/01/96
<P>
<U><H2>The AOL 'Good Times' Virus is a Hoax</H2></U>
Reports continue to surface from a variety of normally reputable sources in regard to a so-called "Good-Times" virus that is contained within e-mail sent through or originating from the America On-Line(tm)
computer service. The latest report (02/27/96) came from a Sheriff's Office in California and was distributed through a number of "police" channels on the Internet.  Besides police and military channels, the hoax has also reportedly proliferated among U.S. Dept. of Agriculture employees, and other reputable government offices. It appeared to be totally legitimate...<B>.it was not</B>.
<P>
Sadly, any number of reliable news sources and individuals have fallen for this rumor in the past, including the EmergencyNet News Service. Late in January, we received a copy of a message from an authentic "military souce" which explained the "virus" that was reportedly being spread by e-mail.   Stupidly, believing this previously reliable reporter, we "bit" and passed along the warning...creating quite a furor among several of our readers, who study such issues on an on-going and professional basis. They immediately, and thankfully, notified us of our error.
<P>
Even though we retracted the alert the next day and in one other subsequent story, the "cat was out of the bag".  Although our intent was honest, and our timeliness exemplary, our facts apparently left something to be desired.  We apologize for our error, stand chastised,  and vow to obtain "several" expert opinions before releasing further information about other potentially destructive viruses. If you read a "virus alert" here in the future, it will be based on at least three reliable sources.
<P>
It should be noted that Microsoft(tm) does acknowledge that there currently is a Word for Windows(tm) virus that can be spread by e-mail and that it runs a "macro" that can allow it to be become destructive. The release of that story admittedly contributed to our belief that the problem could have been transfered to other e-mail providers and systems. Experts have advised us that this method of infection of normal e-mail is not technically feasible at this time. It is confirmed that the "Good-Times" virus either doesn't exist, nor spread an infection . 
<P>
<B>REPEAT...the "Good Times" virus is a hoax, designed to waste your bandwidth and increase your insecurity!  PLEASE DO NOT spend any more time or effort spreading this rumor.... </B>
<P>
(c) EmergencyNet News Service, 1996,  All applicable rights reserved.
<P>
