<HEAD>
<TITLE>Spokane, WA City Hall Bombed</TITLE>
<!-- Comment Here -->
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<B>**FLASH TRAFFIC**</B>
<BR>
EmergencyNet News Service
<BR>
10:45CDT-04/29/96
<P>
<H2>Shrapnel Device Explodes in Spokane, WA</H2>
<P>

(ENN) A "low magnitude" Improvised Explosive Device (IED) is reported to have gone off this morning, at approx. 06:30PDT, in the Spokane, WA City hall. Police and ATF personnel are reportedly on-scene and investigating the incident. The device, was believed to be a "pipe bomb" wrapped with "dry-wall nails" as an anti-personnel/schrapnel adjunct. There were no immediate reports of injuries.  Damage was done to the building, and pieces of the device were found approximately 100 meters from the main blast site. No claim of responsibity has been made for this mornings bombing.
<P>

Spokane, WA (04/01/96) was recently the scene of the a diversionary pipe-bombing of a newspaper office and a bank robbery. Allegations of "militia or white supremacist involvement" in the earlier bombing have been made by several sources.  The Northwest has been extremely active with "militia activity" in the past two months. The Northwest was previously the scene of a series of bombings in the 1980's involving members of the "Aryan Nation" and "The Order."
<P>

ERRI counter-terrorist (CT) analysts say that militia members have become "increasingly nervous and angry" within the past few weeks as federal agents have engaged in a series of raids of various compounds and arrested known militia leaders and confiscated weapons and explosives. As militias find themselves under increasing surveillence and threat of arrest, they reportedly find themselves with three viable choices; go deeper "underground", retaliate against the government, or capitulate and surrender peacefully.  While only the last alternative will assure their safety, and that of the public, the question remains as to how many will choose another and more violent option.
<P>
(c) EmergencyNet News Service, 1996, All Rights Reserved.
