<html>

<head>
<title>FBI Joins &quot;War on Drugs&quot;</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p><img src="Enn3d.gif" align=bottom width=397 height=35></p>
<p>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE-EMERGENCYNET NEWS SVC.-01/11/92-1000CST </p>
<p><font size=5>FBI ENLISTS IN LOCALS' &quot;WAR ON DRUGS&quot; </font></p>
<p>By: Clark Staten </p>
<p>Chicago, IL (ENN) Newly appointed U.S. Attorney General William Barr announced on Thursday that 
he will be shifting the priorities of approximately three-hundred (300) Federal Bureau of Investigation 
(FBI) agents to the nation's &quot;War on Drugs&quot;. Barr cited a decrease in tensions with the Soviet Union and 
the Eastern Bloc, as the reason for allowing the FBI shift from counterintelligence to anti-gang work. </p>
<p>Crime analysts, however, point out that the disintegrating U.S.S.R. may not be the prime motivating 
factor in the Attorney General's decision. They point to the fact that more than thirty (30) major U.S. 
cities have reported record crime rates during 1991, and that drug and gang inspired crimes have 
increased dramatically in the past few years. </p>
<p>Experts also note that U.S. President George Bush had pledged, during his 1988 campaign, to &quot;Fight a 
War on Crime and Drugs&quot;. At least one Chicago political strategist has indicated that the recent move 
may be an attempt at providing &quot;needed reinforcements in the war&quot; prior to the upcoming presidential 
election season. </p>
<p>Chicago Police (CPD) crime statistics indicate that 1991 brought the city's second highest murder rate 
ever, and that gang-related murders have doubled since 1988. Chicago Mayor Daley's response to this 
growing problem was to increase the CPD Gang Crimes Unit to a record strength of 500 officers, 
making it the second largest unit in the department. </p>
<p>City officials in several other major U.S. cities have reported record murder rates. The city of 
Washington D.C. reported it's highest murder record ever during 1991. Cities in California and Texas 
also reported record murder and violent crimes rates, much of it contributed by law enforcement officials 
to a proliferation of gangs and drugs. </p>
<p>The Justice Department also announced the organization of a computerized center for tracking the 
migration of gangs and gang members between states. Attorney General Barr indicated that many gangs 
now operate across statelines, thus making them vulnerable to federal investigation and prosecution for 
inter-state violation of local laws. Barr also indicated that his office will enforce federal anti-drug laws, 
which carry far heavier penalties than do many state and local laws. </p>
<p>(c) Emergencynet News Service, 1992, All rights Reserved.</p>
