<HEAD>
<TITLE>Plan to Save 75-100,000 Cardiacs</TITLE>
<!-- Comment Here -->
</HEAD>
<BODY>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE-EMERGENCYNET-11/24/91-11:30CST
<P>
<H2>75-100,000 MORE AMERICANS COULD BE SAVED EACH YEAR FROM HEART ATTACK</H2>
By Paul Anderson
<P>

Chicago,IL.(ENN) At least one third (1/3) of all Americans that
suffer a cardiac arrest could be saved if communities in the
United States were willing to upgrade their Emergency Medical
Service (EMS) systems, according to Clark Staten of the
Chicago based Emergency Response and Research Institute.
Staten says, "the state-of the art exists today to save at
least seventy-five thousand (75,000) more cardiac arrest
victims every year...if Americans are willing to commit their
financial resources to this effort".
<P>

According to National Institute of Health statistics, more
than 350,000 Americans will suffer cardiac arrests during the
coming year. More than two thirds (2/3) of these events will
occur outside of hospitals, and are potentially treatable by
prehospital providers (Paramedics), according to several
recent studies.  A nineteen (19) month study conducted by
doctors at the Rhode Island Hospital in Providence, Rhode
Island, and published in the November 13th edition of the New
England Journal of Medicine says that the medical community
is "misplacing it's priorities" by spending money on "futile
resuscitation efforts that take place long after they will be
beneficial to the patient".
<P>

Doctors in the Rhode Island study said that the money would
be better spent on "increasing the number of emergency
medical service (EMS) units, staffed with the necessary
equipment and training to get the heart started again".  Dr.
William Gray of the Cardiology division of Rhode Island
Hospital also recommended that members of the general public
should be educated in the basic principals and practice of
cardiopulmonary resuscitation (CPR).
<P>

Another study, recently released by Dr. Myron Weisfeldt of
the Columbia Presbyterian Medical Center in New York, found
that treatment for heart attack victims is often delayed
by as much as sixty (60) minutes.  Weisfeldt says that as
many as fifty (50) percent of all heart attack victims could
be saved if they were treated in a more timely manner, by
using new clot-dissolving drugs and early defibrillation
techniques that have been developed during the past five
years.  Dr.  Costas Lambrew of the Maine Medical Center,
noted that in some hospitals, registration and testing
procedures within emergency rooms may also contribute to
delays in providing potentially life saving treatments.
<P>

"The answer would appear to be an integrated approach to
providing rapid and effective emergency medical care to the
patient...where it occurs... and at the onset of the event",
said Clark Staten, a veteran paramedic and emergency manager.
"The studies say that many cardiac arrests can be prevented,
and the the damage to the heart muscle minimized by beginning
treatment of the cause and effect of the heart blockage at
the scene of the incident", he continued. "The technology and
drugs exist to allow us to save many more lives every year,
if we combine the accumulated knowledge with a reorganization
of our use of emergency medical care resources", Staten said.
<P>

Staten said, "tens of thousands of cardiac patients could be
salvaged"... if:
<P>

<UL>
<LI>1. Those suffering the signs and symptoms of cardiac
   impairment knew when to call for emergency medical care
<LI>2. Many citizens were well trained in the recognition of
   heart attacks and able to perform adequate cardio-
   pulmonary resuscitation
<LI>3. All communities had an integrated/computerized 911
   emergency dispatch system
<LI>4. Multi-tiered emergency medical response systems were
   implemented that utilized all Fire, Police, and EMS
   resources for an arrival of trained technicians within 4-6
   minutes of a cardiac event
<LI>5. Programs were developed that provide rapid defibrillation
   for patients suffering from Ventricular Fibrillation (an
   uncoordinated "quivering" of the heart)
<LI>6. Educated Emergency Medical Technicians (Paramedics)
   were routinely allowed to give clot-dissolving drugs like
   T.P.A. or Activase to patients suffering from heart attack
   signs and symptoms
<LI>7. Patients were transported to appropriate hospitals that
   specialize in treating cardiac patients, after they had
   received the life-saving care previously mentioned
<LI>8. Communities are willing to commit the necessary financial
   resources to the planning and implementaion of these
   programs
</UL>
<P>
"In times of dwindling municipal budgets, this plan sounds
like another plea for tax increases...when, in reality, it is
a call for an efficient use of the dollars that we already
spend for medical care", Staten said.  "It is a unique time
in history... when we discover that we can definitively save
even more lives by re-allocating our financial commitment to
the provision of quality prehospital emergency medical care",
Staten concluded.
<P>                      
(c) EmergencyNet NEWS Service, 1991, All Rights Reserved.
