<HEAD>
<TITLE>Recent Cincinnati Fire Rprts.-12/20/95</TITLE>
<!-- Comment Here -->
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<B>
<BR>
For Immediate Release: 12/20/95-16:00
<BR> 
Cincinnati...</B>

<H3>Recent Cincinnati Fire Reports</H3>

Unfortunately, ENN is presently unable to obtain immediate reports of fires/EMS runs in Cincinnati, Ohio. As much as we'd like to, we can't seem to get up-to-the-minute incident reports, as we have been able to get them from other departments.  But, your editor thought that it would be interesting to see what the Cincinnati Fire Department has been up to lately.
<P>

On Sunday, December 10th, at 1443 EST, Cincinnati firefighters fought a
2 Alarm fire at 1713 Fairfax Avenue.  Fire was in a 4-flat building.
Firefighters rescued three people from the burning building.
<P>

On Monday, December 11th, at 2119 EST, Cincinnati had a 3 Alarm fire
at 7218 Scottwood Avenue.  First arriving firefighters reported heavy
fire from the basement and first floor of a 2-story brick vacant dwelling.
Fire quickly extended throughout the building.  Command reported an
exposure problem and an exterior attack was conducted.  It took 60
firefighters about three-and-a-half hours in frigid temperatures to
battle this blaze.
<P>

Cincinnati firefighters battled a 2 alarm fire at 2255 EST, on Friday,
December 15th, at 259 West McMicken.  Fire was reported in a 3-story
brick apartment building.  Firefighters had some trouble finding the
seat of the fire in the building.  It was finally found in a large
crawlspace located between the second and third floors.  A lot of
truck work was required to knock the fire down.
<P>

At 0132 EST, on Sunday, December 17th, Cincinnati had a 2 Alarm fire
at 1270 IIiff Avenue.  When first arriving fires companies came upon
the scene, they reported heavy fire on the first floor of a 3-story
dwelling.  The fire extended throughout the structure.  It took 36
firefighters with four engines, three ladders, a heavy rescue, a
paramedic rescue unit, a District Chief and an Assistant Chief about
two-and-a-half hours to bring this blaze under the control.
<P>
