<HEAD>
<TITLE>Twin Train Disasters; KY and Mexico</TITLE>
<!-- Comment Here -->
</HEAD>
<BODY>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE * EMERGENCYNET NEWS * 11-19-91 2300 CST
<P>
<H2>TRAIN WRECKS CAUSE DISASTERS IN KENTUCKY & MEXICO</H2>

Chicago,IL. (ENN) Two separate train crashes have resulted in
major disasters in Shepardsville, KY and Tehuacan, Mexico.
<P>

The first of these events events took place at approximately
12:40 p.m. on Tuesday afternoon in an area 150 miles
Southeast of Mexico City.  Reportedly, the train jumped the
track on a curve and slid onto the Veracruz-Mexico highway.
The resulting multiple collisions with twenty (20) cars and
trucks caused as many as seventy (70) deaths and more than
forty (40) injuried.  The Mexican Federal Highway Police
report that many people were entraped within vehicles and the
train and that the death toll may rise. Mexican officials
hypothesized that the train may have sufferred a brake
failure which prevented it from slowing for a sharp curve,
when the accident occured. Details were slow in being
reported due to the remoteness of the area and the fact the
rescue was still underway at the time of this report.
<P>

Shortly after the Mexican derailment (at approximately 1300
CST), a second train accident involved an eighty-nine (89)
car frieght train carrying hazardous materials and explosives
took place in a small town twenty (20) miles south of
Louisville, KY.  The train, in the Kentucky crash, hurtled
off a bridge outside of Shepardsville, Ky. and tumbled into
the Salt River.  More than 1,000 people from Shepardsville
and the surrounding area were immediately evacuated to a Red
Cross shelter at a nearby county fairgrounds.
<P>

Several train cars were set on fire by the collision and
continued to burn until the time of this report.  Reportedly,
a car containing Methylene Diphenyl Diisocyanate was being
encrouched by another burning car.  The Diisocyanate is both
extremely poisonous and flammable. It is similar in chemical
make-up to the Diisocyante that was released in Bhopal,
India.  Also reportedly involved in the incident was another
tank car containing Propylene Oxide that remained on the
bridge over the continuing fire.  Another car that contained
military cluster bombs was involved in the wreck, but did not
explode and was not close to the actual site of the fire nor
the cars that went into the water.
<P>

Fire and disaster officials, on the scene, have declined to
send firefighters into the immediate area to fight the fire.
State Fire Marshall Rodney Raby said that he and other fire
officials had a concern, that, "if we put personnel down
there (near the fire)...that we have no assurances that we'd
get them out".  State Disaster Agency Chief Charlie Frazee
reportedly said, "Our foremost concern is the fact that we
have an insulated tankcar down there that has been subjected
to flames for some period of time".  At least one local
emergency medical service official said that there was a fear
of toxic substances being released near the derailment.
<P>

Clark Staten, Executive Director of the Emergency Response
and Research Institute in Chicago,IL  hypothesized that the
Kentucky officials feared a possible "BLEVE" (Boiling Liquid
Expanding Vapor Explosive) of a potentially toxic chemical
car.  He said, "a BLEVE of a flammable liquid that is also
poisonous is a disastrous event, but it can also may be a
`Godsend'...if the fire consumes the toxic material in it's
entirety by the high temperatures and flash of the
explosion".  "Many toxic materials can be effectively
disposed of by burning, if the fire is hot enough... the
problem is compounded, however, when the materials are not
completely consumed and the potentially deadly, partially
destroyed, by-products of combustion are released into the
air" he concluded.
<P>

Local police officials are said to be conducting an
investigation into the cause of the derailment.  A witness
said that a local garbage truck had struck the bridge, that
was involved in the derailment, just prior to the accident
and that it might have caused the wreck.  Kentucky State
Police are said to be interviewing witnesses and studying the
crash site, but that the investigation will be delayed until
the danger of fire and explosion passes. No injuries were
reported by the local emergency medical service agency.
Kentucky Governor Wallace Wilkenson reportedly visited the
scene late Tuesday and declared the site a state disaster
area.
<P>
