<BR>
<H3>Hurricane Opal; Deadly Storm Hits Gulf Coast</H3>
<BR>
<P>
<BR>
Chicago, IL, (ENN) October 4, 1995 -- Although weakened somewhat in
the past few hours, Hurricane Opal is still a Category 3/4 storm
with 125-145mph winds.  It is being called "extremely dangerous"
by weather watchers and emergency officials. Many Floridians,
Mississippians, and Alabama residents must have taken the
warning to heart, as evacuations have caused massive traffic
jams for those heading North to flee the storm. The traffic has
become so bad in some Gulf Coast areas that police and emergency
planners are suggesting that people who aren't already on the
road stay at home and 'button-up" to wait out the storms.
<P> 

National Weather Service forecasters predict that Opal will make
landfall today in the late afternoon or early evening and that
the eye may pass over the Pensacola, FL, area. Opal is reported
to be moving N-NE at 23mph at the time of this report.
<P> 

Emergency service officials say that they fear that some local
residents may not have taken reports of the hurricane seriously,
or not heard them at all as much public attention has been
deflected in the past day or two by the extensive coverage of
the O.J. Simpson trial and verdict. Another concern raised is
that Jewish residents in the area may not have been properly
warned because they are in the midst of celebrating Yom Kippur,
which could essentially prohibit them from watching TV or
listening to the radio. Also thought to be at risk are elderly
or retired people, who may not pay much attention to media
reports. Emergency officials say, however, that they are hopeful
that most of those in the path of Opal have moved to higher
ground.
<P>
The Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA), which received
much criticism following its response to Hurricane Andrew, has
reportedly sent several senior staff members to the area to
assess preparedness and begin the process of rescue/recovery as
soon as the storm passes. Having FEMA officials immediately
available to assess the damage may help to hasten the state and
federal disaster declaration process and start the flow of
essential supplies, according to several disaster experts.
Controversy erupted in the Miami area shortly after the landfall
of Hurricane Andrew, as difficulties arose in completing the
necessary paperwork and making notifications to activate the
flow of federal dollars and equipment to assist in the local
rescue efforts.
<P>

Local emergency agencies are already said to be on maximum alert
with off-duty police, firefighters, and paramedics being
recalled to stations, so that they can respond as soon as
possible to emergencies caused by the coming deluge of wind and
rain. Many have been assisting in sandbagging efforts in
low-lying areas in the past day or two and others have been
helping friends and neighbors with board-up efforts. Many of the
emergency agencies in the area are volunteers, who may work at a
regular occupation until called upon in an emergency such as
Opal.
<P>  

During an interview this afternoon, with two members of a local
Florida rescue squad, they said that they were in the process of
locating the heavy construction equipment that might be
necessary to assist in the extrication of people that have been
buried or trapped by building collapses. They also say that, at
this time, they are preparing for the worst and are praying for
the best. The interview was concluded with a rapid goodbye and
the sounds of sirens as the volunteer EMTs (Emergency Medical
Technicians) sped off to help someone involved in a traffic
accident caused by the rain-slickened streets. It is likely that
the call will be only one of many in the coming hours.
<P>
<BR>
