<html>

<head>
<title>What are Syria's Intentions?? 08/30/96</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>Excerpted from EmergencyNet News Daily Report<br>
08/30/96 - Vol. 2, No. 243</p>
<p><font size=5><strong>WHAT IS THE INTENTION OF SYRIA?</strong></font><br>
By Steve Macko, ENN Editor<br>
<br>
JERUSALEM (ENN) - It was reported that on Wednesday, MK Hagai Merom, the former chairman of the Israeli 
Knesset's Security and Foreign Affairs Committee, said that he had evidence that there are increasing indications that Syria 
is seriously considering the option of war against Israel as a way of ending a diplomatic deadlock. Merom said that he has 
requested a special session of the Knesset to discuss the intelligence assessments concerning relations with Syria.<br>
<br>
Professor Anthony Cordesman, who is a highly-respected chief researcher at the Center for Strategic and International 
Studies in Washington, said that the findings of a new study indicate that there is a possibility that Syria might attempt the 
initiation of a limited war against Israel. Syria may feel that it may be able to achieve its objective if it could obtain a 
strategic surprise and capture a significant portion of the Golan Heights, before a cease-fire was imposed.<br>
<br>
Intelligence sources in Lebanon are reporting that Syria appears to be taking up more defensive positions near the Syrian 
border and have made no threatening deployments of armor or troops towards the direction of Israel.<br>
<br>
So what is everyone up in arms about this week?<br>
<br>
Syrian troops made some unexpected movements and it caused jitters over its military intentions. But on Wednesday, 
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu sent a small peace offering toward Syria's President Assad. Netanyahu said 
that Israel has not ruled out negotiating a partial withdrawal from the Golan Heights. The message was sent via a letter that 
was delivered by visiting U.S. Senator Arlen Spector, who is the chairman of the Senate Select Intelligence Committee.<br>
<br>
Spector held a three-hour meeting with Assad. He had some interesting things to say afterward. Assad told Spector that 
the troop movements in Lebanon were just normal maneuvers and concealed &quot;no hostile intent&quot; toward Israel. Spector 
added that the Assad that he met with on Wednesday was more &quot;mellow&quot; than the same man that he had met in 1988.<br>
<br>
What Syria wants is for Israel to return the Golan Heights that was captured in the 1967 Six-Day War. Syria insists that 
Israel agree to a land-for-peace agreement.<br>
<br>
In the past week, concern has focused on the 35,000-man army that Syria maintains in Lebanon. Syrian units were shifted 
from the Beirut area eastward to the Bekaa Valley.<br>
<br>
The U.S. State Department indicated that the Syrian troop movements were &quot;defensive in nature.&quot; Israel had not sent any 
message to the U.S. that they were particularly worried about the movements.<br>
<br>
Even in Chicago, where ENN has monitored this situation very closely, most of ENN's sources and analysts did not 
appear to be alarmed by the situation.<br>
<br>
But whatever Syria's Assad is doing is making analysts scratch their heads. There is no concensus of what the message that 
Assad was trying to deliver. Some analysts said that it was a signal that Syria had considered giving up diplomatic efforts. 
Others said that it was an attempt to pressure Israel into being more flexible in its negotiations.<br>
<br>
ENN contacted a number of military and counterterrorism experts in and out of government to get their assessment of what 
was happening and if Syria could reasonably expect any kind of gain from even thinking about attacking Israel. All of the 
different analysis ENN received was very enlightening.<br>
<br>
Reuven Pedatzur, the director of the Galili Center for Strategic and National Security at Tel Aviv University, said, For 
now, there is no real threat of war. But we have to be careful. Things could get out of hand.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Assad seems to have a lot of maybe misplaced confidence in his forces,&quot; said Clark Staten, the senior analyst and the 
executive director of the Chicago-based Emergency Response and Research Institute. &quot;It is my considered opinion that 
Syria can not be successful by themselves; without the cooperation of other countries in the region. Such an attack would 
ultimately be ill-advised and would result in Syria's defeat.&quot;<br>
<br>
Staten added, &quot;Although they may not be on par with a few years ago, strength and motivation may be down, the IDF is 
still one of the premier military forces in that region. They have the best tactical equipment, command and control systems, 
and access to American surveillance satellites and intelligence gathering capabilites. Syria, like Iraq, could be quickly and 
easily &quot;blinded&quot; by aircraft sorties to destroy their rudimentary command nets and radar facilities.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;The Golan area is fortified by the Israelis, who are well dug in and reserves in place. Beyond the forts are the armed 
kibbutzes,&quot; said Paul Copher, analyst-at-large and a counterterrorism expert. &quot;From the rear operating fields, the IDF 
warplanes would take five minutes to respond. The whole area is mined in a strip by the IDF and old Syrian mine fields still 
kill goats and sheep.&quot;<br>
<br>
According to Copher, &quot;The strategic gain for Assad are the old Golan lines, but their troops would barely get settled in 
before a IDF massive cannon and air attack hits them. I could see a massive build up on their side of the hills as a threat, 
but the IDF would do the same.&quot;<br>
<br>
Copher concluded with some information that could make other analysts stand up and take notice. He said, &quot;Assad is 
going overboard according to a Syrian who just returned from a visit. He noted a massive propaganda campaign and the 
&quot;armed camp&quot; mentality. Rockets are alleged to be ready around the major cities for ground-to-air protection. Larger 
rockets are in camo positions in rural areas. The people are finding it hard to get enough food. The money has devalued so 
much this naturalized citizen has to send dollars to Damascus so his relatives can buy sheep on the bayrams.&quot;<br>
<br>
(C) EmergencyNet News Service, 1996. All rights reserved; contact ENN for republication rights.</p>
