<head>
<title>Contract Port Authority Dogs Begin Patrol</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>10/01/96 TUE 19:34 <br>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE: October 1, 1996 <br>
</p>
<p><font size=5><strong>Explosives-Detecting Dogs Begin Airport Patrols<br>
</strong></font><br>
Port Authority Executive Director George J. Marlin today announced that bomb-sniffing dogs have begun patrolling the 
region's three major airports, as part of the comprehensive 10-point security initiative announced recently by the agency. 
At 2 P.M. today the dogs, accompanied by specially trained handlers and Port Authority Police officers, began checks of 
passenger terminals and cargo areas. In addition to random checks, the dogs will be an call to check suspicions luggage 
and cargo at John P. Kennedy International, Newark International and La Guardia airports.<br>
<br>
&quot;Working with our partners at the airlines and the FAA, we are committed to a security program that includes constant 
reviews and upgrades,&quot; Mr. Marlin said. &quot;Rather than wait for our own detection teams to come into service in a few 
months, we're bringing in fully qualified outside contractors to provide this protection on interim basis. Deputy Executive 
Director John J. Haley, Jr., said, &quot;This is an in immediate and important step, one that we can do quickly. But we will soon 
have in place an expanded program, which will be an important part of cur overall 10-point initiative. We are determined 
that the Port Authority will continue to play a leadership role in providing security.&quot;<br>
<br>
In order to put Bomb-sniffing dogs into service immediately, the Port Authority contracted with an FAA-certified outside 
firm on an interim basis. In coming weeks, the Port Authority will acquire and train its own explosives-sniffing dogs, and 
Port Authority Police officers will be trained and certified by the FAA as handlers. The deployment of the 
explosives-detection squads is one of 10 major security initiatives for the airports announced by Mr. Marlin on September 
16. <br>
<br>
The other measures include: <br>
<img src="Blutrngl.gif" align=bottom width=11 height=11> Expand current Port Authority security auditing; <br>
<img src="Blutrngl.gif" align=bottom width=11 height=11> Crack down on frequent violators of airport security procedures; <br>
<img src="Blutrngl.gif" align=bottom width=11 height=11> Install new physical security measures; <br>
<img src="Blutrngl.gif" align=bottom width=11 height=11> Require that all airline contractor personnel involved in security obtain Port Authority-issued identification cards and 
undergo, as a minimum, a 10-year employment history check; <br>
<img src="Blutrngl.gif" align=bottom width=11 height=11> Increase to quarterly the annual review by Port Authority police of the 24-point air cargo security program; <br>
<img src="Blutrngl.gif" align=bottom width=11 height=11> Require that contractor construction personnel in aeronautical areas have Port Authority Id: * advocate stricter minimum 
training and qualification standards for airline security personnel, and provide refresher training in security for all airport 
staff; <br>
<img src="Blutrngl.gif" align=bottom width=11 height=11> Increase the frequency and level of airport-wide security meetings; and <br>
<img src="Blutrngl.gif" align=bottom width=11 height=11> Accelerate Port Authority involvement in research and development of technology-based security measures.<br>
<br>
News Release Courtesy of:</p>
<p>Port Authority of NY and NJ<br>
Office of Corporate Communications<br>
Mark 0 Hatfield Jr. Director <br>
One World Trade Center, New York NY 10048 <br>
(212} 435-7777 (24 Hours (201) 961-6600 Ext. 7777 <br></p>
<p>(Editor's note: we were advised of this story in reference to an ENN report about airport safety and security by Mr. Jim 
Fay of our NYC/NJ Bureau. To see his original story, <a href="/jfkterr.htm"><strong>Click here</strong></a> . For a report on Newark International Airport by Mr. 
Fay; <a href="/newrkrpt.htm"><strong>Click here</strong></a>)</p>
