<TITLE>ENNFAX Sample-11/30/95</TITLE>
<!-- Comment Here -->
</HEAD>
<BODY>
ENNnewsFAX
<BR>
EmergencyNet NEWS Service
<BR>
Thursday, November 30, 1995
<P>
<BR><B>**LEAD STORY**</B>
<H3>NOBODY EVER SAID MOST CRIMINALS WERE SMART...</H3>
<BR>
By Steve Macko
<P>
Many films that come out of Hollywood like to portray their villians
as smart, conniving and intellectual.  The truth of the matter, according
to author Leland Gregory, "That's all fiction.  The truth is a guy gets
drunk, tries to steal a TV and gets his foot caught in an air vent."
Gregory has recently co-authored a book with Alan Ray and Daniel Butler,
called, "America's Dumbest Criminals."  The book is published by
Rutledge Hill Press.
<P>

Some of the stories are truly amusing.  Among some of the funnier
examples is:
<P>
-- An armed robber in Nevada who allowed a convenience store clerk
one phone call during the course of the hold-up.  The robber was
quite surprised when the police came to the store.
<P>
-- A man was convicted and sentenced to 90 days in a Rhode Island
prison.  He hated being in prison so much that he spent 88 of those
days devising an escape plan.  On day 89 he escaped from the prison.
A few months later, authorities recaptured him and he was sentenced
to a year-and-a-half for escape.
<P>
-- Rhode Island must have some interesting criminals.  In another
story from that state -- a man was arrested for breaking into vending
machines and stealing the money from them.  His reason for his crime
was so that he could pay his $400 bail all in quarters.
<P>
-- A thief whose modus operandi was to smash the windows of jewelry
stores and then grab whatever valuables he could, came upon a surprise
one night.  One jewelry store that he had previously stole from had
replaced its windows with unbreakable plexiglass.  When the man came
back to rob the store window again -- he threw a cinder block at the
window, the cinder block bounced off the plexiglass and knocked him
out cold when it hit him in the head.  The incident is reportedly on
video tape.
<P>
-- Another man, this one in Tennessee, came up with a very intricate
plot that sounds like something a fiction writer would had dreamed up.
This man planned to blow up the Percy Priest Dam, which is located near
Nashville and flood the entire city.  He then thought that with the
city submerged under water, all he had to do was don some scuba gear
and he could dive for his riches.  Just because he had never went
scuba diving before did not stop this man from his plot.  Before being
caught, he had managed to explode some dynamite near the dam.  His
blast was only able to knock down a door of an old wooden shed located
near the top of the dam.
<P>
And before this article comes to an end, this author would like to
relate one of his favorite humorous episodes that shows the average
intelligence of many criminals.  Each year, the FBI is able to capture
about 20 bank robbers because the robbers write their demand notes, that 
they hand to the bank tellers ... on the back of their own printed deposit 
slips that have their name and address on it.
<P>
<HR>
<H3>**EMERGENCY SERVICES REPORTS**</H3>
<B>CFD Fire Activity For Today...</B>
<BR>
At 1302 CST, there was a Still and Box Alarm on Box 4333 at
5435 West Adams Street on Chicago's far West Side.  Fire was
in a 3-story brick 6-flat apartment building 60x100.  Fire was
knocked down quickly, but there was two people reported trapped
by firefighters.  There was one confirmed Code Black (DOA) victim.
The dead victim was said to be a 7-year-old female.
Response: E113,96,95,117, T29,26, TL14, BC13,14,8, 2-2-4, Sqd1, 2-7-1, 
A28,23, 4-9-3
<P>
<B>FDNY Fire Activity For Today...</B>
<BR>
BROOKLYN had a 2nd Alarm on Box 2474 at 265 Marlboro Road.  At 0110 EST,
fire was reported through the roof of two stores in a 1-story brick
taxpayer 75x100.
<P>
At 0615 EST, there was another 2nd Alarm fire in BROOKLYN, this one was
on Box 3494 at 130 Bay 20 Street.  Fire was reported in a 3-story
dwelling 20x40.
<P>
<H4>Nationwide Fire Activity...</H4><BR>
Fires on November 29:
<BR>
At 1320 MST, TUCSON, ARIZONA, had a 2 Alarm fire at 713 East Mable.
Heavy fire was reported through the roof of a 1-story dwelling.
<P>
In CLEVELAND, OHIO, firefighters managed to hold what seem to be a
major blaze to a Working Fire alarm at 3210 West 128th.  At about
1630 EST, a 2.5-story wood frame dwelling reportedly exploded and
flames communicated to two similar-type exposure buildings.  All
three dwellings were said to be fully involved with fire.  Firefighters
used two ladder pipes and several handlines on the blaze.  Two
civilians were reported DOA.
<P>
In suburban Cleveland, WICKLIFFE, OHIO, had a 3 Alarm fire at Lloyd Road
and Route 2.  Fire was reported in a 1-story brick vacant industrial 
200x300.  Heavy fire was reported through the roof.  An exterior attack
was used with three ladder pipes and numerous handlines.  Time of the 
alarm was 2030 EST.
<P>
Fire on November 30:
<BR>
In northern Massachusetts, LAWRENCE had a 3rd Alarm on Box 611 at
#68 Salem Street.  A 2.5-story occupied wood frame dwelling was
reported to be fully involved with heavy fire.  Time of the alarm
was 1205 EST.
<P>
<H4>Oakland...</H4>
<BR>
A car struck a group of children crossing a street in Oakland, California,
on Wednesday.  Two small children were killed and two others were 
critically hurt.  Police are still investigating the accident.
<P>
<H4>South Africa...</H4>
<BR>
85 people were injured on Wednesday when a passenger train slammed into
the rear of a freight train near Durban, South Africa.  Four freight
cars were derailed in the mishap.  Authorities said that most of the
injuries were minor and only 15 of the victims required hospitalization.
Cause of the accident was not known.
<P>
<HR>
<H4>Officer Warning...</H4>
<BR>
By: Bob Ballentine U.S. Customs
<BR>
bobbjr@agis.ag.net ballentine@baller90.customs.sprint.com http://www.ag.net/~bobbjr/
<P>
During the early summer of this year, officers of the Connecticut State
Police seized 18 bags of a green leafy substance that was identified as
ILLY.  ILLY is reported to be a mixture of marijuana and/or mint leaves
that are usually soaked in formaldehyde and PCP (Angel Dust).  ILLY
reportedly causes dizziness, nausea, hallucinations and even death.
The State Troopers who handled the evidence developed a light-headed
feeling and nausea.  They felt the effects from the substance for at
least two days.  This substance is usually kept frozen until the time
of sale.  Once the substance begins to thaw, it emits a strong chemical
odor that has a strong negative effect on people.  EXTREME CAUTION
should be exercised if you suspect that you are dealing with this
substance.  Officers are advised to avoid handling, inhaling or allowing
it to come in contact with their skin.
<P>
<HR>
<H3>**MILITARY - INTELLIGENCE - TERRORISM**</H3>
<BR>
<H4>Algeria...</H4>
<BR>
Two seamen from the Baltic country of Latvia were shot and killed and
one other seaman was wounded in an apparent terrorist attack in Algiers
on Thursday morning.  Witnesses said that four armed men attacked the 
Latvians as they were walking on a city street.  Algerian security
believes that Moslem militants are responsible for the attack.
<P>
<HR>
<H4>Northern Ireland...</H4>
<BR>
Authorities in Belfast, Northern Ireland, reported that they found
two suspected bombs on Wednesday, the day before President Clinton's
visit to the city.  One of the devices was found about 600 yards from
the Europa Hotel, where Clinton will be staying during his visit.  This
suspected bomb was blown up by explosive experts.  Police said that it
was crudely made and was bound in tape.
<P>

The second bomb was found about a mile away from the first one.  The
bomb squad was sent to the scene to investigate.  There has been no
claim for the devices and security officials are treating the incident
as serious because of Clinton's visit.
<P>
<HR>
<H4>Egypt...</H4>
<BR>
<H4>EGYPT SECURITY THREATS OUTSIDE THE NATION</H4>
<BR>
   LAURIE KASSMAN
<BR>
   MALAWI, EGYPT
<P>
Egypt is facing more security threats outside its own borders,
but the government insists its crackdown at home against Muslim
extremists is curbing violence. Most of the confrontations are
concentrated in the southern provinces of Minya and Assiut, about
250-kilometers south of the capital.
<P>
In some respects life appears unchanged for centuries in
Malawi, nestled along the banks of the Nile in the shade of palm
trees and sugar cane fields. Water buffalo stand idly by as women
in brightly-colored scarves wash pots, pans, clothes, and babies
in the Nile.
<P>
In town, donkey carts kick up dust as they jostle with cars
and pedestrians on their way to market with onions, beans, and
sugar cane from their nearby farms.
<P>
But the sounds of normalcy are interrupted by piercing sirens
as soldiers and police patrol the town and outlying roads.
Visitors passing through a security checkpoint on the southern
outskirts of Malawi find themselves immediately under army
escort. The police wear bullet-proof vests over black T-shirts
and tote automatic rifles. They are taking no chances.
<P>
More than 900 deaths have been blamed on extremist violence in
the past three-years as Muslim militants fight to set up a strict
Islamic state here. Residents here confide family feuds and armed
burglaries also account for many of the local killings.
<P>
President Hosni Mubarak says the tough crackdown is curbing
terrorism. Analysts suggest that success is forcing the militants
to take their violence outside. Last May, President Mubarak
escaped an assassination attempt in Addis Ababa. This month,
militants murdered an Egyptian diplomat in Geneva and blew up the
embassy in Islamabad.
<P>
A local representative of the Egyptian human rights group,
Fathalla Khafagy, says the situation in Malawi, and elsewhere in
southern Egypt, is calmer than a year ago when people were rarely
seen on the street after dark. Others say the evening curfew that
starts at nine is useless because violence can erupt at any time.
<P>
Mr. Khafagy stresses government force and curfews are not the
answer.  He says, poverty breeds terrorism. Farm land is limited, and
there is too much poverty and too little investment for alternative
projects. Mr Khafagy says the government spends less than seven-
percent of its budget on the south. He says he is less sure about the 
extremist religious views of suspected militants than of their frustrations.
<P>
Amal Rashed is a tiny, sharp-tongued widow in Malawi who is
running for parliament for the opposition El Wafd party. She
defends the security crackdown but also blames corrupt business
and inept administrations for breeding terrorists.  She says putting 
innocent people in jail is also terrorism and so is selling spoiled seeds to 
poor farmers.
<P>
A young salesman in Minya says his business suffers from the
checkpoints and the curfew. Villagers do not move around much any
more, they are afraid of being picked up by police for
interrogation.
<P>
Militants hide in the tall, thick sugar cane fields dominating
the countryside around Malawi and ambush road patrols and tourist
trains. In a new surge of violence this month, militants attacked
three tourist trains in the south. The government has responded
by mowing down the cane fields and sometimes bulldozing houses of
suspected militants.
<P>
A lawyer in the southern university town of Assiut says the
government campaign has produced a deceptive calm. But he does
not expect the low-grade violence to end because, as he puts it,
amputation is not the solution. He says, as long as there is
poverty and no hope for improvement, the south remains a fertile
breeding ground for unrest.
<BR>
:: Produced by INEWS ::
<P>
<HR>
<H4>Egypt...</H4>
<BR>
A passenger train was raked with gunfire on Wednesday night in southern
Egypt.  Nine people were reported wounded and several train cars were
damaged.  The attack happened near the southern Egyptian town of Malawi,
which is located about 160 miles south of Cairo.  The train was traveling
from Cairo to the city of Aswan.  This was the fourth such attack on a
passenger train in Egypt this month.  Muslim militants are the prime
suspects in the attack.
<P>
<HR>
<H4>Isreal...</H4>
<BR>
Three items of interest come to ENN from the Shomron News Service in
Isreal -- property damage resulting from Tuesday's Hizbollah rocket
attacks on northern Isreal is estimated to have caused about $3.3 million
of damage.  Forty dwellings were either destroyed or severely damaged
and 15 vehicles were destroyed.
<P>
The terrorist organization Hizbollah is reportedly funded with Iranian
money and functions with the permission of the Syrian government.  
Hizbollah enjoys a budget of between $80 to $90 million annually.  The
criminal-state of Iran also supplies Hizbollah terrorists with weapons
which are acquired through Syrian channels.  It is estimated that
Hizbollah has about 600 guerrillas who conduct such operations as
Tuesday's rocket attacks.  There are also estimated to be another 200
Muslim guerrillas who are responsible for laying roadside bombs.
<P>
Isreali police arrested two terrorists who are reportedly members of
of the Islamic terrorist group Hamas.  The terrorists were said to had
been on their way to steal weapons from two villages in southwest Isreal.
After a high-speed chase, police searched the two suspects and found
documents detailing the location of the sought-after weapons.  The
terrorists admitted intending to use the stolen weapons to shoot
passerbys on a nearby highway.  One of the terrorists had been sought
by police for involvement in the murder of a soldier several years ago.
<P>
In other news from Isreal ... Two Isreali border policemen are safe
after being kidnapped by five Palestinian gunmen on Wednesday night.
The two hostages were freed after Isreali Prime Minister Shimon Peres
and PLO chief Yassar Arafat interceded in negotiations on their behalf.
The tense hostage drama lasted about three hours and was said to be the
first real test of Isreali-PLO cooperation.
<P>
The drama began at about 8:00 p.m. on Wednesday when six Isreali
plainclothes agents drove a van into the West Bank village of Qabatiya.
There, they spotted the leader of the small Palestianian Black Panther
terrorist group, Samir Zakarneh.  Zakarneh was on Isreal's Most Wanted
List.  When Zakarneh spotted the Isreali agents, he fled into a nearby
coffee shop that had about 30 patrons inside.  A tense hostage drama
ensued.  Additional Isreali personnel responded to the scene.  When
the suspect refused to surrender to Isreali authorities, IDF personnel
threw one stun grenade into the coffee shop and another into a crowd of
several angry Palestianian villagers.
<P>
While the Qabatiya standoff continued, at about 10:00 p.m. co-horts of
Zakarneh kidnapped two Isreali border policemen who were outside a
police station in the town of Jenin.  The two Isreali hostages were
taken to a nearby Palestinian refugee camp and were ordered to call
the IDF and demand that the Isrealis let Zakarneh go and withdraw
from the village.  After three hours of negotiations, in which Peres
and Arafat oversaw, the two Isreali hostages were released and
Zakarneh was handed over to Palestinian police.  The five kidnappers
were also arrested by PLO police.
<P>
<HR>
<H4>Lebanon...</H4>
<BR>
Moslem terrorist guerrillas shelled an IDF outpost in south Lebanon
on Thursday.  Two Isreali soldiers were reported to had been wounded.
The guerrillas attacked the outpost, located in the central sector of 
the security zone, with mortar fire.
<P>
A few hours later, the IDF retaliated to the mortar attack when four
Isreali warplanes fired eight rockets into hills that are used by
pro-Iranian Hizbollah terrorist guerrillas.
<P>
<HR>
Belgium...
<BR>
<H4>NATO PLANNERS WORK ON BOSNIA OPERATION</H4>
<BR>
   JOHN FRASER
<BR>
   BRUSSELS
<BR>
NATO planners are working on the alliance's most ambitions
operation to date, securing the peace in Bosnia. If all proceeds
smoothly, a 60,000 member NATO force could be in place by
Christmas.
<P>
Several political moves must take place before the NATO
operation can begin.  The agreement reached Tuesday must be 
confirmed and ratified by all the parties involved, and Bosnian Serb 
reservations need to be overcome. President Clinton needs to settle 
his disagreements with Congress about U.S. participation in the
operation.
<P>
With the United States providing a third of the force of
60-thousand, European allies have made it clear that the
operation cannot easily proceed without the United States. And
finally, NATO will need an international invitation, issued by
the United Nations, before it agrees to go ahead.
<P>
However, the assumption is that all these hurdles can be
overcome. So alliance military planners are hard at work
preparing for the most daunting challenge in NATO history.
<P>
Already, communications systems have been set up, and a team
of two-thousand planners is moving into Bosnia to work on
logistics. The alliance is in close touch with non-NATO nations,
particularly Russia, which also will be involved in the Bosnian
operation. Political command procedures will have to be worked
out with Moscow, although there has been a recent breakthrough in
agreeing on the military arrangements.
<P>
Details of the operation will be discussed by NATO defense
ministers, who meet next week in Brussels. In London early in
December there will then be a conference of the 40 nations that
will be involved in the Bosnian operation.
<P>
Most of the forces for the new operation will have to be sent
into Bosnia, although some will undertake logistics duties from
bases in Croatia. Meanwhile, some of the forces already there,
who have been helping with the humanitarian operations, will stay
on. They will be transferred from United Nations to NATO command.
<P>
The aim of the Bosnian mission is simple, to ensure a smooth
transition to peace, and to assist with the setting up of the new
Bosnian state. This will be a unified entity, with two
sub-divisions. Part of the territory goes to the Serbs, with the
rest falling under Muslim and Croat authority.
<P>
There will be a central government structure, based in
Sarajevo, and it is hoped that elections can be held as soon as
is practicable. NATO is planning to deploy its forces in Bosnia
for one year, after which it is hoped the country will have been
returned to comparative normality.
<P>
In the meantime, NATO troops will secure the frontiers between
the two sections of the new Bosnia, and try to ensure that
disagreements do not escalate into conflict. It is a mammoth
task, which will provide an answer to the question which was
asked at the end of the cold war, does NATO still have a role in
the new world order, now that its former enemies have become its
friends.
<P>
Inside NATO, there is no doubt of the challenges ahead, and
that if why the search for a new secretary general for the
alliance has taken on new urgency. That post has been vacant
since the resignation of previous incumbent Willy Claes, who was
forced to leave after the Belgian parliament voted that he could
be indicted on corruption charges.
<P>
So far, European members of NATO have not been able to agree
with the Americans on a choice of secretary general. NATO
officials hope the challenges lying ahead in Bosnia will lead to
greater convergence of views among the allies.
<P>
:: Produced by INEWS ::
<P>
<HR>
<H4>Washington, D.C...</H4>
<BR>
Officials at the Pentagon have voiced concern about several hundred
non-Bosnian Muslim fighters who are apparently based near Tuzla, where
troops from the United States will be based.  The Pentagon regards
these Muslim fighters as "hard-core terrorists."  Intelligence estimates
that there are "a couple thousand" of these terrorists in Bosnia that
have come from Algeria, Iran, Libya and Pakistan.  These terrorists
have fought against Serbs.
<P>
The military officials are concerned about the threat that is posed by
groups of religious zealots, as well as other hazards such as: rouge
paramilitary groups (mercenaries), land mines, bad roads and weather.
<P>
<HR>

