<HEAD>
<TITLE>Iraqi Command Council Offers Plan</TITLE>
<!-- Comment Here -->
</HEAD>
<BODY>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE: 02-15-91-13:00 HRS. CST
<BR>
<H3>IRAQ REVOLUTIONARY COMMAND COUNCIL CALLS FOR PEACE</H3>
<BR>
Chicago, IL.  According to numerous reports, Iraq's leading
command council announced it's agreement to United Nation's
Resolution #660, which calls for a withdrawal from Kuwait.
No direct statements were issued, however, by President
Saddam Hussein.
<P>

Iraq demanded that the following conditions be implemented
prior to their compliance with the U.N. resolutions:
<P>
<UL>
<LI>* The U.N. Security Council cancel all other resolutions in
  regard to Iraq that have been issued since the August 2nd
  invasion of Kuwait
<LI>* The U.S. and Allies repair all of the Iraqi damage caused
  by the conflict at Allied expense.
<LI>* Iraq's land and sea rights and territorial integrity must
  be maintained.
<LI>* No negative consequences must be imposed on Iraq for their
  invasion of Kuwait
<LI>* All "foreign military presence" must be removed from the
  Gulf area
<LI>* Eighty (80) Billion dollars in Iraqi debts to various
  sources and nations must be cancelled
<LI>* Iraq and other Islamic nations (i.e. Iran) must be involved
  in the political settlement of the boundries of Kuwait
<LI>* Israel must withdraw from "Palestine and other occupied
  territories".
<LI>* Syrian forces must withdrw from Lebanon.
</UL>
<P>
At first euphoric about a negotiated settlement, American
officials became less enthusiastic as the details of the
Iraqi initiative were released.  President Bush and his staff
reviewed the stipulations for the Iraqi withdrawal, and after
deliberation, labelled the proposal a "cruel hoax".  Senator
Paul Simon of Illinois, stated that he hoped that the effort
for peace was genuine, but that he feared that it "may be
another ploy" in the Iraqi propaganda campaign. Military and
intellegence analysts hypothesized that the Iraqi offer was a
secondary gambit to the Iraqi media campaign, launched after
Thursday's bombing of an alleged "civilian bomb-shelter".
<P>
Coalition military forces, after review and cosultation
regarding the "peace plan", declared that the air-war would
continue as before.  Continued reports of Allied convoy
movements towards the Kuwaiti border would seem to indicate
an acceleration of the date of the ground offensive.  The
newly deployed American 3rd Armored Division is reported to
have received a bulk of it's heavy equipment and is
proceeding toward the front lines.  Constant small unit
probes are being conducted to ascertain the actual nature of
the dug-in enemy's positions.
<P>
(c) Emergency Response and Research Institute, 1991, All rights reserved.
<P>
