<head>
<title>L.A. Fire Kills 9, 40 Hurt</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE-EMERGENCYNET NEWS SRV.-05/04/93-1330CDT </p>
<p><font size=5><strong>NINE DEAD, FORTY INJURED<br>
IN L.A. APARTMENT COMPLEX FIRE</strong></font></p>
<p><strong>By: Clark Staten, EMT-P </strong></p>
<p>Los Angeles - A fire of questionable origin roared through a three-story apartment complex in Los Angeles 
yesterday. In it's wake, seven children and two pregnant woman are dead and dozens more being treated in several 
area hospitals. The fire, which broke out at approximately 4:30p.m. PDT, also left four others in extremely critical 
condition. </p>
<p>Fire Chief Donald Manning said that the fire began on the second floor of a forty (40) unit apartment building in the 
Westlake section of L.A.. Manning said that the building lacked working smoke detectors and that the fire doors, 
used to prevent the spread of flames and smoke from one section of the building to another, were propped open. 
Reportedly, the open fire doors allowed the smoke and super-heated gases to move rapidly through the hallway and 
probably contributed to the high death toll. </p>
<p>According to fire department sources, the first arriving firefighters were faced with a heavy smoke condition and 
people jumping from the second and third story windows. Paramedics quickly established a traige area at the front of 
the building and several were seen performing cardio- pulmonary resuscitation on children as they were rescued from 
the smoky recesses of the stricken building. Other paramedics put oxygen masks on the faces of dozens of smoke- 
inhalation victims that were carried or stumbled out onto the sidewalk. Several of the victims were said to have been 
found unconscious and &quot;stacked-up&quot; in one particularly long hallway that ran the length of the building. </p>
<p>One of the fire's victims was rushed to nearby Good Samaritan Hospital, were a premature infant was delivered in an 
attempt to save it and the mother's life. A hospital spokesperson said that the baby was in critical condition, and that 
the baby's prognosis is uncertain. Both fetuses of two other pregnant women, that were transported to the hospital, 
also died as a result of the fire. Their mothers succumbed to smoke-inhalation injuries as well. A total of twenty-four 
people were taken to the hospital by L.A. City Fire Department paramedics. Twenty others were reportedly treated 
at the scene. </p>
<p>The cause of the fire is still under investigation, according to fire department spokesman Michael Little. Little said that 
a total of sixteen apartments were destroyed by the fire, and that there was no evidence of working smoke detectors. 
He said that the fire was declared under control within an hour of it's inception, but not before the smoke and flames 
took their toll.  </p>
<p>(c) EmergencyNet NEWS Service, 1993, All rights Reserved.<br>
Emergency Response &amp; Research Institute <br>
5656 N. Moody St., Chicago, IL 60646 <br>
(312) 631-3774 - Voice/Messages <br>
(312) 631-4703 - FAX <br>
(312) 631-3467 - Computer/Modem-EMERGENCY BBS-28,8000bps-24hrs. </p>
</body>

