</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Rabin Security Lax?</TITLE>
<!-- Comment Here -->
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><IMG SRC="/RUGER.GIF">
<HR>
<H3>QUESTIONS RAISED ABOUT RABIN'S SECURITY...</H3>
<BR>
By Steve Macko
<BR>
One of the things that Israelis have taken pride in is the efficiency
of their security services.  Known throughout the world as being one of,
if not the, best.  In fact, no country emphasizes security as much as 
Israel.  Some questions have been raised and more are certain to be 
forthcoming about how a right-wing gunman could get within feet of the 
Prime Minister and be able to fire off three shots.  One senior Israeli
security official said, "This is a big blow for the Shabak."  The senior  
security official was referring to the renown Shin Bet, whose mission
is the internal security of Israel.  Shin Bet has a world reputation
for providing excellent security for its leaders and in preventing
terrorist attacks.  Their methods and tactics are textbook examples
for many security agencies in the world.
<P>
The Shin Bet has a special division that handles the security for the
prime minister and for other senior government officials.  This was the
first time that Shin Bet has ever lost a charge.  The unnamed senior
security official said, "There were obviously a lot of mistakes.  There's
going to be a big investigation."  After Rabin left the podium of the
huge peace rally in Tel Aviv on Saturday night and was moving toward
his car, the assassin fired three shots at him.  Rabin was struck twice
and the head of his security detail was reportedly hit in the shoulder.
It is being reported that the murderer, 25-year-old Yigal Amir, used a
9mm Beretta handgun.
<P>
A look back at the television tapes of the peace rally showed that
Rabin was being protected by just two bodyguards.  Witnesses said that
Amir emerged from a passageway at the back of a stage as the prime
minister was only a few steps from his armored car.
<P>
It is being reported that Rabin's security detail apparently mistook
Amir to be a VIP driver and this allowed the assassin to get close
enough to fire his deadly shots.
<P>
According to the Shin Bet's profile for a potential attacker, Yigal
Amir almost fit perfectly -- a fringe activist with no record of
previous violent bahavior.
<P>
A number of questions will be asked in the coming days.  Among them
are: How was an armed man allowed anywhere near the prime minister?
Why were certain standard security procedures not followed?  Why was
the prime minister not wearing a bullet-proof vest, which probably
would had saved his life?   Unfortunately, bullet-proof vests have
become the standard attire of many world leaders since the attempted
assassination attempts on U.S. President Ronald Reagan and 
Pope John Paul II.
<P>
One of the answers to the questions could be in the psychology of the
security detail.  The bodyguards may have been looking for an attack
coming from an Arab and not a Jew.  If this is true, then there was most 
certainly a breakdown in the evaluation of risk assessment.  This is 
because of the political turmoil that has been erupting in Israel during 
the past several months.  There has been physical attacks upon other
government officials in the past few months.  Including the Police
Minister being kicked by a Jewish protester.  Other recent physical 
attacks on Israeli government officials have included: the Environment
Minister's car being forced off a highway, the Education Minister was
punched in the stomach by an extremist, and the Housing Minister was
trapped by an angry crowd.  So, on a whole, the security detail should 
have realized that an attack by an Israeli was possible given the 
political climate in the country.
<P>
An author and expert on intelligence, Yossi Melman, said that the
security was "a total failure because the handwriting has been on the
wall for the past month."
<P>
Even though Israel is or was surrounded by enemies of the state,
politicians were always easily accessible to crowds of citizens and
politicians think of nothing when plunging into crowds to shake hands.
Something that is long gone from the American political scene, to a
great extent.
<P>
It has been reported that the prime minister's security detail had
recently been enlarged from its normal two or three bodyguards, which,
if true, is astonishing at such a low number.  The Mayor of Chicago
and the Governor of Illinois have larger security details than two
or three bodyguards and we will not even broach the subject of the
massive security detail of the President of the United States.
<P>
The former deputy head of the Shin Bet, Gideon Ezrach, said that when
Rabin had recently visited the town of Nablus on the West Bank, the
security detail was "more psychologically alert" then when they were
in Tel Aviv.  Ezrach also said, "I also think that we all did not
believe that such a thing could happen."  In Nablus, the security
detail was alert and focused on any threat that could come from
Palestinian militants.  Especially since Islamic extremists who are
very angry over the recent killing of Fathi Shakaki, the leader of the
Islamic Jihad, in Malta.
<P>
What must also be looked at is Rabin's attitude toward his own security.
In recent months, it was reported that the prime minister had been
heckled at and there were signs of hostility toward him by right-wingers
and some Jewish settlers.  But as Rabin, himself, recently said, "I am
concerned about the overall outlook but not on a personal basis."
<P>
One official said that the prime minister refused to wear a bullet-proof
vest.  Yossi Melman said that Shin Bet should have insisted that Rabin
wear one.  But a political professor at Hebrew University, Ehud Sprinzak,
said that Rabin would had refused in any case.  Sprinzak said, "We are
talking about a very old soldier who went through all kinds of dangers
in his life.  He did not consider an assassination a serious danger."
<P>
It is being reported that during the peace rally a journalist turned
to the prime minister's wife and asked her if Rabin was wearing a
bullet-proof vest.  Leah Rabin turned to the journalist in astonishment
and replied, "Why all of a sudden a protective vest?  Have you gone
crazy?  What are we ... in Africa?"  The journalist answered the prime
minister's wife saying that in light of recent threats, was she not
afraid that some lunatic would rush up and shoot Rabin?  Again, in
utter astonishment, Leah Rabin replied, 'Why all of a sudden protection?
What sort of protection?  That's ludicrous.  I don't understand the ideas 
you journalists have."
<P>
That exchange between the prime minister's wife and the journalist
tells a great deal. If one were to study the history of assassinations, as 
is taught to U.S. Secret Service agents, one would find some similarities
in the attitude of security between Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin and
President John F. Kennedy.  It can be quite expected that the attitude 
of Rabin's successor toward his personal security will be different and 
there is talk that the next prime minister may not have much to say about 
how his security is handled, which assuredly will be enlarged.
<P>
(c) Emergency Response & Research Institute, 1995, All rights reserved.
<BR>
