<html>

<head>
<title>FEMA Final Situation Report - Bertha</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p><font color="#0000FF"><font size=5>FEMA FINAL SITUATION REPORT</font><font size=2> </font><font size=5>--Hurricane Bertha</font></font><br>
Reporting Period: from <font color="#FF0000">7 a.m., July 12, 1996 to 7 a.m. July 13, 1996</font> <br>
(All times not otherwise stated are Eastern Daylight Times)<br>
<br>
<font color="#0000FF"><strong>BACKGROUND:</strong></font><strong> </strong>The National Weather Service Office in Wilmington, NC, indicated that the center of 
Hurricane Bertha made landfall at approximately 4:45 p.m. Eastern Daylight Time (EDT) at Wrightsville Beach, 
about five miles east of Wilmington, NC. Hurricane force winds of 105 mph impacted the area from Cape Fear 
to New River Inlet, including Surf City. At 3:00 am EDT, the center of now Tropical Storm Bertha was located 
near latitude 36.7 north and longitude 77.0 west or about 45 miles west-southwest of Norfolk, Virginia. 
Maximum sustained winds have diminished to near 65 mph mainly in squalls over the coastal waters. Bertha is 
moving toward the north-northeast at about 18 mph. This motion is expected to bring the center of Bertha near 
the southern Chesapeake Bay of Virginia early this morning. Continued weakening is expected today as Bertha 
travels over land. Tropical storm force winds extend outward up to 230 miles mainly to the east of the center.<br>
<br>
<br>
<font color="#0000FF">CURRENT SITUATION</font>: The National Emergency Response Team (ERT-N) Red Team has been ordered to 
stand down from an alert status. The alert notification was first issued 7/9/96.<br>
<br>
The North Carolina Division of Emergency Management estimates 250,000 people have evacuated. South 
Carolina officials estimate 500,000 of their citizens have left their homes. The Federal Highway Administration 
(FHA) reports that evacuations have progressed smoothly.<br>
<br>
The ERT-A on station in Columbia, SC, reports that National Guard helicopters will carry Preliminary Damage 
Assessment Teams (PDA) into storm-damaged South Carolina communities Saturday morning, July 13.<br>
<br>
The National Flood Insurance Program (NFIP), administered by FEMA, shows 42,529 flood insurance 
policies in force in North Carolina and 87,152 in South Carolina. NFIP officials have asked the underwriting 
associations in both States to put a single-adjuster program into effect, so that a single insurance adjuster can 
visit a property and verify both wind damage and flood damage.<br>
<br>
United States Virgin Islands (USVI) Disaster Field Office (DFO) personnel: FEMA employees - 11; DAE 
reservists - 35; Local hires - 0; Other Federal agencies - 12. There are two Recovery Centers on St. Thomas, 
one on St. John, and one on St. Croix.<br>
<br>
<font color="#0000FF">CASUALTIES</font>: Six storm related injuries were reported at the Camp LeJeune Marine Base, two of whom 
remained hospitalized Friday.<br>
<br>
<font color="#0000FF">WEATHER FORECAST</font>: Bertha has been downgraded to a tropical storm and has prompted the issuance of 
tropical storm warnings from the North Carolina-Virginia border to Rhode Island. Coastal storm surge flooding 
of 3 to 5 feet above normal tide is expected in areas of onshore winds to the east of the center. In addition, 
battering waves will occur on top of the storm surge. The estimated minimum central pressure is 994 Mb at 
29.35 inches. There is the possibility of isolated tornadoes along the path of Bertha. Rainfall totals of 4 to 6 
inches with the possibility of flash floods are expected along the path of Bertha.<br>
<br>
<font color="#0000FF"><strong>SEVERITY OF IMPACT ON POLITICAL JURISDICTIONS</strong></font>:<br>
<br>
<font color="#FF0000">North Carolina:</font> Significant damage along the coastal and sound areas in the Wilmington, NC, area and 
northward. Heavy flooding along the coastal and near inland areas of the State. The North Carolina Division of 
Emergency Management estimates 250,000 people evacuated ahead of the hurricane. Estimates are 186,000 
customers are without power or phone service. Damage reports by county are:<br>
<br>
Bladen County - power outages Simpson County - power outages Pender County - power outages Duplin 
County - power outages Onslow County - power outages and trees down Brunswick County - trees and 
power lines down Baldhead Island - damages to power lines, trees, and structures Southport - damages to 
power lines, trees, and structures New Hanover County - multiple power outages and erosion damage Carolina 
and Wrightsville Beaches - major erosion Kure Beach - heavy structural damage and pier destroyed Surf City - 
pier partially destroyed There is an unconfirmed report that the Sand Hotel has washed into the ocean. Carteret 
County - trees and power lines down Wake County - several State Fair buildings windows damaged<br>
<br>
All sirens associated with the Brunswick Nuclear Plant are inoperable. Two sirens are physically down and the 
other 32 are down due to power outages.<br>
<br>
<font color="#FF0000">South Carolina: </font>South Carolina suffered relatively light damage except for the counties of Horry and 
Georgetown. These two counties suffered wind, flooding, and power outages including power lines down and 
roofs damaged. A Preliminary Damage Assessment (PDA) is scheduled to begin for these two counties on 
Saturday morning.<br>
<br>
<font color="#FF0000">Delaware:</font> Full Emergency Operations Center (EOC) activation began at 8:00 am, July 12, 1996. Delaware 
Emergency Management Agency (DEMA) continues to coordinate with local jurisdictions and has activated the 
Emergency Support Functions (ESFs). Several local jurisdictions have activated their own EOCs. DEMA is 
sending 200 sand bags to New Castle County. An evacuation is underway in the Sussex County beach area. 
Evacuations for all tent campers in State Parks were ordered and should be nearly complete. No shelters have 
been opened. <br>
<br>
<font color="#FF0000">District of Columbia: </font>The DC EOC has been activated and will continue with Communications Watch status 
overnight. DC has been placed under a flash flood watch. Public Works has been notified to clean water catch 
basins and for potential tree removal.<br>
<br>
<font color="#FF0000">Maryland:</font> Maryland Emergency Management Agency remains in limited activation. No shelters have been 
opened. Governor Parris Glendening is warning coastal areas of the possibility of strong winds, rain, and storm 
surge in coastal areas around Ocean City from 10:00 am Saturday until 2:00 p.m. <br>
<br>
<font color="#FF0000">Virginia: </font>Norfolk County has activated its EOC. A State of Emergency still exists by order of Governor Allen. 
The National Guard has been activated. Eight shelters have been opened. Virginia Beach has declared a State 
of Emergency and is closing beaches until Bertha has passed. There has been substantial flooding along the 
coastal and near inland areas of Virginia.<br>
<br>
<font color="#FF0000">Road/Transportation Status:</font> Airports: Myrtle Beach Airport is closed. All other airports and associated facilities 
in the threatened area are open and at readiness level Charlie, which is the highest level of pre-disaster 
preparedness.<br>
<br>
<font color="#FF0000">Railways: </font>AMTRAK has curtailed service on a number of trains that travel through North and South Carolina. 
No alternate transportation is being provided, as effects are expected to be brief. Freight railroad operations are 
not yet affected as of 9:44 a.m. on July 12.<br>
<br>
<font color="#0000FF"><strong>STATUS OF DECLARATION: </strong></font>There have been no requests for Federal Assistance from the affected 
coastal States. The President declared a major disaster declaration for the USVI 7/11/96 (DR-1126-VI).<br>
<br>
<font color="#0000FF">STATUS OF FEDERAL OPERATIONS:</font><br>
<br>
<font color="#0000FF">INFORMATION AND PLANNING SECTION: Fully operational.</font><br>
<br>
<font color="#0000FF">OPERATIONS SECTION:</font><br>
<br>
<font color="#0000FF">OPERATIONS SUPPORT BRANCH:</font><br>
<br>
ESF #1 (<font color="#FF0000">Transportation)</font>:The Department of Transportation The Coast Guard placed North Carolina and 
Virginia in Condition 1, their highest alert condition, which indicates final preparations for the storm have been 
made. All operational Coast Guard aircraft normally stationed at Elizabeth City, NC, were relocated pending 
the passage of the storm. Several major cutters are anchored in the Chesapeake Bay and small boats have been 
lashed down on shore. All units are ready to conduct operations once the storm has passed. The Coast Guard 
is conducting port surveys and is preparing to conduct search and rescue operations.<br>
<br>
Virginia officials are considering closing several area bridges and tunnels including the Chesapeake Bay Bridge 
Tunnel, Hampton Roads Bridge Tunnel (I-64), Monitor and Merrimac Bridge Tunnel, and the Downtown and 
Midtown Tunnels (I-264) due to tidal surges.<br>
<br>
.ESF #7 (<font color="#FF0000">Resource Support</font>): General Services Administration (GSA) personnel have been instructed by 
Regional Operations Center (ROC) staff to continue to identify potential Disaster Field Office (DFO) locations 
between Richmond and Norfolk, VA. Sourcing of all necessary equipment and supplies continues.<br>
<br>
<font color="#0000FF">INFRASTRUCTURE SUPPORT BRANCH:</font><br>
<br>
ESF #3 (<font color="#FF0000">Public Works and Engineering</font>): HQ United States Army Corps of Engineers (USACE) reports their 
Emergency Operations Center remains at Level II activation. The EOC is maintaining coordination with FEMA, 
the Director of Military Support (DOMS), and subordinate elements.<br>
<br>
USACE South Atlantic Division reports the Charleston and Wilmington Districts are running 24-hour operation 
under their hurricane plans. The three other districts (Mobile, Savannah, Jacksonville) remain in a support role. 
USACE has prepared 54 generators for deployment to potential disaster sites in Region IV.<br>
<br>
USACE Jacksonville District has received three missions from FEMA for the Virgin Islands to include 
temporary roofing, sonar profiles of waterway channels and Damage Survey Report writers. They are also 
coordinating with FEMA and Department of Transportation (DOT) to ship emergency generators.<br>
<br>
Prime Power teams have deployed to NC. Additional Prime Power teams have been identified and are ready to 
be deployed to SC and VA if needed.<br>
<br>
ESF #12 (<font color="#FF0000">Energy</font>): The General Electric Nuclear Energy Facility in Wilmington, NC, which is a Nuclear 
Regulatory Commission (NRC) licensee facility, has declared an alert. The commercial fuel fabrication plant shut 
down all processes on July 11, 1996. This shutdown is a standard NRC licensing condition. The Brunswick 
(NC), Nuclear Power Plants 1 and 2 are in cold shut down. The Surry (VA) Nuclear Power Plants 1 and 2 are 
still operational and may not need to be shut down due to their power water reactor design.<br>
<br>
<font color="#0000FF">HUMAN SERVICES BRANCH:</font><br>
<br>
ESF #6 (<font color="#FF0000">Mass Care)</font>: Agencies providing mass care in NC are the American Red Cross (ARC) and the 
Salvation Army. The ARC is housing over 5000 persons in 50 emergency shelters in North Carolina. The ARC 
has served about 47,500 meals to evacuees and emergency workers.<br>
<br>
South Carolina: Georgetown and Horry Councils on Aging have made contact with local emergency 
management offices to coordinate assistance with transportation of special needs populations. The Salvation 
Army has moved 21 mobile feeding units into North and South Carolina staging areas.<br>
<br>
ESF #11 (<font color="#FF0000">Food</font>): Officials from the Virgin Islands' Department of Human Services have not reached a decision 
regarding a request to implement the Disaster Food Stamp Program. Information gathering continues.<br>
<br>
Region IV: The Food and Consumer Service (FCS) staff have been deployed to staff the ROCs to work with 
State agencies. FCS continues to work with State agencies and other Federal agencies to gather information 
that will enable a prompt food assistance response to the disaster victims.<br>
<br>
Donations: The North Carolina State Donations Coordinator and the voluntary agency community continue to 
collaborate in the task of identifying warehouse space and a site for a Donations Resource Staging Area.<br>
<br>
For offers of goods and volunteer services:<br>
<br>
ADVENTIST COMMUNITY SERVICES For offers of goods and volunteer services.<br>
<br>
AMERICAN RED CROSS For bulk offers of goods.<br>
<br>
<font color="#FF0000"><strong>EMERGENCY SERVICES BRANCH:</strong></font><br>
<br>
ESF #4 (<font color="#FF0000">Firefighting</font>): The United States Forest Service Incident Management Team is on station at Fort Bragg, 
NC, to manage the reception and distribution of relief supplies. Pat O ESF #8 (Health and Medical): As of 7 
p.m. July 11, four signed mission assignments from FEMA have been received. 1) To support the ERT-A 
activity in the U.S. Virgin Islands; 2) To provide technical support and manage ESF #8 activities in Virginia; 3) 
To provide support to the ROC/DFO/EST and ERT-A deployment and reimbursement for expenses in Puerto 
Rico; and 4) ESF #8 activities in North Carolina.<br>
<br>
United States Public Health Service (<font color="#FF0000">USPHS</font>) HQ EOC is staffed and <font color="#FF0000">on standby</font>. The Veterans 
Administration Six Disaster Medical Assistance Teams (DMATs) are on stand-by alert for a coastal response.<br>
<br>
ESF #10 (<font color="#FF0000">Hazardous Materials</font>): Environmental Protection Agency (EPA): Region IV and III have been in daily 
communication. Teams are on station in the affected areas, awaiting Saturday<br>
<br>
<font color="#008000">DEPARTMENT OF DEFENSE (DOD)/DEFENSE COORDINATING ELEMENT: </font>DOD has established a 
primary Mobilization Center at Fort Bragg, NC, to serve as a receiving/staging area for disaster supplies, 
equipment and vehicles. Supplies will be transported through Pope Air Force Base, adjacent to Fort Bragg. 
Army helicopters will be available. An alternative mobilization center is in readiness at Fort Gordon, GA.<br>
<br>
<font color="#0000FF">MITIGATION: </font>Ten Region IV Disaster Assistance Employees (DAEs) have been placed on standby for 
possible deployment to participate in Preliminary Disaster Assessment (PDA) Teams in North and South 
Carolina. The Hazard Mitigation Technical Assistance Program (HMTAP) contractor, Woodward-Clyde, Inc., 
has been alerted for possible activation. Region IV Mitigation staff members are also on standby to serve as 
liaisons to the ERT-A Teams.<br>
<br>
<font color="#0000FF">CONGRESSIONAL AND GOVERNMENT LIAISON:</font> The CLO/PIO responded to an inquiry from the 
Office of Senator Hollings of South Carolina, regarding contacts within his State, and coordinated with the 
ERT-A CLO in South Carolina for contacts with the South Carolina congressional delegation.<br>
<br>
<font color="#0000FF">EMERGENCY INFORMATION AND MEDIA AFFAIRS: </font>The Emergency Information and Media Affairs 
(EIMA) conducted a live 10-minute interview on Hurricane Bertha with the 85-city Talk Radio News Network, 
and several live interviews with WTOP All News Radio. The evening EST Director was interviewed by WUSA 
Channel 9 and on WJLA Channel 7. FEMAbriefings, feeds, and support to the numerous news crews in 
attendance including CNN, AP, C-SPAN, NBC, CBS, FOX, WUSA-TV and Reuters.<br>
<br>
<font color="#0000FF">SMALL BUSINESS ADMINISTRATION (SBA): </font>The agency has deployed an advance team to the USVI, 
coordinating efforts with FEMA to set up recovery centers. SBA will be represented on today<br>
<br>
<br>
Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) Office of Emergency Information &amp; Public Affairs --- 
Washington, D.C.<br>
