<head>
<title>FEMA Update #3; Hurricane Bertha</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p><font color="#0000FF"><font size=6>Hurricane Bertha Update 3</font></font><br>
<br>
The situation in brief as of <font color="#FF0000">6:00 p.m. Tuesday, July 9:</font><br>
<br>
The interagency Emergency Support Team (EST) remains on 24-hour duty at Federal Emergency Management 
Agency (FEMA) headquarters in Washington, working with emergency response personnel in the field to 
deploy necessary resources to the Virgin Islands and continuing contingency planning for a possible East Coast 
landfall by Hurricane Bertha. The EST, led by FEMA, coordinates all federal disaster response and recovery 
efforts. <br>
<br>
FEMA's national Emergency Response Team (Red), remains on alert for possible deployment on the East 
Coast. It is one of three 100-plus-member teams available for deployment to a catastrophic disaster when 
FEMA's regional emergency response teams are committed to disaster operations within their own jurisdictions. <br>
<br>
<font color="#FF0000">FEMA's Field (damage) Assessment Team in the U.S. Virgin Islands was demobilized and departed St. 
Thomas at 11:00 a.m. this morning. It will be staged in Thomasville, Ga., in readiness for a possible East Coast 
response.</font><br>
<br>
Today FEMA officials joined U.S.V.I Governor Roy Schneider and Maj. Gen. Rudolfo Francis, commander of 
the U.S.V.I. National Guard, for an aerial inspection of hurricane damage on the islands. They reported homes 
repaired following Hurricane Marilyn had kept their roofs, but those whose owners had delayed making repairs 
had lost their protective plastic tarps and suffered further damage from this storm.<br>
<br>
Electric power has been fully restored on St. John and St. Croix and is steadily being restored on St. Thomas. 
Water and sewage systems are becoming operational as the power is restored.<br>
<br>
Federal disaster officials on St. Thomas confirmed that there is an 8-week supply of food in the U.S.V.I., much 
of it in the form of military AMeals, Ready to Eat@ shipped to the islands during the Hurricane Marilyn 
response last year.<br>
<br>
Puerto Rico Gov. Pedro Rosello and FEMA officials today conducted a flyover inspection of damaged areas of 
that island, reporting that roads are clear from the eastern end of the island to San Juan. <font color="#FF0000">The Governor earlier 
told FEMA Director James Lee Witt that Puerto Rico's own resources are sufficient to meet its needs from this 
storm.</font> <br>
<br>
Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) Office of Emergency Information &amp; Public Affairs --- 
Washington, D.C.<br>
<br>
Information Available 24 hours a day . . . <br>
... on the World Wide Web: <a href="http://www.fema.gov"><strong>http://www.fema.gov</strong></a><br>
... via fax-on-demand: phone in the U.S.A. (202) 646-FEMA (646-3362)<br>
... via digital audio for broadcasters &amp; print: contact eipa@fema.gov<br>
</p>
<p><a href="/disaster.htm"><strong>Return to the ENN Disaster/Rescue Page</strong></a></p>
</body>

