<head>
<title>California Counties Declared Flood Disaster</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE-EMERGENCYNET NEWS-02/13/92-1630CST </p>
<p><font size=6>LOS ANGELES &amp; VENTURA COUNTIES 
DECLARED DISASTER AREAS </font></p>
<p>By Clark Staten </p>
<p>Los Angeles, CA - California Governor Pete Wilson today declared Los Angeles and Ventura counties 
as state disaster areas due to the third major rain storm to strike Southern California in the past four 
days. Fire, EMS, and Rescue operations are described as continuing at a &quot;frantic pace&quot;, according to a 
high-ranking Los Angeles City EMS official. </p>
<p>According to Governor Wilson, &quot;Clearly a state of immediate peril to lives and property exists...the 
damage in these areas is extreme and impossible to measure at this point in time&quot;. By 4:00 p.m. 
Wednesday, 2.07 inches of rain had fallen in Ventura, CA, further destabilizing the already satuarated 
hill sides and prompting fears of mudslides. In Los Angeles, the National Weather Service reports that 
as much as 4.00 inches of rain has fallen there in the past two days. Yesterday, the Ventura River was 
reported &quot;out of it's banks&quot; and was said to have &quot;swallowed&quot; a mobile home park. </p>
<p>According to U.S. Coast Guard officials, a Marine CH-46 Air- Sea rescue helicopter on a mission, also 
crashed into the rugged hills of Northern Ventura and one person is missing from the copter and 
presumed dead. Eight others were rescued from the crash site and were transported to the St. John's 
Regional Trauma Center, where their condition is unconfirmed at the time of this report. </p>
<p>According to Ojai, CA. Fire/Rescue officials and the Ventura County Sheriff's office, a couple was 
killed there yesterday at approximately 7:00 a.m., by a mudslide driven boulder which struck their home. 
According to a neighbor, the woman involved in this incident was pregnant and the unborn baby was 
also killed. Rescuers say that the boulder was lossened by torrential rains that have continued in that 
area for the past three days. </p>
<p>A neighbor described the sound of the mudslide as &quot;fearsome&quot; and that it sounded like &quot;thunder&quot; when it 
struck the side of the house were the people were killed. Mark Baker, the neighbor, is quoted as saying; 
&quot;There was screaming coming from the house just after the slide...then you couldn't hear anything&quot;. A 
newsman on the scene described the neighbors in the vicinity as be extremely distraught over the deaths 
of the well-liked couple. </p>
<p>Los Angeles and Ventura County fire departments and Emergency Medical Service agencies are said to 
be working at maximum capacity as the magnitude of the incident continues to become evident. 
Reportedly, Ventura County Rescue helicopters have removed more than 100 people from car and 
rooftops as the rapidly rising flood waters engulfed entire neighborhoods. </p>
<p>Rescue workers are said to be still searching the Los Angeles river near Van Nuys, CA. for the body of 
a 15 year-old boy that had fallen into the swiftly rushing water. Reportedly, Firefighters had twice 
attempted to rescue the youngster with a thrown flotation device yesterday, without success. The boy 
was tentatively identified as Adam Bischoff of that city. Another man was also reported lost in the 
Huntington Park area by Los Angeles County Fire Officials; he was last seen in the vicinity of Compton 
Blvd. and the Los Angeles River. </p>
<p>In Orange County, CA., flooding is also said to be extensive. An Orange County Fire Spokesman said, 
however, that no known loss of life has occured there. He did indicate that all available personnel were 
being utilized to help beleaguered homeowners with flooded property. Areas as far north as Kern 
County and Bakersfield, CA. were said to be evacuating residents because of fears of mudslides and 
additional flooding. </p>
<p>The California Highway Patrol says that many mudslides have struck the Pacific Coast Highway and 
Highway 101, making travel almost impassable in some parts of the area. They also admitted that the 
weather and disruptions of traffic patterns may slow the rescue efforts in some areas. The Patrol also 
reported the storm-related death of one man in a traffic accident on Interstate 5 near the town of Lepec, 
CA.. Many other canyon roads were reported completely covered by mud and debris. </p>
<p>California meteorologists are said to be predicting the possibilty of another major wave of rain and wind 
to follow the now near-record rainfalls that have recently occured. An additional Pacific Ocean storm is 
said to be forming off the California Coast. It is raining in Los Angeles at the time of this report, and it 
could continue for as much as another forty-eight hours, according to sources at the National Weather 
Service. Numerous government and emergency officials are said to be requesting &quot;real-time&quot; weather 
updates from the forecasters, out of fear of worsening conditions. </p>
<p>(c) Clark Staten, EmergencyNet NEWS Service <br>
Emergency Response &amp; Research Institute<br>
6348 N. Milwaukee Ave., Suite312, Chicago, IL 60646<br>
(312) 631-3774 - Voice/Messages <br>
(312) 631-3467 - Computer/Modem -Emergency BBS - 24Hours <br>
</p>
</body>

</html>

