<head>
<title>FEMA Situation Report #2; Hurricane Bertha</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p><font color="#FF0000"><strong>Federal Emergency Management Agency<br>
Emergency Support Team <br>
FEMA Headquarters <br>
Emergency Information and Coordination Center</strong></font><br>
<br>
<font color="#0000FF"><font size=5>SITUATION REPORT #2 HURRICANE BERTHA</font></font><br>
<br>
Reporting Period:<font color="#FF0000"> 6 p.m, EDT July 8 - 6 a.m. EDT July 9, 1996</font><br>
<br>
<font color="#0000FF"><font size=4>BACKGROUND: </font></font>At approximately 3 a.m. EDT, July 9, 1996, Hurricane Bertha became a Category III 
hurricane, with maximum sustained winds near 115 mph. Some fluctuations in strength are possible today. At 
about 8 p.m., July 8, 1996, Hurricane Bertha passed over the Virgin Islands (USVI) and moved on a path 
taking it about 70 miles north of San Juan, and 80 miles Northeast of Aguadilla, Puerto Rico (PR). It is currently 
located near Latitude 20.7 N; Longitude 68.4 W. or about 180 miles east-southeast of Turks Island. Present 
movement is toward the WNW at about 18 mph. A gradual turn towards the northwest is expected during the 
next 24-hours. Although the current forecast for Hurricane Bertha potentially threatens Florida by late 
Wednesday night or early Thursday morning, two computer models suggest the possibility of more of a 
northward turn into a possible weakness in the subtropical high pressure ridge. Thus, there is a distinct hope that 
it will recurve without making landfall on the U.S. </p>
<p><font color="#FF0000">As of 11 p.m. July 8,</font><br>
<br>
<font color="#0000FF"><font size=4>CURRENT SITUATION:</font></font><br>
HQ FEMA: FEMA's Emergency Information and Coordination Center (EICC) was activated on July 7 
followed by activation of a Level 2 Emergency Support Team (EST) at8 a.m. on July 8. Both the EICC and 
EST are operating on a 24-hour basis. A FEMA Liaison Group is activated at the National Hurricane Center. 
The Eastern Field Assessment Team (FAsT) departed Charleston AFB via USAF C141 at 3:17 a.m. EDT July 
9 and is expected to arrive St. Thomas 6:37 a.m. July 9. FEMA has alerted two additional FAsTs to prepare 
for potential response. The Urban Search and Rescue (US&amp;R) Task Force (Nebraska) and the US&amp;R 
Incident Support Team have been placed on .alert. The US Public Health Service has pre-identified four 
Disaster Medical Assistance Teams (DMATs) and one Medical Support Unit (MSU) to respond as required.<br>
<br>
Region II: Activated Level 2 Regional Operations Center (ROC) at 8 a.m. on July 7 and transitioned to Level 1 
operations at 8 a.m. on July 8. Dispatched Emergency Response Team-Advance (ERT-A) to St. Thomas on 
July 7. Requested HQ FEMA provide before and after photo reconnaissance of the USVI to distinguish 
between Bertha damage and prior hurricane damages. Region II is working through ESF #1 to arrange for 
deployment via military aircraft of ERT personnel resources to St Thomas by noon July 9. The Caribbean 
Division projects deployment of 29 Preliminary Damage Assessment (PDA) teams in Puerto Rico on Tuesday, 
July 9, to assess the situation.<br>
<br>
IRR Prepositioning: Plastic sheeting (100 X 20Ft.) 700 rolls positioned in USVI; 5,660 rolls<br>
positioned in PR. Plastic sheeting (18 X 22Ft.) 1,264 rolls positioned in PR. Water tanks<br>
(1,500 gal.) 17 positioned in USVI. Generators; 150 (10kw or less) in USVI; 126 (various<br>
capacities) in PR. Meals, Ready-to-Eat (MREs) -2,496 cases (12 meals per) in USVI; 5,760 cases<br>
in PR.<br>
<br>
Virgin Islands Pre-landfall Actions: Governor declared State of Emergency on July 7. EOCs activated on all<br>
three islands. National Guard activated. Sandbags distributed. Marine warning issued. Price freezes<br>
imposed. St. Croix: An island-wide curfew is still in effect until noon Tuesday, July 9. Power on the island<br>
is down. Water and waste are not being pumped.<br>
<br>
Virgin Islands Post-landfall Actions: Beginning damage<br>
assessments.<br>
<br>
Puerto Rico Pre-landfall Actions: EOC activated; National Guard activated; price freezes in effect. FEMA<br>
staff have predeployed to four Civil Defense zones on the islands of Culebra and Vieques. Electricity in San<br>
Juan is down as of 5:30 pm Monday, July 8. Florida Pre-landfall Actions: Preparations are underway on the<br>
U.S. mainland in Florida in the event that Bertha tracks towards the United States. The State of Florida EOC is<br>
at Level II for Dade, Broward, and Monroe Counties. The EOC will go to Level III at 7:30 a.m., July 9, when 
it will begin 24-hour operations. State ESFs 1,6,8,12,14 and 16 will activate at 8:00 a.m., Tuesday, July 9.<br>
Other ESFs will report to the State EOC at 2:00 p.m. for a briefing.<br>
<br>
<font color="#0000FF">CASUALTIES: </font><br>
Two deaths have been reported off the coast of Puerto Rico by local officials. Also, the Coast Guard is 
reported to be searching for a ship in distress off of Puerto Rico. </p>
<p><font color="#0000FF">WEATHER FORECAST: </font><br>
The government of the Bahamas has issued a hurricane warning for the central Bahamas. Hurricane warnings 
are in effect for the Turks and Caicos Islands, the southeastern and central Bahamas, and the Dominican 
Republic from Cabo Caucedo on the south coast to Monte Cristi on the north coast. A tropical storm warning 
and a hurricane watch remain in effect for the north coast of Haiti. </p>
<p><font color="#0000FF">SEVERITY OF IMPACT:</font><br>
Jurisdictions Affected: Preliminary reports from the ERT-A in the USVI indicate some damage to structures and 
grounding of watercraft on St. Thomas. Numerous homes have been damaged. Tarps placed on roofs damaged 
in last year's hurricanes have been blown off. The Governor of the USVI has instructed the public to stay 
indoors until it has been determined it is safe to go outside. Church bells, emergency sirens, and fire alarms will 
sound when it is safe to venture outside. A 12 noon to 12 noon curfew has been imposed from July 8 to July 9.<br>
<br>
The USVI Civil Defense reports light damage around the islands after passage of Hurricane Bertha<br>
<br>
<font color="#0000FF"><font size=4>Road/Transportation Status:</font></font><br>
<br>
<font color="#0000FF">Airports: The airport in St. Thomas has reopened. Barring severe damage, the other<br>
airports should be up and running as quickly as possible.</font> Some airlines have canceled flights<br>
to the islands affected by the storm. But they advised passengers to check with their airline<br>
in advance because damage might delay the flights.<br>
<br>
Other: <font color="#0000FF">All ports in Puerto Rico and the USVI have been closed to incoming traffic. </font>Vessels<br>
are departing and proceeding to sea as quickly as possible. Cruise lines diverted ships to the<br>
west and south. American Airlines and Carnival Cruise Lines say they hope to resume service<br>
</p>
<p><font color="#FF0000">July 9. STATUS OF FEDERAL OPERATIONS:</font><br>
<br>
National Hurricane Liaison Team is working in the National Hurricane Center in Coral Gables, Florida. They 
are coordinating written reports and frequent briefings on hurricane intensity, landfall potential, strength, etc.<br>
<br>
Information and Planning Section: ESF 5 began operations with a Level III or mini-EST on Sunday, July<br>
7. Staff prepared initial reports. Made contact with staff at the ROC, the ERT-A in the Virgin Islands, and<br>
the Caribbean Office. Maps of the affected areas and predicted hurricane tracks were prepared and posted. A<br>
video-conference hookup with the Hurricane Center in Coral Gables, FL, provided the FEMA senior staff,<br>
departments and agencies, and the field offices an opportunity to exchange information.<br>
<br>
Planning meetings were held Monday and will continue daily to establish EST priorities and operating priorities. 
The Information and Planning Section began daily situation reporting and the preparation of a daily briefing<br>
<br>
Logistics Section Planning for deployment of personnel<br>
to the Virgin Islands.<br>
<br>
Operations Section<br>
<br>
<font color="#008000"><font size=4>DEFENSE COORDINATING ELEMENT:</font></font><br>
<br>
DOD-DCO reports that four Emergency Preparedness Liaison Officers (three Army and one Air Force)<br>
are present in the ROC representing the DCO function and First US Army. FEMA National has<br>
initiated three Mission Assignments involving air transportation for FEMA FAsT, MATTS, and<br>
ERT-A personnel deploying to Puerto Rico and the VI. The MATTS was subsequently canceled as not<br>
needed.<br>
<br>
<font color="#008000">Operations Support Branch</font><br>
<br>
ESF #1 <font color="#008000">(Transportation)</font> ESF 1 is on a24-hour operations schedule. An ERT-A<br>
team of six is positioned in San Juan and available for ESF-1 duties. An ERT<br>
team of eight will be deployed to the DFO when directed. Air service will be<br>
resumed today. Status of harbors and port facilities is unknown at this<br>
time. FHWA is concerned with road and bridges damages should heavy rainfalls<br>
occur in Puerto Rico. ESF 1 is coordinating preliminary arrangements<br>
for movement of ERT personnel to Puerto Rico and the VI. DOT is attempting to<br>
arrange for a military aircraft to move ERT-A team from New York to St. Thomas<br>
Tuesday, July 9, at noon.<br>
<br>
ESF #7 <font color="#008000">(Resource Support): GSA Fleet Management is trying to locate 27 4x4 FEMA Excess cars for<br>
potential use.</font> Contractors are on standby and presently locating sources for various items.<br>
The balance of the Team on Puerto Rico will be moved to St. Thomas. The Federal Protective<br>
Services Division has been notified to be on standby for deployment. Coordinating the alert<br>
of two additional FAsT teams. Public Building Service personnel have been alerted for Puerto<br>
Rico and the VI. Deploying 6 INMARSAT and ADP equipment to Denton MERS. Federal buildings in<br>
Puerto Rico and VI are presently closed. Equipment and logistics packages will move to<br>
Thomasville to link up with FAsT vehicles Denton MERS is coordinating two logistics<br>
packages.<br>
<br>
<font color="#008000">Infrastructure Support Branch</font><br>
<br>
ESF #3 <font color="#008000">(Public Works and Engineering):</font><br>
ESF-03 established a work station at the<br>
ROC, FEMA Region II office. Further,<br>
the South Atlantic Division reports that<br>
254 generators are available in<br>
Jacksonville, Florida, ranging from 10 -<br>
550 KW's, which are ready to be shipped<br>
by barge. Alternative modes of<br>
transportation are being investigated<br>
with ESF-01.<br>
<br>
Virgin Islands: Presently, FEMA is in the process of issuing ESF-03 Mission Assignments for the 
pre-deployment of ERT-A, FAsT, Prime Power efforts, and the establishment of the ROC station. The ERT-A 
team is scheduled to be fully staffed by 6:30 pm tomorrow in San Juan for deployment to USVI. The Prime 
Power element is scheduled to be deployed early tomorrow morning. Additional Mission Assignments, including 
debris removal and temporary roofing, are presently being coordinated with FEMA. Field reports indicate that 
approximately 700 rolls of plastic roofing are in stock in the USVI.<br>
<br>
Puerto Rico: Presently, ESF-03 has been issued mission assignments for the pre-deployment of ERT-A, FAsT, 
Prime Power efforts, and the establishment of the ROC station. Additional mission assignments, including debris 
removal and temporary roofing, are presently being coordinated with FEMA.<br>
<br>
<br>
<font color="#008000">Human Services Branch</font><br>
<br>
ESF #6 <font color="#008000">(Mass Care):</font> ESF #6 staff have<br>
deployed to the Region II ROC and the<br>
Caribbean Division. Three additional<br>
staff are on standby for the USVI as<br>
required.<br>
<br>
In support of Mass Care activities, <font color="#008000">Red Cross has two Level-4 teams on standby. </font>One team is scheduled for 
the USVI - St. Thomas, while the other is being held for Puerto Rico or for later in the week for Florida or East 
Coast if needed.<br>
<br>
Puerto Rico: Shelters are managed by the Puerto Rico Departments of Housing and Education and supported 
by the American Red Cross. Some cots were delivered overnight.<br>
<br>
Shelters open: St. Thomas - 6<br>
St. John - 2 St. Croix - 3 Puerto Rico - 201 Number of persons sheltered (total for USVI) - 915 Number of 
persons sheltered (total for PR) - 3,065<br>
<br>
ESF #11 <font color="#008000">(Food): </font>Puerto Rico: 130,000,000 pounds of combined State and Federal food<br>
stocks are available for use in Puerto Rico. Due to expected flooding and mud slides,<br>
resupply of food to shelters from state warehouse may be a problem.<br>
<br>
U. S. Virgin Islands: The only food known to be in the USVI is the 2,496 cases (12 to a case) of MREs that 
FEMA currently has on St. Thomas. Since schools are closed for the summer, both schools and the state 
warehouses are nearly empty. Department of Education reports that they have 7 days supply of food at the 
shelters in St. Thomas. Food supplies in Puerto Rico would not be available for U.S. Virgin Islands if Puerto 
Rico is hit by the storm.<br>
<br>
If FEMA still has space at Lindberg Bay, USDA wants several bays worth of space for incoming food. If not, 
then other warehouse space will be needed to receive food as it arrives.<br>
<br>
<font color="#008000">Voluntary Organizations: Region II FEMA</font><br>
VOLAG Coordinator is stationed with the ERT-A team in San Juan, Puerto Rico and<br>
working with ESF-6. Contact has been made with the Mennonites and Church of<br>
the Brethren coordinators on St. Thomas. As soon as air travel is<br>
possible, FEMA VOLAG Coordinator will meet with them on Tuesday, July 9.<br>
<br>
Donations: ARC donations telephone numbers have been activated: For In-Kind<br>
1-800-7-IN KIND or 1-800-746-5463; for Spanish-speaking 1-800-257-7575.<br>
<br>
<font color="#FF0000">Emergency Services Branch</font><br>
<br>
ESF #4 <font color="#FF0000">(Firefighting)</font> ESF #4 has staff at the EOC. The Blue Incident Command Team is on<br>
standby to assist GSA with the operation of the receiving and distribution center.<br>
<br>
ESF #8 <font color="#FF0000">(Health and Medical)</font>: A request for minimum of 3 DMATS and 30 nurses to augment USVI medical 
has been anticipated by FEMA ERT-A leader. An anticipatory Mission Assignment request has been designed 
to include these as well as other initial needs as damage becomes apparent, disaster is declared<br>
and request is made by the Territory.<br>
<br>
A request has been made to Dept. of Veterans Affairs Operations Center in Martinsburg, WVA for staffing 
assistance for ROC and for ERT-A.<br>
<br>
ESF #9: <font color="#FF0000">One USR team is on standby in Florida</font> to cover possible impact of a hit in Florida; and one team in 
California is on standby for Caribbean response if needed.<br>
<br>
Department of Defense/Defense Coordinating Element: Request for rotary/wing support was forwarded to 
DOD for action.<br>
<br>
<font color="#0000FF">Emergency Information and Media Affairs:</font><br>
<br>
Two news releases were distributed in the morning and early evening summarizing FEMA and other federal 
agency activities in connection with Bertha.<br>
<br>
The FEMA Radio Network distributed audio &quot;sound bites&quot; with Barbara Russell on St. Thomas answering 
questions about FEMA/Federal activities and plans in the Virgin Islands. The interview was recorded as Bertha 
was beginning to affect the U.S.V.I. An advisory was faxed to news media in the V.I., P.R., Florida, as well as 
the National news media. The FEMA Radio Network is also distributing Hurricane preparedness public service 
announcements.<br>
<br>
An advisory was prepared for national news media regarding a photo opportunity Tuesday morning during the 9 
a.m. hurricane briefing in the EIDA. A media availability with Director Witt<br>
will follow the EIDA briefing; the media availability is scheduled for Rm. 401 at FEMA HQ.<br>
<br>
FEMA's World Wide Web site has been providing frequently updated Hurricane information throughout the 
weekend. On Monday, FEMA's World Wide Web site established an all-time record for accesses to the 
FEMA Website.... approximately 1,000,000 accesses occurred during an 12 hour period on Monday. This 
represents a 10,000 per cent increase over previous highs!<br>
<br>
Members of FEMA's Red Team (predesignated public affairs officers assigned to key functions in the Red 
Team Joint Information Center) have been put on alert. FEMA is coordinating with Regional Public Affairs 
Officers currently in Lead PAO training at NETC to discuss potential deployments which may be required for 
Category 2 or below events..<br>
<br>
Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) Office of Emergency Information &amp; Public Affairs --- 
Washington, D.C.<br>
<br>
Information Available 24 hours a day . . . <br>
... on the World Wide Web: <a href="http://www.fema.gov"><strong>http://www.fema.gov</strong></a><br>
... via fax-on-demand: phone in the U.S.A. (202) 646-FEMA (646-3362)<br>
... via digital audio for broadcasters &amp; print: contact eipa@fema.gov<br>
</p>
