<html>

<head>
<title>FEMA Update-Hurricane Bertha-07/11/96</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p><font color="#FF0000">Federal Emergency Management Agency <br>
Emergency Support Team <br>
FEMA Headquarters <br>
Emergency Information and Coordination Center<br>
</font><br>
<font color="#0000FF"><font size=5><strong>SITUATION REPORT #4P HURRICANE BERTHA</strong></font></font><br>
<br>
Reporting Period: <font color="#FF0000">6 a.m. EDT, July 10, 1996 to 6 a.m. EDT, July 11, 1996</font> (All times not otherwise stated are 
Eastern Daylight Times)<br>
<br>
<font color="#0000FF">BACKGROUND: </font>As of 5:00 am EDT Thursday, July 11, Hurricane Bertha was located near 28.8N, 77.0W 
or about 380 miles south of Wilmington, NC. Maximun sustained winds are near 100 mph with little change in 
strength expected through Thursday night. Bertha is expected to move toward the north-northwest near 13 
mph. A gradual turn toward the north is expected on 7/11/96. Landfall may take place sometime Friday, July 
12, near the boundary of North and South Carolina. CURRENT SITUATION:<br>
<br>
Region II: The Preliminary Damage Assessment (PDA) Teams are expected to complete their assessment of the 
United States Virgin Islands (USVI) on 7/10/96. The status of priority issues received from St. Thomas is 
summarized as follows:<br>
<br>
St. Croix St.John St. Thomas Shelters: Closed Closed 1 open/18 people<br>
<br>
Power: Fully Operational Fully Oper. Some feeders<br>
<br>
Water: Normal Water being Normal distribution gravity fed distribution<br>
<br>
Sewage Fully Fully Fully System: Operational Operational Operational<br>
<br>
Distribution of tarps will be handled by the Territory using remaining inventory from FEMA 1067-DR-VI. For 
additional needs, the source and cost information will be provided by FEMA.<br>
<br>
FEMA Emergency Support Team (EST): The FEMA EST is currently activated at Level 2 on 24-hour basis 
but will begin Level 1 operations beginning 7/11/96 day-shift. Level 1 status includes the 12 key Federal 
response agencies in addition to FEMA and, in this case, the National Weather Service.<br>
<br>
Region IV:<br>
<br>
(1)<font color="#FF0000"><font size=4> Evacuations as of 4:42 p.m., July 10, 1996:</font></font><br>
<br>
North Carolina: <font color="#FF0000">Dare County--Hatteras Island (Mandatory). </font><br>
<font color="#FF0000">Hyde County--Ocracoke Island (Mandatory).</font><br>
<br>
South Carolina <font color="#FF0000">Voluntary evacuation </font>in low lying<br>
areas of Charleston and Beufort Counties.<br>
<br>
<font color="#FF0000">Georgia Tybee Island (Mandatory).</font><br>
<br>
Florida: <font color="#FF0000">Evacuation orders have been signed for low lying areas; Barrier Islands, special facilities in Nassau, St. 
Johns, Volusia, and Brevard Counties.</font><br>
<br>
<font color="#FF0000">Evacuations orders are pending for Duval and Flagler.</font><br>
<br>
Region III &amp; IV State EOC Activations:<br>
Virginia EOC is operating a Readiness Condition 3; Florida's EOC has been<br>
activated; Georgia's EOC has been activated; North &amp; South Carolina's<br>
EOC's are monitoring the storm path and evacuating coastal areas. <br>
<br>
Alternate-Regional<br>
Operations Center (A-ROC) Status:<br>
The A-ROC is fully operational in its monitoring activities for both Hurricane Bertha and the 1996 Olympic 
Games. <br>
<br>
Regional Emergency Response Team-Advanced<br>
(ERT-A) Support: Region III will provide ERT-A support to the State of Virginia, Region VI will provide 
ERT-A support to North Carolina, Region VIII for South Carolina and Region X for Georgia should<br>
Hurricane Bertha make landfall. <br>
<br>
<font color="#0000FF">National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA):</font><br>
Kennedy Space Center (KSC) non-essential employees were released from work at 9:00 am to allow them the<br>
opportunity to prepare their homes for the storm. A ride-out crew of approx. 250 persons remain in<br>
27 &quot;hardened&quot; facilities. Space Shuttle Atlantis was rolled back from the launch pad and secured in the Vehicle 
Assembly Building at 1:00 pm. All NASA aircraft at KSC have relocated. NASA facilities at Langley Research 
Center, Hampton, VA, and Wallops Flight Facility, WallopsIsland, VA, have activated their storm crews<br>
and are preparing for potential landfall. <br>
<br>
<font color="#0000FF">CASUALTIES:</font> No change from previous report.<br>
<br>
<font color="#0000FF">WEATHER FORECAST: </font>Hurricane Bertha remains a Category II hurricane having maximum sustained winds 
near 100 mph. There is a chance that the hurricane will intensify as it moves over the warm waters of the Gulf 
Stream. Forward speed is 13 mph to the north-northwest. There is still a possibility that Hurricane Bertha could 
recurve eastward and miss the coast. However, scientific models bring the hurricane over land within 36 hours. 
Hurricane warnings are in effect from Brunswick, GA, north to Virginia. Warnings have been discontinued south 
of Brunswick, GA. A hurricane watch is in effect from Virginia and into the lower Chesapeake Bay.<br>
<br>
<font color="#0000FF">SEVERITY OF IMPACT:</font><br>
Minimal damage reported on USVI, Puerto Rico, Vieques and Culebra. ESF #10 reports water treatment 
plants and sewage treatment plants were not affected and that power has been restored. All interstate<br>
highways, airports and bridges are open on the USVI and Puerto Rico.<br>
<br>
<font color="#0000FF">Housing Status:</font><br>
<br>
<font color="#800000">St. Thomas, USVI</font><br>
Residential Housing <br>
Destroyed 33 <br>
Major Damage 237 <br>
Minor Damage 410 <br>
Inaccessible 28<br>
Miniminally affected 600<br>
<br>
<font color="#0000FF">Personal Property/Contents Only </font>(IFG Program) <br>
High Damage 216 <br>
Lot to moderate damage 119 <br>
Low damage 270<br>
<br>
Tarps Damaged or missing 293<br>
<br>
<font color="#0000FF">Schools</font><br>
Three schools on St. Thomas have been assessed<br>
with $827,000 in damages.<br>
Island of Culebra Residential Housing<br>
Destroyed 2 <br>
Major Damage 8 <br>
Minor Damage 11<br>
Miniminally affected 12<br>
<br>
<font color="#0000FF">STATUS OF FEDERAL OPERATIONS:</font><br>
<br>
<font color="#0000FF">Operations Section</font><br>
<br>
<font color="#008000">DOD/Defense Coordinating Element:</font> Region IV: There will be no execution of missions tonight; only planning 
and the identification of resources. No decisions will be made until after the 0900 hours briefing on 7/11/96.<br>
FEMA National Emergency Response Team (ERT-N) Red Team will remain on alert. The management portion 
of the team will deploy to Washington on 7/11/96 for briefings and updates.<br>
<br>
Department of Defense (DOD) will provide rotary wing support and conduct aerial assessments of the<br>
impacted areas of North and South Carolina, Georgia, and Virginia for three days. DOD will confirm that Fort<br>
Bragg will be the primary Base Support Installation (BSI) and will also identify 1 or 2 alternate BSI's<br>
west of Fort Bragg. The National Hurricane Center's (NHC) prediction indicates 60+ mph winds over Fort<br>
Bragg which may cause considerable damage to Fort Bragg and its infrastructure. Other requirements<br>
include the transport of 4-10 Disaster Medical Assistance Teams (DMATs) from CONUS locations to<br>
a location TBD, transport Urban Search and Rescue (US&amp;R) Task Force from Nebraska and transport 
Incident Support Team (IST) for location TBD. DOMS Representative verified that a Defense<br>
Coordinating Officer (DCO) and Defense Coordinating Element (DCE) Staff would meet each ERT-A at the<br>
appropriate State EOC upon deployment.<br>
<br>
<font color="#0000FF">Operations Support Branch:</font><br>
<br>
ESF #7 (Resource Support): Procurement actions will be completed on 7/10/96 for the<br>
following items to be delivered to Fort Gillem, GA:<br>
<br>
6,000 blankets, diapers (assorted sizes); flashlights with batteries; portable radios with batteries; 3,000 cots and 
comfort kits; 1,000 20x20 tarps; 900 sleeping ba gs; 600 tents (8 man); 600 individual rolls of bathroom tissue.<br>
<br>
General Services Administration (GSA) has alerted the ESF #7 elements in FEMA Regions 3, 7, 8, and 10 to 
match those regions alerted by FEMA. GSA will establish the ESF #7/GSA EOC on a 24 hour basis at 8:00 
am on Thursday, July 11, 1996.<br>
<br>
<br>
ESF #11 <font color="#0000FF">(Food): </font><br>
Region IV: Personnal from the Food and Commodity Service (FCS) Southeast Regional Office in<br>
Atlanta, Georgia, are on stand-by for deployment. The FCS Regional Office in Dallas, Texas, is on<br>
stand-by for back-up. Food supplies from Florida to New England have been inventoried and appear to be<br>
sufficient. Additional food sources have also been identified.<br>
<br>
Region II: ESF #11 reports that the major chain grocery stores in the Virgin Islands have been contacted and 
the majority of the retail food stores reopened when the curfew was lifted. The fast food businesses are 
operating.<br>
<br>
The USVI Human Services Commission will implement a new schedule for people on St. Croix to pick up their 
regular food stamps. Pick up dates are determined depending on the client's case number.<br>
<br>
<font color="#FF0000">Emergency Services Branch</font><br>
<br>
ESF #4<font color="#0000FF"> (Firefighting): </font>Region IV: ESF #4 will stage an Interagency Incident Mangement Team at<br>
Charlotte, NC when the Request for Federal Assistance (RFA) submitted by ESF #7 is approved.<br>
<br>
ESF #8 <font color="#0000FF">(Health and Medical): </font>Region II: No Federal Assistance needed in the<br>
Health and Medical field. Hospitals and clinics are fully operational.<br>
<br>
Region IV: <font color="#0000FF">Placed 3 DMAT units (OH-1; MI-1; PHS-1) and a Medical Support Unit (MSU) on the Initial 
Response Resources (IRR) list. </font>Placed 5 DMAT units (OK-1; NC-1; FL-2; NM-1; FL-1) on standby.<br>
<br>
ESF #10 <font color="#0000FF">(Hazardous Materials):</font> Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) Region 4 is communicating with 
FEMA Headquarters by conference call daily. EPA Region 2 is stepping down on the calls. Communication in 
conference calls will also include Regions 3 and 5.<br>
<br>
<font color="#0000FF">Emergency Information and Media Affairs:</font> A media advisory was issued informing media outlets of the 
availability of the FEMA Director's daily briefings via satellite uplink. Plans have been made to uplink morning 
and evening briefings from the Executive Information Display Area (EIDA) via satellite as required through 
Monday.<br>
<br>
The Office of Emergency Information and Media Affairs (EIMA) continues to respond to reporter requests and 
schedule the Director and other FEMA personnel for interviews regarding Hurricane Bertha's progress.<br>
<br>
FEMA's World Wide Web site usage continues at record pace. Today, EIMA also began distributing situation 
reports via the Internet. Nearly 2,000 subscribers receive these reports. EIMA is continuing to post National 
Weather Service advisories and GIS tracking maps. The FEMA Radio Network received more than 300 
inquires for recorded soundbites of Director Witt.<br>
<br>
Staffing plans for three potential Joint Information Centers (JIC) are being finalized with potential staff members 
on standby. Plans are also underway to establish a JIC at FEMA Headquarters.<br>
<br>
<br>
Courtesy of : Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) Office of Emergency Information &amp; Public 
Affairs --- Washington, D.C.<br>
<br>
Information Available 24 hours a day . . . <br>
... on the World Wide Web: <a href="http://www.fema.gov"><strong>http://www.fema.gov</strong></a><br>
... via fax-on-demand: phone in the U.S.A. (202) 646-FEMA (646-3362)<br>
... via digital audio for broadcasters &amp; print: contact eipa@fema.gov<br>
</p>
