<html>

<head>
<title>Bertha Update; 07/12/96-Virgin Island Declaration</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p><font color="#0000FF"><font size=6>Hurricane Bertha Update</font></font><br>
<br>
The <font color="#FF0000"><font size=3>situation in brief as of 7:00 p.m. Friday, July 12:</font></font><br>
<br>
The 70-member interagency Emergency Support Team (EST) at Federal Emergency Management Agency 
(FEMA) headquarters in Washington, D.C. remains on 24-hour duty to respond to Hurricane Bertha's landfall 
on the East Coast. The EST, led by FEMA, coordinates all federal disaster response and recovery efforts. It 
includes representatives of the 12 key federal response agencies in addition to FEMA and, in this case, the 
National Weather Service.<br>
<br>
Advance elements of three regional Emergency Response Teams (ERT-As) are likewise operating around the 
clock in the states expected to be most affected by Hurricane Bertha initially: the Region VIII (Denver) ERT-A 
is in Columbia, S.C.; the ERT-A from Region VI (Dallas) is in Raleigh, N.C.; and the ERT-A from FEMA 
Region III (Philadelphia) is in Richmond, Va. The Region X (Seattle) ERT-A remains on alert.<br>
<br>
<font color="#FF0000">The 130-plus members of FEMA's national Emergency Response Team (ERT-N) &quot;Red Team,&quot; however, who 
had been on alert since Tuesday morning, were ordered to stand down by FEMA Director James Lee Witt a 
short while ago.</font> The Red Team is one of three national teams that deploy to a catastrophic disaster.<br>
<br>
Regional Operations Centers at FEMA Region IV headquarters in Atlanta and Region III headquarters in 
Philadelphia remain on 24-hour duty.<br>
<br>
FEMA's advance Emergency Response team (ERT-A) on station in Columbia, S.C., reports that <font color="#FF0000">National 
Guard helicopters will carry preliminary damage assessment teams into storm-damaged South Carolina 
communities Saturday morning, July 13.</font><br>
<br>
The ERT-A in South Carolina confirms that an estimated 500,000 residents of that state were evacuated before 
Bertha's landfall. Sixty-eight American Red Cross shelters are currently open, but occupants reportedly already 
are becoming anxious to return to their homes.<br>
<br>
The ERT-A on station in Raleigh, N.C., currently totals more than 100 FEMA staff and seven representatives 
of other federal response agencies. It reports that 94 Red Cross shelters are currently open in <font color="#FF0000">North Carolina, 
housing 1,920 evacuees. The ERT-A says preliminary damage assessments will also begin in that state on 
Saturday morning.</font><br>
<br>
The U.S. Coast Guard will close the port of Hampton Roads, Va., at 8 p.m. Friday, July 12, as a safety 
precaution. No vessels may enter, leave or move within the port until at least 4 a.m. Saturday or possibly longer.<br>
<br>
The Food and Commodity Service of the U.S. Department of Agriculture (USDA) is the principal source of 
food for emergency shelters in the affected area, most of which are in schools. Substantial food supplies are 
already stocked in the schools through USDA's school nutrition program.<br>
<br>
Data from the National Flood Insurace Program (NFIP), which is administered by FEMA, show 42,529 flood 
insurance policies in force in North Carolina and 87,152 policies in South Carolina. NFIP officials have asked 
the underwriting associations in both states to put a single-adjustor program into effect, so that a single insurance 
adjustor can visit a property and verify both wind damage (covered under homeowners policies) and flood 
damage (covered under flood insurance policies) at the same time, in order to speed the claims process for 
victims of Hurricane Bertha.<br>
<br>
U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) teams are on station in the affected areas, awaiting Saturday's 
damage assessments. They will visit damaged commercial facilities and public utilities, looking for oil spills and 
other hazardous wastes. The EPA will be working closely with the U.S. Public Health Service to determine 
water quality and working with the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers on proper disposal of storm debris.<br>
<br>
U.S. Department of Energy staff are on alert pending Saturday's assessments of damage to electric power 
plants and other utilities.<br>
</p>
<hr>
<p><font color="#0000FF"><font size=5>VIRGIN ISLANDS DECLARED MAJOR DISASTER AREA IN 
THE WAKE OF HURRICANE BERTHA</font></font><br>
<br>
WASHINGTON July 11, 1996 -- The head of the Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) 
announced today that federal disaster funds have been made available for the U.S. Virgin Islands to aid the 
recovery of residents victimized by Hurricane Bertha.<br>
<br>
FEMA Director James Lee Witt said the assistance was authorized by President Clinton under the major 
disaster declaration issued for the territory this evening. The President took the action after FEMA reported that 
at least 1,400 homes sustained damage from Bertha which buffeted the territory last Monday with winds in 
excess of 85 miles an hour.<br>
<br>
Immediately after the declaration, Witt designated the islands of St. Croix, St. John and St. Thomas eligible for 
federal funding to supplement the recovery needs of affected residents and business owners. <br>
<br>
The supplemental assistance, to be coordinated by FEMA, can include grants to help pay for temporary housing 
needs, minor home repairs and other serious disaster-related expenses. Low-interest loans from the U.S. Small 
Business Administration also will be available to cover uninsured private and business property losses.<br>
<br>
In addition, Witt said federal funds will be provided for the territory and affected local governments to pay 75 
percent of the eligible cost for debris removal, emergency services related to the hurricane, and approved 
projects that reduce future disaster risks. Witt added that damage surveys are continuing and other forms of 
assistance may be designated based on the assessments. <br>
<br>
Barbara Russell, of FEMA's regional office in New York City, was named by Witt to coordinate the federal 
relief effort. Russell said that residents and business owners who sustained hurricane losses can begin the 
disaster application process immediately by calling 1-800-462-9029, or 1-800-462-7585 (TDD) for the 
hearing and speech impaired. The toll-free telephone numbers will operate from 8 a.m. to 6 p.m. (EDT) seven 
days a week until further notice.<br>
<br>
Russell said that those who received assistance for Hurricane Marilyn last year are eligible to apply again for 
Hurricane Bertha losses. However, under FEMA's policy on duplication of benefits, grants for home repairs will 
be restricted to applicants who can verify that repair work from assistance received for Hurricane Marilyn has 
been either totally or partially completed.<br>
<br>
To qualify, Russell said that eligible applicants must show receipts for FEMA funds spent on completed repairs, 
or present the balance of unspent funds if the work has not been completed. Damage surveys following Bertha 
revealed that the most severely affected homes were those that had not undertaken permanent repairs. <br>
<br>
Home repair grants are provided as part of FEMA's Disaster Housing Assistance program. For Hurricane 
Marilyn, FEMA reported that housing assistance to date has been provided to some 14,800 individuals and 
families at a cost of more than $65 million. Of that total, $53.379 million has been disbursed to 8,239 qualified 
applicants for home repairs. <br>
<br>
<br>
Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) Office of Emergency Information &amp; Public Affairs --- 
Washington, D.C.<br>
<br>
Information Available 24 hours a day . . . <br>
... on the World Wide Web: <a href="http://www.fema.gov"><strong>http://www.fema.gov</strong></a><br>
... via fax-on-demand: phone in the U.S.A. (202) 646-FEMA (646-3362)<br>
... via digital audio for broadcasters &amp; print: contact eipa@fema.gov</p>
</body>

