<BODY>
<BR>
<H3>The International Fire Service Instructor Exchange Program</H3>
<P>

No one country has a monopoly on the best practices and procedures when
it comes to saving lives. We have much to learn from each other.  The
Alliance For Fire and Emergency Management recognizes this and is
developing an international instructor exchange program.
<P>
<HR>

Jack Welch, CEO of General Electric, puts it like this:
<BR>

"In the environment of the 1990s, globalization must be taken for granted.
There will only be one standard for corporate success: international market
share.  Success within a particular country will not even guarantee corporate
survival.  The winning corporations--those which can dictate their
destiny--will win by finding markets all over the world. "
<P>
<HR>

While corporate America is fighting for economic survival, the fire service
is fighting for the survival of innocent victims of fire, most of whom are
children or the elderly. Doesn't it make sense that we should be just as
aggressive in pursuing answers, training techniques and technologies
internationally which could be instrumental in saving lives?
<P> 

The International Fire Service Instructor Exchange program has been
developed to bring together the most elite and knowledgeable fire service
instructors from around the world to share their experience and expertise. 
This program is the first and only one of its kind designed especially for 
fire and emergency service training professionals.  The value of this program
can be seen by the commitments to participate already made by some of the
world's leading fire service training experts such as:
<P>
<HR>  

Jeff Godfredson, Metropolitan Fire Brigades Board, Melbourne, Australia
<BR>
Frank David, Commandant, Fire Service College, Gloucestershire, England
<BR>
Kennie Thorn, Deputy Director, Swedish Rescue Services Agency, Karlstad,
Sweden
<BR>
Alan Walker, Director, Louisiana State University, Firemen Training
Program, Baton Rouge, Louisiana
<BR>
Steve Edwards, Director, Maryland Fire & Rescue Institute, College Park,
Maryland
<BR>
Ronald Hopkins, Professor, Eastern Kentucky University, Richmond,
Kentucky
<BR>
<P>
<HR>

In order to make this program as feasible as possible for instructors to
participate, we are looking at a very short term of two weeks for each
exchange, although we will make it possible for this period to be extended
as necessary depending upon the nature of the course and the availability of
the instructors.
<P>

The goal of The Alliance is to raise enough funds so every instructor
participating will have their round-trip air-fare paid for and will also have
a per diem allowance for their meals. We do not want to see fire service
instructors barred from participating in this exchange program because they
can't afford it.  Instructors will be chosen by an independent instructor
selection committee based on their area of professional expertise, their
career background and qualifications. A needs assessment identifying the
training needs and strengths from each of the participating organizations is
currently in process. This is a proactive approach to ensure that this
program is as value-packed as possible.
<P>

This program will establish a forum for the free exchange of best educational
programs and instructors between participating countries.  The end results
of this program will be the development and application of new training
techniques and technologies from around the world which will be instrumental
in saving lives and property. The front lines of fire fighting are not
found in the heat of the fireground, they're found in the classroom, where
firefighters are taught the skills they need to survive and to save lives and
property.  That's why this program is aimed at instructors.
<P>
<HR>

If you would like more information on this exciting new initiative of The
Alliance, please mail or fax a brief letter with your name, address and phone
number, or send an E-Mail message  to:
<P>

International Instructor Exchange
<BR>
The Alliance for Fire and Emergency Management
<BR>
30 Main Street
<BR>
Ashland, Massachusetts  01721
<BR>
U.S.A.
<BR>
Voice: 508.881.5800 Fax: 508.881.6829 E-Mail: webmastr@afem.org
<P>
<BR><A HREF="/firepage.htm"><B>Return to the Fire Operations Page</B></A>
<P>
</BODY>
