<HEAD>
<TITLE>Police Press Cali Cartel</TITLE>
<!-- Comment Here -->
</HEAD>
<BODY>
Excerpted from EmergencyNet NEWS Service (ENNFAX)
<BR>
Monday, April 1, 1996
<BR>
Vol. 2 - 091
<P>

<B>**LEAD STORY**</B>
<P>

<H2>CALI DRUG CARTEL UNDER PRESSURE...</H2>
By Steve Macko, ENN Editor
<P>

In 1995 alone, in the New York City borough of Queens, 20 high-level
Colombian drug dealers were found murdered.  In one gruesome
incident in July, the body of one Colombian was found stuffed
inside of a suitcase along the side of a road in Queens.  The
victim had been bound and gagged with duct tape.  A cord had
been wrapped around his neck and a rotting onion was stuffed
inside of his mouth.
<P>

Authorities say that only recently the Cali drug cartel has
been able to overcome some internal stresses on their illegal
operation that was caused by several high-level arrests in 1995.
Only recently has the violence that has been targeted against
drug dealers leveled off.  What that shows is that a power shift
in New York's drug underworld has taken place.
<P>

It is an underworld of bloody turf wars, hitmen who are trigger-
happy, vicious people who won't even think twice about taking
out opposition.  But even though there was a major shakeup in
what is called the world's premier drug cartel -- the cocaine
and the heroin continued to flow into the United States unabated.
But one thing is for certain, the way that the Cali cartel operates
has been transformed.
<P>

The New York City Police Department (NYPD) has increased its
pressure on the drug dealers.  Large drug shipments have been
replaced by smaller ones.  Flashy displays of wealth by drug
dealers has been eliminated.  Stash houses have been moved.
New people have been hired.  Command centers for drug operations
have moved out of the city and into the suburbs of Long Island
and New Jersey.
<P>

The chief of narcotics investigations for the Borough of Queens
District Attorney's Office, Peter Crusco, said, "Paranoia on
their part has gone through the roof."  Crusco said that the
big-time drug dealers are now "working out of suitcases" to
avoid detection from authorities.
<P>

The pressure on the cartel is not only coming from inside of
the United States.  In Colombia, in 1995, six of the highest-
ranking members of the cartel were arrested.  When those arrests
happened, many thought that finally the Cali cartel had been
brought to its knees.
<P>

Last August, after the arrest of one of the key drug-traffickers
in Colombia, Lee Brown, the former director of the Office of
National Drug Control Policy, said, "The cartel is crumbling."
But the situation on the streets in New York City told a different
story.
<P>

While many law enforcement officials say that the Cali drug cartel's
operation may have been disrupted for a short period of time -- the
price and supply of drugs has now begun to once again stabilize.
And that's the best indicator of what is happening.
<P>

Late last year, the wholesale price of a kilogram of cocaine in
New York City was $25,000.  It has now dropped to the current
going price of $21,000 a kilo (2.2 pounds).  The United States
Drug Enforcement Administration (DEA) says that is a sign that
supplies have been stabilized.
<P>

The Agent-In-Charge of the DEA's New York office said that he is
not surprised that the Cali cartel has been able to rebound.  He
said that because of the immense size of the cartel they are able
to "undercut anyone."
<P>

In another illustration of the power of the Colombian cartel, the
Mexicans have been trying to corner the heroin trade in New York
City for decades -- but they've never been able to quite do it.
The Colombians were able to dominate the New York heroin market
almost overnight.  Four years ago, the Colombians only had a 15
percent market share of the New York heroin market.  Today, they
account for 80 percent.
<P>

Carlo Boccia, the head of the New York City DEA office, said this
about the Cali cartel, "There's not an organization anywhere that
can compete with them."  But even though it sounds like things are going well for the
Colombians -- they have been feeling the pressure from law
enforcement.
<P>

Because of increased police action against them in their
traditional strongholds in New York City -- they've had to
move out onto Long Island, the suburbs of New Jersey and
even to the States of Connecticut and Pennsylvania.
It's even more difficult to spot a drug dealer.  Gone are
the flashy, expensive, luxury cars and the gold chains.
Drug dealers are now trying to keep a low profile.
<P>

Another sign that law enforcement is hurting them is the
effort to cut the risk of losing multi-million dollar
losses of drugs seized.  Drug shipments have apparently 
been reduced in size.  What used to be sent in one shipment
is now sent in twenty. Regardless of all of this seemingly good news -- the war on
drugs is still far, far from being won.
<P>
(c) EmergencyNet News Servcie, 1996, All Rights Reserved.
