<html>

<head>
<title>Researchers Report E-Coli Detector</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>Excerpted from the ENN Daily Report - Saturday - 12/14/96 - Vol. 2, No. 349<br>
<br>
<font size=5><strong>Researchers Say They Have Effective E-Coli-157 Detector</strong></font><br>
<br>
(ENN) Berkeley, CA -- Ray Stevens, a chemist at the Ernest Orlando Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory, says that 
his team has developed a rapid and reliable test to detect the now familiar 0157:H7 E. Coli bacteria.<br>
<br>
The bug, which has become famous in recent years for causing outbreaks of illness and even deaths in the United States 
and other countries, took the life of one person and sickened fifty others recently in an unpasteurized apple juice incident in 
the Pacific Northwest. Eleven people have died and more that 300 have also been diagnosed with the E. Coli bacteria in 
Scotland within the past two weeks.<br>
<br>
One of the problems in identifying rapidly progressing epidemics is that of identifying the problem virus or bacteria that is 
causing sickness. In the case of sensor developed at the Berkeley labs, they say that it can almost instantenously report 
whether or not E.Coli is present. And, Stevens says that the test is inexpensive and could be widely used by medical and 
prehospital professionals.<br>
<br>
According to Stevens, &quot;We can make an inexpensive sensor that could be placed on a number of different materials such 
as plastic, paper, or glass...the cost is so nominal that could even be part of a bottle cap or container lid.&quot; &quot;If you open the 
lid and the test sensor has changed color, then you would know you have a contaminated food product,&quot; he concluded.<br>
<br>
Until now, no technology existed to provide rapid, on-the-spot tests for the potentially virulent 0157 strain of E. Coli. 
Currently the laboratory test takes at least 24 hours to determine the presence of the bacteria. Analysts who study 
chemical and biological weapons and infectious diseases said that they hope the new sensors prove reliable and that 
production of them can quickly be &quot;up-ramped&quot; to make them widely available to public health personnel.<br>
<br>
(C) EmergencyNet News Service, 1996; all rights reserved. Contact ENN for redistribution rights.</p>
</body>

</html>
