<head>
<title>Arizona Viper Militia; Members Arrested</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>EmergencyNet NEWS Service, Tuesday, July 2, 1996, Vol. 2 - 184<br>
<br>
<strong>==============<br>
**LEAD STORY**<br>
==============</strong><br>
<br>
ENN 7/2/96 09:32<br>
<br>
<font size=5><strong>ARIZONA MILITIA GROUP ARRESTED BY FEDERAL 
AUTHORITIES</strong></font>.<br>
<br>
By Steve Macko, ENN Editor<br>
<br>
PHOENIX (ENN) - Federal law enforcement authorities arrested thirteen members of what could be 
described as a very dangerous anti-government group calling itself the &quot;Viper Militia&quot; on Monday 
afternoon. The suspects are charged with plotting for more than two years to bomb government 
buildings. Members of the militia group are said to have held training exercises in the Arizona desert in 
which they detonated ammonium nitrate bombs.<br>
<br>
In Washington, at a news conference, U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno said that the group plotted to 
use explosives to destroy buildings that house: the Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI), the U.S. 
Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms (ATF), the Internal Revenue Service (IRS), the Immigration 
and Naturalization Service (INS), the U.S. Secret Service (USSS), the Phoenix Police Department and 
the Arizona National Guard. Arrest and search warrants were carried out against the twelve suspects on 
Monday. An ATF bomb squad had to remove explosive material at one home in the Phoenix suburb of 
Peoria.<br>
<br>
In a videotape made by the militia group in May of 1994, a member talks about security measures, 
communications equipment and other features of targeted buildings. In Phoenix, U.S. Attorney Janet 
Napolitano said, &quot;The voiceover on the videotape gives advice on how to actually collapse the 
buildings.&quot; The narrator on the videotape suggests that &quot;anti-personnel devices&quot; could be placed in 
mailboxes near the entrance of a building that houses several federal agencies and said that by destroying 
a water main near the building could hamper firefighting efforts. The tape also showed the exterior of the 
building where the IRS is located and describes the schedules of security guards and other security 
measures.<br>
<br>
In describing an attack on the Phoenix Police Department, the narrator on the tape said that it would be 
difficult to take over the building, but that &quot;it would be a major political statement if it were taken over.&quot; 
The records and equipment inside of the building, according to the narrator, &quot;would be invaluable.&quot;<br>
<br>
Much of the information that lead to the indictments of this dangerous group came from an undercover 
Arizona State Police officer who infiltrated the group.<br>
<br>
A next door neighbor to two of the militia members who were arrested in Peoria described the men as 
&quot;definitely pro-gun people.&quot; The neighbor said that the people who associated with the suspects had 
expressed anger at the government's handling of the standoffs near Waco, Texas, and Ruby Ridge, 
Idaho. The neighbor said, &quot;I think they're like the rest of us, they get frustrated about legislation that 
restricts gun use.&quot;<br>
<br>
On Monday, it was announced that twelve militia members had been arrested in the conspiracy plot. On 
Tuesday morning, John Magaw, the director of the U.S. Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms said 
that thirteen people have been arrested in connection with the case. The 13th person was arrested late 
on Monday night. Magaw warned, &quot;Terrorism has come to the United States. Do not forget for one 
minute the Oklahoma City bombing.&quot;</p>
<p>(c) EmergencyNet News Service, 1996, All Rights Reserved.</p>
