<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE></TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="aqua.gif">
<P><IMG SRC="aquapol.gif">
</P><hr><b>
Subject: Compulsory Education Attendance Exemption for Home Instruction<br>
Index:  Instructional Program
<hr>
<P>1. PURPOSE</B></P>
<P>To establish an effective working relationship with parents who choose to establish home school education for their child as provided under Utah law.</P>
<P><B>2.REFERENCES</B></P>
<P> 2.1.53A-11-102 Utah Code Annotated 1953 as amended 1988. </P>
<P> 2.2.R300-419, Utah Administrative Code, 1990. </P>
<P> 2.3.R300-700, The Elementary and Secondary School Core Curriculum and High School Graduation Requirements. </P>
<P><B>3.DEFINITION</B></P>
<P> <B>3.1.Home Instruction or Home School</B> means that a person having control of a minor between six (6) and eighteen (18) years of age accepts the responsibility for providing the education of such minor at home in accordance with law instead of having the minor attend a public or regularly established private school.</P>
<P> <B>3.2.Full-time student</B> means, for purposes of participation in student activities, a student enrolled in a Davis County School District school a minimum of three-fourths (3/4) of the full day. </P>
<P> <B>3.3.Part-time student</B> means, for purposes of participation in student activities, a student enrolled in a Davis County School District school less than  three-fourths (3/4) of the full day.</P>
<P><B>4.POLICY</B></P>
<P>On an annual basis, a minor may receive a full release from attendance in the Davis County School District if the minor is taught at home in the subjects prescribed by the State Board of Education in accordance with the law for the same length of time as minors are required by law to be taught in the district schools.  In a spirit of cooperation with parents who choose to establish a home school education for their child, the following procedures are intended to comply with the law and facilitate the request for release of the child from compulsory education attendance requirements.</P>
<P> <B>4.1.   Parent Responsibilities</B></P>
<P> A parent, guardian, or other person having custody over a school-age minor who resides in Davis County may receive a full release from attending school if the minor is taught at home in the subjects prescribed by the State Board of Education for the same length of time as children are required by law to be taught in the District schools.  Parents who choose to release their child from compulsory attendance and provide a home school for the instruction and education of their child will: </P>
<P> <B> 4.1.1.Complete and submit &quot;Request for Compulsory Attendance</B><B> Exemption&quot; </B><B>form.</B></P>
<P>   (a)Complete and submit &quot;Request for Compulsory Attendance Exemption&quot; form (or facsimile) to the Davis Board of Education.  </P>
<P>   (b)If possible, complete the request process prior to removing child from public school if the student is enrolled in a Davis District school.</P>
<P>  4.1.2.Provide 180 days of instruction per year between July 1 and June 30.</P>
<P>  4.1.3.While school attendance prior to the age of six is optional, parents are strongly urged to provide 2 1/2 hours of instruction per day for children of kindergarten age in subjects as specified by the Core Curriculum of the State of Utah for kindergarten. </P>
<P>  4.1.4.Provide a minimum of 4 1/2 hours of instruction per day in grade one, and 5 1/2 hours of instruction per school day for grades two and above.</P>
<P>  4.1.5.Provide instruction in grades 1 through 6 in accordance with the State of Utah Core Curriculum.  The Core Curriculum includes, but is not restricted to such subjects as, reading, mathematics, science, social studies, language arts, music, art, and healthy lifestyle/fitness.</P>
<P> </P>
<P>  4.1.6.Provide instruction in grades 7 through 12 in accordance with the State of Utah Core Curriculum.  The Core Curriculum includes but is not restricted to such subjects as language arts, mathematics, science, social studies, healthy lifestyle/fitness, arts, information technology (computer skills), vocational education, and appropriate electives.  See &quot;Program of Studies for grades 7-12.&quot;  </P>
<P>  4.1.7.Application for exemption is required annually and the exemption is contingent upon certification by the parent or guardian that the student will comply  with sections 4.1.1. through 4.1.6. </P>
<P>  4.1.8.Request, if desired, special education services which the district will provide in accordance with state rules and regulations.  The age may vary for eligible students who must be provided special educational services.</P>
<P> <B>4.2.Board and District Responsibilities</B></P>
<P> The Davis Board of Education will coordinate services and respond to questions regarding compulsory education exemptions.  The Board will:</P>
<P>  4.2.1.Review requests for Compulsory Attendance Exemption.</P>
<P>  4.2.2.Notify applicants of the Board's/District's decision within three weeks after receiving the request for exemption.</P>
<P>  4.2.3.Issue a <B>Compulsory Attendance</B><B> Exemption Certificate for Home </B><B>Instruction</B> to applicants that meet the requirements of the policy as stated herein.</P>
<P>  4.2.4.Notify the local school principal of the parent's decision to withdraw the child from school.  The principal will remove the child from the school enrollment records.</P>
<P>  4.2.5.Provide at the request of parent or guardian the following items at costs established by the Board of Education.  Costs will be the same as those for regular education students. </P>
<P>   (a)A Home Instruction Information Packet.  The packet will include the district policy, attendance exemption  procedures, and pertinent application forms.  The packet will be provided at no cost.</P>
<P>   (b)Textbooks, when available and needed, at a rental fee established by the Davis Board of Education.  Replacement cost is to be charged for damaged books or books not returned to the school at the end of the school year.  Parents may choose to purchase adopted textbooks from available suppliers.</P>
<P>   (c)Academic requirements for each level, subject and grade.</P>
<P>   (d)End of level and standardized norm reference testing will be administered  in accordance to a schedule established for district students.</P>
<P>   (e)District in-service classes to parents for a designated fee.</P>
<P>  4.2.6.Receive  requests for exemption.   Exemption will be determined by compliance with the requirements as described herein.</P>
<P> <B>4.3.Students Enrolled in a combination of Public, Private &amp; Home Instruction</B></P>
<P> Students may divide their enrollment between public and home instruction or private school enrollment and may thereby obtain access to specialized instruction or other programs not readily available in these programs.  Students who choose to participate as part-time students shall comply with district andschool policies and rules.</P>
<P>  <B>4.3.1. Full-time Students are eligible to:</B></P>
<P>   Participate as school officers, class officers, cheerleaders and similar positions .</P>
<P><B> </B><B> </B><B>4.3.2</B><B>.</B><B>Part-time</B><B> students are eligible to:</B></P>
<P>   (a)Participate as members of intramural teams, members of school clubs, and participate in other school activities.</P>
<P>   (b)Purchase activity cards and participate as spectators at school functions.</P>
<P>   (c)Participate and hold office in activity clubs if they are enrolled in the school based classes that generate and support the clubs.</P>
<P><B> </B><B> </B><B>4.3.3</B><B>.</B><B>Part-time students are ineligible to:</B></P>
<P>   (a)Participate as team members or performers in competitive activities sponsored by the Utah High Schools Activities Association.</P>
<P>   (b)Participate as team members or performers in Junior High School competitive activities.</P>
<P> <B>4.4.Re-Entry to District Schools</B></P>
<P> In the interest of determining an appropriate placement and curriculum, students exempted from compulsory attendance requirements who choose to re-enter the public schools of Davis County will be admitted under the same entrance requirements as other students entering the District schools.  The student will be placed by the school principal after consulting with parents.. These requirements apply to all entering students  whether part-time or full-time.</P>
<P>  4.4.1.At the principal's discretion, the principal may  use placement tests, parent consultation, and other evidence of student progress to assist in proper grade level placement and placement in specialized programs. Appeals will be directed to the Credit Evaluation Committee.</P>
<P>  4.4.2.Credit requests for home instruction will be evaluated under the provisions provided in the District Credit Evaluation Standards and Guidelines Policy (4I-411).</P>
<P> <B>4.5.Appeals</B></P>
<P> Decisions to deny a compulsory education exemption certificate may be appealed by the parent/guardian of the student to the Davis County School District Board of Education.  Requests for appeal must be written and submitted within ten working days following the decision.  The Board will review the decision and respond in writing within ten working days.  The response will include the reason(s) for the decision.</P>
<P></P>
<h2>Required Forms and Letters</h2>
<A HREF="04i-102p.htm">Parent/Guardian Letter</A><br>
<A HREF="04i-1024.htm">Request for Compulsory Attendance Exemption</A><br>
<A HREF="04i-1025.htm">Sample Compulsory Attendance Exemption Certificate </A><br>
