<BODY BGCOLOR="#c6d3ad">
<H2><I>All about . . .</I></H2>
<H1><FONT COLOR="Green" SIZE="+5">D</FONT><FONT SIZE="+5">AVIS COUNTY SCHOOLS</FONT></H1><H1><FONT COLOR="Lime" SIZE="+5"></FONT>Native American Tutoring

</H1>
<P>Native American Homework Centers at every Davis junior high and high school 
serve 190 students in cooperation with the Davis County Indian Parent Association.  
Elementary one-on-one tutoring is also offered.
</P>
<P><B>Native American Tutoring, 451-1116</B></P>
<H1>
Summer School
</H1>
<P>Many Davis schools offer summer school classes in a variety of areas including 
biology, math, reading, computer skills, volleyball and other sports.  At the secondary 
schools, classes may be taken for both makeup and original credit.  
</P>
<P>Summer school is a self-supporting program, so tuition is charged to each student 
who participates.  Participation is voluntary.  If you are interested in summer school 
programs in your community, call your local school or Adult and Community Education at 
451-1135 after May 1 for class offerings.
</P>
<H1>Adult and Continuing Education
</H1>
<P>Adult and Continuing Education courses continue to offer excellent lifelong 
learning opportunities throughout Davis County.  Over 3,800 adults and more than 3,000 high 
school age students participate in high school completion courses during the evening in 
Davis County schools each year.  This amounts to 192,700 hours of classroom participation.
</P>
<P>An Adult High School Graduation in June highlights the achievements of adults 
who earned the Davis County Adult High School diploma.  Over 2,500 credits are earned 
by students taking courses at night.  This frees 83 classrooms averaging 30 students per 
class if courses had been taken during the day program.  163 adults also completed  the 
GED and earned credit toward their high school diplomas.
</P>
<P>Competency based education and computer aided instruction have reduced the 
&quot;seat-time&quot; frustration that many adults have faced when taking courses.   Additional home 
and video based educational opportunities are now available.
</P>
<P>Over 10,000 Community Education courses are taken by adults and youth interested 
in a wide variety of courses ranging from Auto Repairs to Dutch Oven Cooking.  Courses 
for recreation and self-esteem merge with computer and vocational offerings to 
provide positive experiences for all ages throughout the county.
</P>
<P>For more information about credit and noncredit offerings, contact the Adult 
and Community School director's office in Farmington at 546-7348, 451-1135  or your local 
adult education or community school coordinator located at each district high school.
</P>
<P><B>Adult and Community Education, 546-7348, 451-1135</B></P>
<P><I><FONT SIZE="+2"><A HREF="AADCSTOC.HTM">Back</A></FONT></I></P>
