<BODY BGCOLOR="#c6d3ad">
<H2><I>All about . . .</I></H2>
<H1><FONT COLOR="Green" SIZE="+5">D</FONT><FONT SIZE="+5">AVIS COUNTY SCHOOLS</FONT></H1><H1><FONT COLOR="Lime" SIZE="+5"></FONT>School Food Service

</H1>
<P>This program operates as an independent business on a budget of $12,411,000.  
Each of the District's 70 schools (including Davis Applied Technology Center) has a 
fully equipped kitchen.  Food Service highlights include:
</P>
<UL>
<LI>     30,000 hot lunches prepared and served daily by 446 cooks and assistants.
</LI>
<LI>     76 percent of elementary pupils (some 18,000 youngsters) participate in the 
School Lunch Program each day. The cost is $1.15 per meal.
</LI>
<LI>     48 percent of junior high students pay $1.50 for lunch.  Students have five choices. 
 Fifteen percent eat on the a la carte line. Average daily participation in junior 
high schools is 6,800 students.
</LI>
<LI>     26 percent of high school students pay $1.50 for lunch.  These students have up to 
ten choices.  Ten percent eat on the a la carte line.  Average daily participation in high 
school is 3,500 students.
</LI>
<LI>     Breakfast is served each day at 63 schools.  Average participation for breakfast is 2,300.
</LI>
<LI>     Lunch is served at DATC, day care centers located in the high schools and  the 
Head Start Programs at 14 locations.
</LI>
<LI>     After school snacks for Project Pride and Project Care are served at six locations.  
After school sack lunch suppers are also provided for the 3-6 programs at two schools.
</LI>
<LI>All lunches and breakfasts are federally subsidized and meet federal guidelines.
</LI>
</UL>







<P><B>School Foods Service, 451-1210</B>
</P>
<H1>Transportation
</H1>
<P>169 school buses traveling over 341 different routes transport 14,000 students to 
and from school daily.  The distance ranges from 1 to 48 miles traveling approximately 
2,000,000 miles each year.  This includes 50 buses carrying special education students.  27 of 
these buses are equipped with power lifts to accommodate students with special needs.
</P>
<P>State law sets the minimum distance for students to qualify for bus services.  
Elementary students must live 1.5 miles or more from the school.  Secondary students must live 2 
miles away or more to qualify.
</P>
<P><B>Transportation, 774-7475</B></P>
<P><I><FONT SIZE="+2"><A HREF="AADCSTOC.HTM">Back</A></FONT></I></P>
