<H2><I>All about . . .</I></H2>
<H1><FONT COLOR="Green" SIZE="+5">D</FONT><FONT SIZE="+5">AVIS COUNTY SCHOOLS</FONT></H1><H1><FONT COLOR="Lime" SIZE="+5"></FONT>Student Services

</H1>
<P>The Department of Student Services is established to serve students who require 
special alternatives, exceptions and directions in order to obtain a satisfactory school experience.  
</P>
<P>The major areas administered by Student Services follows:  transfer requests, 
consultation with administrators, counseling students, referral to alternative programs, Youth 
In Custody, Crisis Team, foreign student placement, liaison with juvenile court, 
At-Risk Students, Drug Free Schools programs, Safe School issues and homeless students.  
Student Services is responsible for coordination of the secondary Comprehensive Counseling 
and Guidance model.
</P>
<P><B>Student Services, 451-1159</B></P>
<H2><BR>
Special Education
</H2>
<P>Special Education service was provided for 8,113 District students including 
195 preschoolers with disabilities during the 1994-95 school year.  These students were:
</P>
<UL>
<LI>     Developmentally Delayed          </LI>
<LI>Intellectually Disabled
</LI>
<LI>     Other Health Impaired          </LI>
<LI>Specific Learning Disabled
</LI>
<LI>     Multi-disabled          </LI>
<LI>Behaviorally Disordered
</LI>
<LI>     Hearing Impaired          </LI>
<LI>Deaf 
</LI>
<LI>     Visually Impaired          </LI>
<LI>Communication Disordered
</LI>
<LI>     Orthopedically Impaired          </LI>
<LI>Autistic
</LI>
<LI>     Dual Sensory Impaired (Deaf/Blind)          </LI>
<LI>Traumatic Brain Injured
</LI>
</UL>






<P>Approximately 600 special education teachers, teaching assistants and related 
staff, including social workers, school psychologists, physical/occupational therapists, 
speech/language specialists, vision/hearing specialists and interpreters work with students in 
the schools.
</P>
<P>     Additional services are provided by:
</P>
<UL>
<LI>     Davis Diagnostic Resource Center <BR>
(a testing center located at Monte Vista Elementary)
</LI>
<LI>     Pioneer Adult Rehabilitation Center
</LI>
</UL>

<P><B>Special Education, 451-1169</B>
</P>
<H2>Parent Education Resource Center 
</H2>
<P>PERC has a wide variety of educational and training materials which give 
suggestions on how to improve family functioning and how to solve family problems, thereby 
enabling children to succeed in school and  life. 
</P>
<P>A lending library, available to all parents, contains books, toys and audiovisual 
media (filmstrips, cassette tapes, videos) to answer parents' questions. Parenting classes 
are offered on a variety of subjects:  Raising Responsible Children, Discipline, Self 
Esteem, Attention Deficit Disorder, and Enjoying Adolescents.  A nominal fee is charged.
</P>
<P>Centers are located in Bountiful at 385 W. 1000 N., Kaysville at 320 S. 500 E. 
and Clearfield at the Family Support Center, 1360 E. 1450 S.
</P>
<P><B>PERC, 546-7309</B></P>

