<TITLE></TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="bk30.gif">

<H1 ALIGN="center">Center for Collaboration &amp; Innovation</H1>

<HR>
<H3>
THE LEARNING LAB: A CENTER FOR COLLABORATION AND INNOVATION 

</H3>
<P>The following classes are offered by the Learning Lab, a joint project of the Davis District Staff Development Department and the DEA, UEA, and NEA Center for Innovation.</P>
<P>

The Learning Lab sponsors classes, support groups, learning, sharing, and collaboration around the topics that are of interest and concern to educators.</P>
<H3 ALIGN="center">
	WHAT IS IT? 
 </H3>
<P ALIGN="center">A network of collaboration and innovation.</P>
<H3 ALIGN="center">	WHERE IS IT? 
 </H3>
<P ALIGN="center">Wherever.  Groups and classes meet all around the district.</P>
<H3 ALIGN="center">		
	WHO IS IT?
</H3>
<P ALIGN="center">Teachers, administrators, support staff, and parents who want to come together to share ideas and information around common themes and interests.</P>
<H3 ALIGN="center">		
	WHY? 
 </H3>
<P ALIGN="center">To connect <B>YOU</B>  with people and information.</P>
<P>
		
Interested in classes, study groups, action research, staff development, information on a particular topic?????<BR>

Call Learning Lab Coordinator: Sandy Petersen at 451-1183.

Here are some Learning Lab offerings that you may want to have at your school.</P>
<H3>

PERSONAL AND PROFESSIONAL DEVELOPMENT FOR TEACHERS</H3>
<P>
How do adults learn and develop?  Are there predictable life stages?  What are the characteristics of the stages of teacher development?  How do age and gender impact professional development?  How can teachers continue to work hard and progress without risking burnout?  What are your personal styles of learning, communicating, and relating to others?

An increased understanding of adult development can &quot;broaden the window&quot; through which we view ourselves and others.  It can positively impact how effectively we communicate with, respond to, and facilitate learning for ourselves and others.

This class is designed to give teachers a better understanding of the stages of adult development with an emphasis on clarifying and deepening personal and professional growth through self-awareness.</P>
<P>
	
	FOR: K-12 teachers &amp; administrators<BR>
	INSTRUCTOR: Sandy Petersen
	<BR>
CREDIT: 1 credit hour
	<BR>
COST:  $10
	<BR>
PLACE: By  arrangement at your site

	
</P>
<H3>INTRODUCTION TO ACTION RESEARCH
</H3>
<P>This course is designed to teach you the methods for conducting an action research project.  It is designed to promote collaborative work among teachers who are interested in answering questions about their own practice

	</P>
<P>FOR: K-12 teachers &amp; administrators
	<BR>
INSTRUCTOR: Sandy Petersen
	<BR>
CREDIT: 1 credit hour
	<BR>
COST: $10
	<BR>
PLACE: By arrangement at your site.


</P>
<H3>CONFLICT MANAGEMENT</H3>
<P>
Conflict is a fact of life.  No school is conflict free, nor (believe it or not) would you want it to be...
Dealt with effectively, conflict can:
 	open the lines of communication
 	provide opportunities for creativity and growth
 	increase personal and organizational self-awareness
 	build and improve upon working relationships
Unfortunately, conflict (and the avoidance thereof) can be and often is destructive to people and organizations.  It results in a drain on the time and energy of teachers and administrators, and leads to dissatisfaction, upset and discouraged people.

The constructive use and resolution of conflict is an essential skill for administrators and a valuable tool for teachers.  This workshop will focus on helping participants understand the &quot;ten most deadly&quot; personalities, determine and understand their own preferred style of responding to conflict, and teach some specific skills for turning destructive conflict into win/win scenarios. 
	</P>
<P>FOR: Entire faculty or specific groups<BR>
INSTRUCTOR: Sandy Peterson  &amp; 		Kaye Chatterton
	<BR>
CREDIT: Variable 
	<BR>
COST:  $10
	<BR>
PLACE: On the road.  By request.  They would be happy to come to your school to do the seminar with an entire faculty or with specific groups, e.g. Joint Staff, professional organizations, etc.  Call Staff Development (451-1119 or 451-1183 to schedule).


</P>
<P ALIGN="left"><A HREF="Fall96in.htm">Back to Davis County Professional Development Page</A>
</P>

