<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE></TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#92EDEF">
<H1 ALIGN="center">Davis School District Foundation</H1>
<H3>I.   HISTORY</H3>
<P>The Davis School District Foundation was first incorporated in the mid1980's.   The bylaws were most recently amended in September 1994.  The Davis School District Foundation is an IRS 501(c)(3) organization.  All donations, whether cash or material, are tax deductible. </P>
<H3>II.  BOARD OF TRUSTEES</H3>
<P>The Foundation has worked to develop and maintain an active, working board representing the various communities and interests of our county.  The bylaws stipulate there shall be a trustee from each of the seven high school attendance areas.  In addition, a representative from the Board of Education, the Davis Education Association, and the PTA are included on the board. </P>
<P> Monthly meetings are held September through May in the morning at 8:00 a.m. on the third Monday of the month with occasional changes for holidays.  The Board can change this as needed.</P>
<P>Interested community members who would like to assist the Davis School District Foundation should call 4511182 for further information.
</P>
<H3><B>III.  INCENTIVES FOR EXCELLENCE</B>
</H3>
<P>Incentives for Excellence, the state matching fund program, has served as an important vehicle attracting private dollars with the incentive of matching public monies allowing local  schools the means to implement significant sitebased projects which enhance educationalexcellence in any area of the curriculum.  Applications for these grants are due in October of each year.
</P>
<H3>IV.  FOUNDATION PROJECTS
</H3>
<P>     Teacher Grants  The Davis School District Foundation Teacher Grants, approximately twenty $500 awards, are presented to teachers in December or January. 
</P>
<P>      Applications are sent to the schools in November and are due in December to enable the awards to be presented at a board of education. 
</P>
<H4>     Hall of Fame
</H4>
<P>     The District's annual recognition evening for outstanding teachers has become a premier event.  Each school selects one outstanding teacher to recognize. 
</P>
<P>     From the teachers who are nominated, the Teacher of the Year is selected as well as</P>
<P>     the Elementary and Secondary Teacher of the Year.  The Bountiful Auto Dealers      Association,   Northwest Pipeline, and Kern River Gas Transmission Company are     major sponsors of this event.</P>
<H4>     Artists In Residence
</H4>
<P>    This program is sponsored by the Utah Arts Council.  It provides an artist of choice for a school.   If the school has not had a previous grant,     the Foundation assists  schools with the match that is required.</P>
<P>     United Way  At Risk Students   The Foundation is a designated agency of United Way. These monies are used to fund At Risk Student Grants to teachers.     United Way  PARC  The Pioneer Adult Rehabilitation Center (PARC) is also a designated agency of United Way utilizing the Foundation's 501(c)(3) tax status. 
</P>
<H4>     PARC's mission is to enhance the quality of life for the severely disabled. </H4>
<P>     United Way  Teen Line  Teen Line is a United Way agency that receives funding through the application process.  It is a statewide telephone line using a 1800 number     where teens can call during evening hours to discuss problems.  Trained teen volunteers man the phones so that troubled callers are always talking to their peers.      However, a trained adult counselor is always available, if needed.  Teen Line's phone number is 1800479TEEN (8336).
</P>
<H3>V.   DONATIONS
</H3>
<P>Most donations received by the Davis School District Foundation have been designated for the support of individual school, district, or Foundation projects.  One hundred percent ofeach donation goes to the program or school designated by the donor.</P>
<P>     Payroll Deductions  It is now possible for district employees to sign up for a payroll deduction to the Foundation and designate a school or program of their choice. 
</P>
<P>     State Income Tax Checkoff  For several years, we have received funds designated for the Davis School District Foundation through the State Income Tax Checkoff     Program. Zions Bank Partners in Education Visa Card  This credit card is available to     district patrons.  This card rebates 1% of all purchases to Davis School District Foundation and 1/2% per year to the credit card holder.  Applications are available     at Zions Bank or from the Davis School District Foundation office.</P>
<H3>VI.  FUNDRAISING
</H3>
<P>PTA's and community councils have been major partners for the schools in our district.  In an effort to benefit local schools and enhance educational opportunities for students, most PTA's and/or school community councils do fundraising.  Fundraising projects need to be approved by the Davis School District Foundation and accepted as part of the schoolfundraising plan by the local school principal.</P>
<H3>VII. INVEST IN FUTURES
</H3>
<P>The focus on partnerships has been the Foundation's single largest initiative.  In concert with Governor Leavitt and school districts throughout Utah particularly along the Wasatch Front, we have worked to establish partnerships for our schools or to enhance existing partnerships. </P>
<P>Layton Hills Mall has also agreed to assist the Davis District Foundation to promote school/business partnerships.   The Foundation has been grateful for the assistance offeredby the Layton Hills Mall.</P>
<P>Four types of partnerships are encouraged:</P>
<P>     Partners in Education  offers businesses the opportunity to donate resources to an area school.
</P>
<P>     Crayons to Computers  businesses or individuals can donate unused materials to enhance classroom activities.
</P>
<P>     Adoptaclass  This program allows businesses to donate to an individual classroom and fulfill a &quot;wish list&quot; of teacher needs.
</P>
<P>     Teachers in Training  2600 teachers need training in classroom software technology.  A $100 donation will pay for a substitute teacher and the purchase of a     site license.  Teachers are trained at the District Technology Training Center at Woods Cross High School.
</P>
<H3>VIII.     SCHOLARSHIPS
</H3>
<P>The Foundation administers a growing number of scholarships.   Scholarships may be designated to a specific school.  Information can be obtained at each local high school inDavis School District.  </P>
</BODY>
</HTML>
