<CENTER><H1>The Home of the Falcons
<H2>Clearfield High School</H2></H1>
<H3>931 South Falcon Drive</H3>
<H3>Clearfield, Utah 84015</H3>
<H4>Phone (801) 774-7460</H4>
<H4>Fax (801) 774-7647</H4><BR>
<BR>
</CENTER><P>
<H1><IMG SRC="lowe-mrs.gif" ALIGN=left> Welcome to Clearfield High School's Home Page.  
I'm Tamara Lowe the Principal of the school.</H1>

<H2><STRONG>Can We Brag</STRONG>!</H2>
<UL>
<LI>We will have over 1800 students this year.
<LI>Green is our favorite color.
<LI>We have eleven outstanding Advanced Placement Classes.
</UL>
<BR>
</UL>
</UL>
</UL>
<P>We are very proud of the accomplishments of our faculty and students.  Our 95-96 ACT composite score was 22.2, we had outstanding performances in athletic events, and several staff members were recognized for their work by selection for prestigious summer seminars and cash awards for excellence.
<P>This year our student leaders have the theme "<EM>Right Here, Right Now"</EM>  and they introduced an academic challenge to each grade level to raise the class GPA each term.
<P>The very best part of the Clearfield High tradition is the fact that we care about kids, and we put our actions where our mouth is.  We want to make our school a pleasant place to be where the adults meet students with a positive attitude, a smile, and an expectation of excellence.  This year we will be concentrating on preparing students to enter a career field of choice when they graduate.
<P>Several times a year we award "<EM>CHS Pride Pins"</EM> to students who have done something extra to make themselves or the school better.  Students have earned pins in the past for being a special friend to newcomers, for improved attendance or grades, for returning lost property intact, for cleaning up in the Commons without being asked, for service above that expected for the rest of the studentbody, etc.

<H4>Clearfield High School's Philosophy Statement</H4>
<P>	High school is not an end; it is part of a lifelong process of education.  We believe in preparing students for a 21<SUPER> st</SUPER> century world in which most will face multiple careers.  Proficiency in areas such as critical thinking, group collaboration, interpersonal skills, problem solving, and computer literacy must be acquired in order to succeed in a global society.  Students and teachers are encouraged to utilize community resources in order to enhance the curriculum.
<P>	Administrators and teachers will provide a safe learning environment in which challenging expectations are clearly understood.  Students need to be part of the goal setting/curriculum planning process in order to feel a sense of ownership in their education.  Students with special needs and circumstances particularly need a flexible curriculum with viable options to meet their needs.  
<P>	Teachers, students, and parents are all accountable in the learning process.  We encourage parents to reinforce the value of education,  attendance, punctuality, and a strong work ethic.   Attending school is a privilege; respect for the education process is a necessity.
<P>
<BR><BR>
